<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National Football League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It's no longer the Barry Sanders Show in Detroit. That doesn't  
mean the Lions won't be entertaining this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to see us play a real loose game,'' coach Bobby  
Ross said. ``The game we played the other night is going to be 
pretty indicative of how we play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 35-31 loss at Atlanta, second-year quarterback Charlie  
Batch completed 11 of 16 passes for 146 yards and a touchdown, 
while backup Gus Frerotte was 15-of-21 for 171 yards and a 
touchdown. The Lions rushed for 113 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	That's what Lions fans can expect this season with Sanders  
retired, Ross said. The team will think pass first and try to 
complement it with the run. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to ignore the running game. That's going to be  
big part of it. But we've got some skilled people we have to take 
advantage of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tonight, the Lions play their first game at the Silverdome since  
Sanders' retirement when they play host to the Cincinnati Bengals. 
Ross said he left training camp with a sense of accomplishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've had a very good camp,'' Ross said after  
Thursday's practice. ``We've made a lot of progress as a team. What 
I'm reminding them out there is that we have to carry this over to 
the Pontiac portion of our camp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other preseason games tonight, its Philadelphia at the New  
York Jets, Pittsburgh at Carolina, Buffalo at Washington and 
Tennessee at Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	In other training camp news:  
</P>
<P>
                             *Jaguars    	
</P>
<P>
	Jaguars wide receiver Keenan McCardell suffered a contusion of  
the lower right leg in practice Thursday, leaving his status for 
the team's opener Sept. 12 in doubt. 
</P>
<P>
	McCardell, enjoying one of his best preseason camps of his  
eight-year NFL career, hurt his leg on a running play near the end 
of practice and will be out indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were negative, but Jaguars officials wouldn't speculate  
on how long he might be sidelined. They said he would miss 
Saturday's preseason game with the Giants in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Chargers    	
</P>
<P>
	Chargers quarterback Ryan Leaf had to be forced away from a  
verbal confrontation with a heckling fan on Thursday, the latest 
episode in his short but troubled NFL career. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hours after the tense situation, Leaf said he gets the  
feeling that no one in the organization wants him around after his 
contract becomes voidable following the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it's in the team's best interests to let me go, but I  
don't want that to be the case,'' said Leaf, the second pick 
overall in the 1998 draft who was benched midway through his rocky 
rookie season. ``It doesn't seem like there's anything positive 
around here at all right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jimmy Johnson says he's in no hurry for Dimitrius  
Underwood to join the Dolphins. The rookie defensive end, waived by 
Minnesota after saying he preferred a religious calling to 
football, is willing to meet with Johnson, but also is not rushing 
to get back on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, the 29th overall pick in April's draft, was claimed  
Monday off waivers by the Dolphins. Johnson talked with him for the 
first time Tuesday and predicted the rookie will eventually join 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Titans    	
</P>
<P>
	Quarterback Steve McNair will not start tonight when the Titans  
play an exhibition game at Arizona, according to coach Jeff Fisher. 
</P>
<P>
	McNair has not practiced since Sunday's exhibition loss to  
Kansas City because of back spasms. He is expected back in the 
lineup Aug. 27 when Tennessee plays Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Neil O'Donnell, a 10-year veteran, will start in McNair's  
place. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Colts    	
</P>
<P>
	The Colts closed their training camp with veteran Jay  
Leeuwenberg unhappy over a demotion to a backup role on the 
offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not taking it very well at all,'' Leeuwenberg said. ``I'm  
going to do everything in my power to change the decision between 
now and the start of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leeuwenberg has started 37 consecutive games for the Colts, the  
team's second-longest streak. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	With backup quarterback Kerry Collins nursing a sprained foot,  
Giants third-stringer Mike Cherry might get a chance to play longer 
than expected Saturday night when the Giants host Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	The game plan has Kent Graham starting and playing the first  
half. Cherry is scheduled to play in the second, if Collins can't 
go. Cherry has been the Giants' No. 3 quarterback for the past two 
seasons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
