<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect in Atheist Case Gets 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN (AP) -- A suspect in the disappearance of atheist Madalyn  
Murray O'Hair has been sentenced to eight years in prison on a 
federal weapons charge, days after he got 60 years for stealing 
from her organization. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Sam Sparks cited David Waters' long criminal  
history, which includes a murder conviction in 1965. Waters is a 
three-time felon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is my opinion you should be kept out of society for as long  
as possible,'' Sparks said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters was convicted on Aug. 11 on state charges of stealing  
more than $50,000 from Ms. O'Hair's atheist organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters, a former office manager for Ms. O'Hair, had been on  
probation since 1995. He landed back in court after federal 
authorities found 119 rounds of ammunition in his Austin apartment 
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal authorities suspect Waters, 52, orchestrated the 1995  
disappearance of Ms. O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and adopted 
daughter Robin Murray O'Hair. No charges have been filed in that 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Waters' attorney, Patrick Ganne, accused federal authorities of  
trying to punish Waters for Ms. O'Hair's slaying without having to 
bring him to trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. O'Hair is best known for a case that led to a 1963 U.S.  
Supreme Court decision that, along with a decision the previous 
year, struck down organized prayer in public schools as 
unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ms. O'Hair and her two adult children vanished from San  
Antonio along with $500,000 in gold coins, authorities questioned 
whether they were victims of foul play or had merely run off with 
their organization's money. 
</P>
<P>
	Others suggested that Ms. O'Hair, who was 77 and ailing, had  
gone off to die quietly so Christians wouldn't pray over her. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
