<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Arraigned in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The leader of a Catholic  
protest group and eight followers were arraigned Friday on charges 
connected to their thwarted efforts to prevent Protestants from 
marching past a Catholic neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Divisive Protestant parades, met by organized Catholic  
opposition, have triggered street violence in Northern Ireland for 
the past four summers. 
</P>
<P>
	An independent Parades Commission empowered to weigh both sides'  
rights approved last Saturday's march by about 40 Protestants, 
making any Catholic attempt to block the parade illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belfast Magistrates Court, Judge Harry McKibbin granted bail  
to the nine defendants -- all men ranging in age from 27 to 40 -- 
until their next scheduled court appearance Oct. 15 to face charges 
of obstruction and disorderly conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Only three were identified as residents of Lower Ormeau, the  
south Belfast neighborhood at the center of the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerry Rice, a former Irish Republican Army prisoner, leads the  
militant group that is trying to prevent any of Northern Ireland's 
marching Protestant brotherhoods from passing Lower Ormeau. 
</P>
<P>
	Lines of riot police kept Rice from joining about 200 supporters  
who blocked the road at dawn last Saturday. Many protesters fought 
back with their feet and fists as police dragged them from the 
pavement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of the defendants denies categorically that they  
committed any offense,'' said one of the defendant's attorney, Joe 
McVeigh. ``Further, each formally complains at the brutal manner of 
the police and the way the police forced this parade through the 
Ormeau Road in contravention of their most basic human rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the courthouse, 20 supporters of the IRA-linked Sinn  
Fein party held placards demanding the abolition of the 
predominantly Protestant police force. The IRA killed about 300 
members of the Royal Ulster Constabulary before calling a 1997 
cease-fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Friday, police arrested a 69-year-old woman and her son  
after overnight rioting in Larne, a Protestant town north of 
Belfast. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said someone fired several shotgun blasts at officers as  
they investigated reports that a vigilante mob had beaten up a man 
and set fire to his car. 
</P>
<P>
	Three officers and a firefighter suffered minor wounds in the  
confused melee that followed, police said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
