<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Playing Golf, Raising Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NANTUCKET, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton on Friday promoted  
peace in Northern Ireland and his wife's political prospects in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The president opened with an afternoon of golf on this New  
England holiday island after a hop from his vacation headquarters 
at Martha's Vineyard. His foursome included Sen. John Kerry, 
D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	On tap was a Clinton speech at a fund-raising dinner for the  
American Ireland Fund, an organization whose charitable, 
not-for-profit work includes promoting reconciliation in Northern 
Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also was to headline a private fund-raising reception  
intended to help pay for Hillary Rodham Clinton's political effort. 
It was the first time he has formally pitched in on her behalf. She 
is considering a run in 2000 for the Senate seat held by retiring 
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than the fund-raiser, the first lady had her own Nantucket  
agenda, beginning with a visit to an old whaling church. The visit 
was part of her yearlong effort to promote awareness of American 
historical treasures in need of preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons, along with daughter Chelsea and their chocolate  
Labrador Buddy, arrived Thursday night -- the president's 53rd 
birthday -- for their fifth Martha's Vineyard vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and his family are dividing their vacation this year  
between the island and New York state, a nod to Mrs. Clinton's 
senatorial aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons will spend their first nine days away from the  
White House at the 20-acre Oyster Pond spread of Massachusetts 
developer Richard Friedman. 
</P>
<P>
	The excitement level on Martha's Vineyard is far lower than it  
was during the Clintons' first two vacations, with only a 
sprinkling of shop signs and newspaper advertisements taking 
notice. 
</P>
<P>
	One sign hailed the Clintons as ``our true heroes.'' Another  
store retrieved from storage larger-than-life cardboard cutouts of 
the Clintons. Tourists posing with them were asked to put a dollar 
in a fishbowl ``for charity.'' A newspaper ad ignored the first 
couple but welcomed ``Buddy Clinton'' back to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	On Nantucket, Mrs. Clinton was visiting a church as part of a  
White House program celebrating the millennium effort to encourage 
preservation of the nation's culture and heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 28, the Clintons plan to leave Martha's Vineyard for  
posh East Hampton, N.Y., and a weekend of raising money for the 
Democratic National Committee and Mrs. Clinton's possible campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the Clinton's will settle in for five days in  
Skaneateles, a town in the Finger lakes region southwest of 
Syracuse. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
