<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Faldo Annoyed Over Ryder Cup Status  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- British golfer Nick Faldo complained  
Friday about not being informed about his chances to earn a wild 
card spot on the European Ryder Cup team. 
</P>
<P>
	Faldo is playing at the BMW Open, where a wild scramble to  
qualify for golf's premiere team event is underway before the 
European team is named Sunday when the tournament ends. 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks of the three-time Masters champion, anxious to play  
a record 12th Ryder Cup, were aimed at European captain Mark James. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would have been nice to get a message `nay or  
yeah','' Faldo said. ``You either want me or you don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James had triggered speculation that Faldo, no matter how he  
does at the BMW, would not be chosen by saying he wouldn't select a 
wild-card outside the top 20 on the Ryder Cup points list. 
</P>
<P>
	Faldo, who has slumped the past two years, would only reach No.  
22 even by capturing the BMW Open. After Friday's second round, he 
is seven strokes off the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	James said Friday he makes a point of not talking to golfers  
about their wild-card chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's probably a dozen people in the situation where they  
would like to know,'' James said. ``I could say something and then 
in a day or so, the situation could change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only eight players have wrapped up places on the team that will  
defend its trophy against the United States Sept. 24-26 in 
Brookline, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 24 golfers in the field at the BMW Open are still in  
the running for the two other berths, plus the two wild cards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel lucky I'm not one of them -- there's a lot of tension  
out there,'' said Colin Montgomerie, joint leader at the 
tournament, who long ago secured his place on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Misunderstandings have risen in the past over Ryder Cup wild  
cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweden's Jesper Parnevik left a pregnant wife at home four years  
ago, believing then European captain Bernard Gallacher had promised 
him a wild-card if he played the final qualifying event. 
</P>
<P>
	Parnevik played, but was left off the team.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
