<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise Again / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds resumed their rally Friday, rising for the  
fifth time in six sessions and pushing long-term interest rates 
below 6 percent for the first time in a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 5/8 point, or $6.25  
per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, an influence on the interest 
charged on many loans, fell to 5.98 percent from 6.03 percent on 
Thursday and the lowest finish since July 22. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up 1/16 point higher, while intermediate maturities gained 1/8 
point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market has rallied over the past week amid hopes that a  
likely interest rate boost by the Federal Reserve on Tuesday will 
be the last move by the central bank to contain inflation for the 
near-term. Rising inflation and interest rates make the fixed 
payoff on bonds less appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Thursday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
rose to 4.81 percent as the discount rose to 4.69 percent, up 0.08 
percentage point from late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 5.08 percent while the discount rose to  
4.88 percent. One-year yields rose to 5.14 percent while the 
discount rose to 4.88 percent, up percentage point from a day 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, held steady at 4.93 3/4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell was unchanged at 113 1/32. The average 
yield to maturity was 5.85 percent, down from late Thursday's 5.86 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
