<HEADLINE> Conde Nast May Buy Disney Magazines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Conde Nast, publisher of Vogue, Glamour and  
Mademoiselle, will reportedly add Women's Wear Daily and W to its 
list of major fashion magazines with the purchase of Fairchild 
Publications from Walt Disney Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times, citing unidentified executives, reported  
Friday that Conde Nast has agreed to pay $650 million for 
Fairchild. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Disney declined to comment on the report  
Friday, and Conde Nast executives did not immediately return 
repeated telephone calls from The Associated Press. The agreement 
was to be announced by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney's profits and its stock price have been weak and it has  
been under pressure to sell some of its assets to concentrate on 
its core businesses -- its movie studio and theme parks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times reported last week that Conde Nast and Hearst  
Magazines, publishers of Harper's Bazaar and Town &AMP; Country, were 
involved in a bidding war on Fairchild. 
</P>
<P>
	The jewel of the acquisition is W, a glossy fashion monthly that  
has become a general-interest magazine. W has taken apparel 
advertising from magazines at both Hearst Magazines and Conde Nast. 
</P>
<P>
	Conde Nast, a division of Advance Publications, also publishes  
Allure, GQ, Vanity Fair and The New Yorker, among other magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fairchild group also publishes several trade magazines  
including Supermarket News, Brand Marketing, Footwear News and 
Children's Business. 
</P>
<P>
	With addition of Fairchild, Conde Nast would have a powerful new  
offering for advertisers, who could be given cut rates for buying 
ads as a package in several of its fashion publications. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney acquired Fairchild in 1995 with its purchase of Capital  
Cities ABC, but publishing has never among its top businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago it sold other publishing businesses that were  
acquired with Capital Cities ABC including four newspapers, among 
them Kansas City Star and Fort Worth Star-Telegram. The newspaper 
publisher Knight Ridder bought the papers for $1.65 billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
