<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 16:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Headers May Cause Mental Harm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Adult soccer players appear to suffer a loss of  
some mental abilities over time, possibly from whacking the ball 
with their head, two researchers suggested Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Their study, outlined at the annual meeting of the American  
Psychological Association, bolsters a growing body of research 
pointing to possible mental harm from headers. 
</P>
<P>
	But researchers caution that no study has conclusively  
demonstrated that headers -- as opposed to concussions from 
colliding with other players -- are to blame. It is also unknown if 
the impairment, as measured by psychological tests in such studies, 
translates into any real handicaps in everyday life. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the findings, I think it may be worth pursuing this  
further by asking: Does a lifetime of soccer playing lead to 
problems with social or occupational functioning?'' said David 
Abwender, a neuropsychologist at New York State 
University-Brockport. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Soccer Federation had no immediate reaction to he  
report. 
</P>
<P>
	Abwender and Danielle Symons, a doctoral student in sports  
science at the University of Florida, studied a total of 26 men and 
women who played soccer at the Brockport campus and six current or 
former professionals, aged 30 to 55. A group of swimmers was used 
for comparison. 
</P>
<P>
	On tests of reaction time and ability to deduce unstated rules  
of a card game, soccer players did 12 and 16 percent worse on 
average than swimmers. Soccer players who have competed at 
relatively higher levels -- and presumably did more frequent heading 
-- performed significantly worse on five of 11 tests, even when age 
differences were accounted for. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Webbe, a Florida Institute of Technology psychologist who  
has also studied mental impairment in soccer players, said the 
Brockport study appears to buttress similar findings elsewhere. He 
said simple common sense suggests headers might do harm in the long 
run. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were to go up to someone and say, `Would you bang your  
head against that wall 20 or 30 times a day?' you'd probably say, 
`No,''' said Webbe. 
</P>
<P>
	George S. Baroff, a psychologist who studies brain impairment at  
the University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill, said such cognitive 
loss may stem from a mixture of repeated concussions from 
collisions and banging from headers. 
</P>
<P>
	In interviews, researchers differed in their recommendations for  
parents and soccer leagues because so many questions remain. 
Several encouraged teaching proper heading technique to children 
and using a small ball; some went as far as broaching the idea of 
soft helmets or even banning headers among children younger than 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Haley, the men's soccer coach at Springfield College, said  
he is interested and awaits further research. 
</P>
<P>
	``My greatest concern as a coach is two guys going full steam  
and cracking heads,'' he said. ``It could be pretty traumatic.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 07:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevorkian Associate Prefers Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GALESBURG, Mich. (AP) -- With Jack Kevorkian behind bars,  
authorities believe that his crusade to legalize doctor-assisted 
suicide will be carried on by his associate, Georges Reding. 
</P>
<P>
	Their styles differ -- Kevorkian's flamboyance is in sharp  
contrast to Reding's low-key nature -- but prosecutors say both men 
have equally strong convictions about what they see as the right of 
suffering people to die. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian was jailed in April, sentenced to 10 to 25 years after  
being convicted of murdering a Lou Gehrig's disease patient. By 
then, Reding had taken up what his attorneys called a 
``fellowship'' with Kevorkian, assisting in several deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities now believe Reding may have taken another step in  
picking up where Kevorkian left off. On Thursday, he was charged in 
New Mexico with first-degree murder in the death of a 54-year-old 
woman who had multiple sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities had thought Donna Brennan died of natural causes in  
August 1998. However, an autopsy showed she died of a sedative 
overdose. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding's association with Kevorkian became public in July 1996,  
when Kevorkian attorney Geoffrey Fieger introduced him at a meeting 
of the National Press Club, describing the connection as a 
fellowship. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding, a 74-year-old retired psychiatrist, told the crowd he  
had witnessed five assisted suicides and would continue to help 
Kevorkian judge the mental status of people who seek his help in 
dying. 
</P>
<P>
	``The five people I saw die, their serenity was so beautiful,''  
Reding said. ``It's very beautiful and it's full of sorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reding said he had joined Kevorkian because he was ``embarrassed  
by the cowardice of my profession'' in not supporting patients who 
seek suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	While the beliefs of Kevorkian and Reding may be similar, their  
public personas are very different. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian often taunted, even dared, prosecutors to put him on  
trial. He once dressed up as Thomas Jefferson for a trial. He held 
a news conference to burn an order barring him from assisting in 
suicides. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Schwartz, an attorney who has represented both Kevorkian  
and Reding, said he can't picture a similar performance from 
Reding. He has ``No Trespassing'' signs posted on his farm a short 
drive from Kalamazoo in western Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dr. Reding had I think once or twice talked to the press --  
it's not really something he's interested in,'' Schwartz said. 
``He's not interested in furthering some cause ... just helping 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dairy farmer Frank Drobney has lived a few houses down the road  
from Reding for about nine years. But he knew nothing about 
Reding's beliefs or activities until this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's so isolated, I don't think anyone knows him around  
here,'' Drobney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lin Foote, an assisted-suicide advocate in Kalamazoo County,  
said he's known of Reding for years, finally meeting him this 
spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a lunch of quiche, wine and cheesecake at Reding's home,  
Foote said, a small group talked generally about the future of 
assisted suicide, given Michigan's defeat last year of a 
proposition that would have legalized it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He certainly is ... rather gregarious, very pleasant. His wife  
was very charming,'' Foote said. ``But Dr. Reding is not a showman. 
He's not looking for publicity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, while Reding has not displayed the same penchant for the  
dramatic as Kevorkian, ``nothing would surprise or shock me,'' 
Oakland County Prosecutor David Gorcyca said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding was born in Belgium, his wife, Kathleen Reding, said  
earlier this summer. As a child, he accompanied his father, an 
oncologist, on visits to cancer patients. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, The Oakland Press of Pontiac quoted Reding as saying he  
used to hasten the deaths of patients while working with his 
father. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father was a very distinguished physician in Europe who  
told me `If you do not do this, you have no heart, and if you do it 
and get caught, you are a dumbbell,''' Reding told a free-lance 
writer for the story. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding emigrated to New York in the 1960s and, in 1990, he and  
his wife moved to Galesburg, where he worked as a psychiatrist. 
Mrs. Reding is a Western Michigan University professor who writes 
about death and dying. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwartz said he believes Reding and Kevorkian became friends  
about 1996 through ``Physicians for Mercy,'' a support group of 
doctors backing Kevorkian. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding and Kevorkian were later arrested for allegedly  
participating in three assisted suicides in Oakland County. Charges 
were dropped after the prosecutor decided there was insufficient 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, both were arrested after a body was dropped off at a  
suburban Detroit hospital. Reding was acquitted of charges he 
interfered with police and resisted arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwartz has predicted that any case in New Mexico wouldn't go  
far. 
</P>
<P>
	``The public down there is more conservative than the one  
here,'' he said. ``The people in New Mexico have a much greater 
unhappiness with government interfering in their personal lives.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
