<HEADLINE> Cardinals' Dye To Undergo Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- Arizona Cardinals offensive lineman  
Ernest Dye will undergo surgery Sunday to repair nerves damaged in 
a car accident that nearly severed his arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors feel confident that Dye's arm will remain viable, the  
team said in a statement. The doctors felt it is time to repair the 
nerve damage he sustained in Monday's accident south of Flagstaff, 
where the team holds its training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye has already undergone one operation at Flagstaff Medical  
Center to repair the bone and restore blood flow to his arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other players in the car at the time, Lester Holmes and Carl  
Simpson, received only minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Holmes was driving Dye's car when it veered off  
rain-slicked Interstate 17 and rolled. 
</P>
<P>
	The car was traveling about the posted 75 mph speed limit in a  
heavy rain at the time of the crash, according to DPS reports. 
  	   	
