<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF To Hold Talks in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund announced  
Friday it was dispatching a team to Ecuador for weekend talks aimed 
at assembling an economic support program for the troubled South 
American nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect to continue to work closely with the Ecuadorian  
authorities to finalize a comprehensive program that addresses 
Ecuador's current economic difficulties,'' the IMF said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador has been struggling with what its president, Jamil  
Mahuad, has called the country's ``worst economic crisis in 70 
years.'' El Nino floods have ravaged the country and last year's 
steep decline in the global price of oil, Ecuador's main export, 
has hurt the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF officials have been involved in discussions with Ecuador on  
a proposed $400 million loan to help the country restructure its 
banking system. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuadorian officials said earlier this week the government would  
be able to meet a $94 million interest payment due at the end of 
this month on $6.3 billion in Brady bond debt. But financial 
markets remained jittery, fearing that Ecuador could become the 
first nation to default on Brady bonds since they were introduced 
in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Brady bonds, named after former U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas  
Brady who served in the Reagan and Bush administrations, were 
created to resolve the Latin American debt crisis of the 1980s. The 
bonds are backed by zero-coupon U.S. Treasury securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In its statement Friday, the IMF said that the program it hoped  
to work out with Ecuador ``would complement the authorities' 
efforts to work in a transparent and cooperative manner with 
private creditors on financing arrangements that honor to the 
fullest extent possible Ecuador's commitment to pay its 
creditors.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
