<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Irish to Lay Down Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NANTUCKET, Mass. (AP) -- Saying some Northern Ireland leaders put  
``their whole identity'' into continuing violence, President 
Clinton urged all sides in the conflict Friday to trust each other 
enough to lay aside their arms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have got to help them let go,'' he told a fund-raiser for  
the American Ireland Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said peace will not flourish in Northern Ireland if its  
leaders do not put total faith in the agreements that can create 
it. That can start, he said, by laying down arms without insisting 
that some other faction go first. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of these folks have been doing this for so long that  
their whole identity is caught up in the continuation of the 
conflict,'' Clinton said. ``We have got to target those critical 
decision makers and give them an image of a life they can have that 
is meaningful and rich. ...We have got to help them let go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The event, attended by about 300 people, raised $92,000 for the  
fund, an organization whose charitable, not-for-profit work helps 
promote reconciliation in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will be contributed in first lady Hillary Rodham  
Clinton's name to the ``Vital Voices'' project that brings 
Protestant and Catholic women together, said Sheila O'Malley, 
director of the fund's board. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said she was honored. ``Thanks to the fund, we've  
really been able to make progress by bringing people, particularly 
women, together,'' she said. ``Thank you for believing so strongly 
that peace will last, that it will take firm root.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he wished all of the parties in Northern  
Ireland would move as resolutely toward peace as have the women 
with whom Mrs. Clinton works. ``Sometimes, I think her world will 
have more to do with whether peace will really take hold than the 
one I've moved in,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Clinton headlined a private fund-raising reception  
intended to help pay for Mrs. Clinton's own political efforts. It 
was the first time he has formally pitched in on her behalf. She is 
considering a run in 2000 for the Senate seat held by retiring 
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than the fund-raiser, the first lady had her own Nantucket  
agenda, beginning with a visit to an old whaling church. The visit 
was part of her yearlong effort to promote awareness of American 
historical treasures in need of preservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The president opened his 16-day vacation with an afternoon of  
golf on this New England holiday island after a hop from Martha's 
Vineyard, where the Clintons are staying. His foursome included 
Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons, along with daughter Chelsea and their chocolate  
Labrador Buddy, arrived Thursday night -- the president's 53rd 
birthday -- for their fifth Martha's Vineyard vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and his family are dividing their vacation this year  
between the island and New York state, a nod to Mrs. Clinton's 
senatorial aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons will spend their first nine days away from the  
White House at the 20-acre Oyster Pond spread of Massachusetts 
developer Richard Friedman. 
</P>
<P>
	The excitement level on Martha's Vineyard is far lower than it  
was during the Clintons' first two vacations, with only a 
sprinkling of shop signs and newspaper advertisements taking 
notice. 
</P>
<P>
	One sign hailed the Clintons as ``our true heroes.'' Another  
store retrieved from storage larger-than-life cardboard cutouts of 
the Clintons. Tourists posing with them were asked to put a dollar 
in a fishbowl ``for charity.'' A newspaper ad ignored the first 
couple but welcomed ``Buddy Clinton'' back to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	On Nantucket, Mrs. Clinton was visiting a church as part of a  
White House program celebrating the millennium effort to encourage 
preservation of the nation's culture and heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 28, the Clintons plan to leave Martha's Vineyard for  
posh East Hampton, N.Y., and a weekend of raising money for the 
Democratic National Committee and Mrs. Clinton's possible campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, the Clinton's will settle in for five days in  
Skaneateles, a town in the Finger lakes region southwest of 
Syracuse. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
