<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Squash Players Hurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- A bus taking Egyptian squash players to a  
tourist resort overturned Friday while speeding, killing the driver 
and injuring four players and an official, security officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The players -- the women's team and two men players -- were  
traveling to the city of Madaba on their day off between matches at 
the Arab Games in Amman, said the officials, speaking on condition 
of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The most seriously injured was Nasreen Nasha't, who underwent  
surgery in a hospital near Madaba for a broken thigh bone, said 
Egyptian diplomats who also spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	She was later taken to the King Hussein Medical Hospital in  
Amman where she underwent a second surgery on a broken jaw. Nasha't 
also suffered concussion, Health Minister Ishaq Maraqa told The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her condition is 70 percent stable,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Nasha't finished eighth in the individual championship, which  
ended Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other women -- Iman Amir and Umniya Abdul Qawi -- suffered  
bruises and were taken to the King Hussein Medical Hospital in 
Amman. Amir won the silver medal and Qawi the bronze in the women's 
squash championship on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The gold was won by Egypt's Enjy Kherillah, who not on the bus.  
</P>
<P>
	The bus was carrying about 15 people, all of them Egyptians.  
Only the unidentified driver, who died, was Jordanian, the security 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said one member of the men's team, Mohammed Mithat,  
and a sports administrator, Mohammed Ismail Sharmi, also suffered 
bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the accident occurred on the outskirts of Madaba when  
the speeding bus climbed the sidewalk and overturned. No other 
details were available. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear if the Egyptians intend to go on with the team  
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Madaba, about 18 miles southwest of Amman, is known for its  
Byzantine ruins featuring mosaic floors and picnic spots near a 
couple of waterfalls. It also is the site of Mount Nebo where Moses 
is said to have sighted the promised land. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
