<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talk Showing Slaying Trial Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Defense attorneys are attempting to shift  
the blame in the retrial of a man accused of killing a gay 
acquaintance after they taped an episode of ``The Jenny Jones 
Show'' on secret crushes. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Amedure pursued Jonathan Schmitz to a point that Schmitz  
``lost it,'' defense attorney Jerome Sabbota said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz is accused of second-degree murder in the shotgun  
slaying of Amedure three days after the taping in 1995, in what 
prosecutor Donna Pendergast called ``the epitome of senseless 
violence and destruction, the cold-blooded and unwarranted 
obliteration of human life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sabbota told jurors that Schmitz should be convicted of  
nothing more than manslaughter. ``I won't ask you to set him free. 
I want you to convict him of what he did,'' he said in opening 
statements. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz, then 24, and Amedure, 32, flew to Chicago for the  
taping on March 6, 1995. Amedure, who was gay, revealed his crush 
on Schmitz to the studio audience during the taped segment, which 
never aired. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Schmitz calmly went about his business three  
days after the taping, buying ammunition and a shotgun, then 
shooting a defenseless Amedure twice in his mobile home. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland County sheriff's Deputy Craig Stout, who took Schmitz's  
confession the day of the shooting, testified that Schmitz was 
angry about being humiliated on national television. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wasn't showing any open emotion,'' Stout said. ``He had  
kind of a worried look on his face.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors also heard the 911 call placed by Gary Brady, Amedure's  
roommate, who testified that Schmitz came to the mobile home that 
morning, came in once, then returned to his car to retrieve a 
shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was another knock on the door,'' Brady said. ``He  
(Amedure) said, `Gary, help! He's got a gun, he's going to 
shoot.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz was convicted of second-degree murder in 1996 and  
sentenced to 25 to 50 years in prison. An appeals court later 
overturned the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge in the new trial has ruled that the defense won't be  
allowed to present evidence of Schmitz's history of mental illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Michigan law, diminished mental capacity cannot be used as  
a defense against a charge of second-degree murder. Such a defense 
was allowed in the first trial because the original charge then was 
first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate civil case, a jury in May found the show and its  
corporate owner, Warner Bros., negligent and ordered them to pay 
$25 million in damages to Amedure's relatives. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
