<HEADLINE> Pirates Leave Schourek on Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates didn't make a roster  
move Friday involving left-hander Pete Schourek, who will miss at 
least one start with inflammation in his left shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	There was speculation the Pirates might put Schourek on the  
disabled list, a move they still might make Saturday to clear a 
roster spot for left-handed reliever Jason Christiansen. 
</P>
<P>
	The one problem with that is it might make it more difficult to  
trade Schourek, since he would be on the disabled list Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Players are eligible for the postseason if they are on a team's  
roster Aug. 31. Players on the disabled list are eligible for the 
postseason, but another player on the active roster must be removed 
to make room for the injured player. 
</P>
<P>
	Schourek (3-7, 5.68 ERA) must clear waivers before he can be  
traded and his $2 million guaranteed salary for next season is an 
impedance to any sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Left-hander Jimmy Anderson (1-0, 3.72 ERA in five games) will  
take Schourek's spot in the rotation Saturday and will oppose 
Diamondbacks left-hander Randy Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	That isn't likely to bother Anderson, who opposed Mark McGwire  
in his first career start on August 6, a 5-1 victory in which 
Anderson allowed St. Louis one run and six hits over six innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was 3-0 with a 1.54 ERA in three starts against  
Pittsburgh last season after the Houston Astros barely beat the 
trading deadline by acquiring him from Seattle on July 31. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
