<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Climber Scales Sears Tower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A French daredevil known as ``Spiderman'' for his  
climbing exploits scaled the 1,450-foot Sears Tower this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Alain Robert of Valance, France, was met on the roof of the  
110-story building by officers with handcuffs. Chicago police said 
Robert was charged with two misdemeanor counts, criminal trespass 
and failure to use a safety device while operating an aerial show. 
</P>
<P>
	The climb created a spectacle on Wacker Drive, a busy downtown  
thoroughfare. Traffic backed up and TV station helicopters hovered 
to show the stunt live on morning news programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert, who scales tall buildings for publicity, has climbed  
more than 30 skyscrapers, including the Empire State Building in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sears Tower held the ``world's tallest'' title from 1973  
until 1996, when the 1,483-foot Petronas Twin Towers skyscraper in 
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, was ruled taller. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert's effort marks the second time the building has been  
conquered by daredevils. On Memorial Day 1981, Dan Goodwin, a Las 
Vegas stuntman who went by the name ``Spider Dan,'' climbed the 
building after spending $4,000 on equipment, which included three 
huge glass carrier suction cups. He was charged and convicted of 
disorderly conduct and fined $35. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin's successful attempt to climb the 100-story John Hancock  
Center later that year was nearly thwarted by the Chicago Fire 
Department, which used water hoses to try to wash him off the side 
of the building. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
