<HEADLINE> Colts LB Royal To Be Subpoenaed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The attorney for a French Quarter dancer will  
attempt to have Indianapolis linebacker Andre Royal served with a 
subpoena at Saturday's game between the Colts and New Orleans 
Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal, traded by the Saints to the Colts last year is being sued  
by Rebekah Cehajic, a former dancer at Rick's Caberet. She claims 
Royal hit her, groped her and left without paying for private 
dances on March 18, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal was scheduled to be deposed by Cehajic's lawyer, Stephen  
Rue, on Friday. But Royal's lawyer canceled the deposition because 
he couldn't reach the player to confirm he would show up, Rue said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rue said he rescheduled Royal's deposition for Sept. 13, but  
asked for a civil sheriff's deputy serve the player with a subpoena 
to make sure he appears for questioning. Rue said he wants the 
subpoena served at the night game because that's the only place he 
knows Royal will be in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to play games with Mr. Royal,'' Rue said. ``It's  
unfortunate that I have to go to these measures to have Mr. Royal 
attend a deposition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Royal's lawyer did not return a telephone message seeking  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Police booked Royal with misdemeanor charges of simple battery  
and public drunkenness. He has denied striking the woman but did 
apologize for his behavior. Royal subsequently was cleared of any 
wrongdoing in the criminal case. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after he was released from jail, Royal signed a $3.8  
million offer sheet with the Saints when the Carolina Panthers 
refused to match it. 
</P>
<P>
	Cehajic, who has moved to California, is suing Royal for  
personal injuries. She also wants him to pay her for lost wages and 
for $200 she says he owes for private dances she performed for him. 
  	   	
</P>
