<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Privacy Deadline Missed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the information age, when even the most  
sensitive information zips across continents with lightning speed, 
there's widespread agreement on a need for federal legislation to 
protect the privacy of medical records. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, after years of effort, Congress has failed to pass a law,  
despite giving itself a deadline -- Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate was close until getting hung up over a pair of  
issues: the right to sue over improper use of records and privacy 
of teen-agers who have abortions. Congress will try again after it 
returns to Washington this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've had three years, and lots of bills have been  
introduced, and hearings have been held, but there's been no 
serious movement,'' said Janlori Goldman, a privacy advocate who 
directs the Health Privacy Project at Georgetown University. ``I 
think it's very distressing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So, for the moment, more privacy safeguards are in place for  
Americans' video rentals than for their medical records. There are 
no guarantees that private information won't be sold to 
pharmaceutical companies, passed to employers or whispered about in 
insurance company offices. A hospital clerk could sell your records 
to a malpractice attorney or leak them to a newspaper, and it's not 
against the law -- at least, not federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	A patchwork of state laws protects medical privacy, but the  
protections vary widely. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all-party agreement that federal legislation is needed,  
sharp disagreement persists over details. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, privacy advocates and consumer groups want a tough  
law that makes it difficult for health insurance companies, 
researchers and law enforcers to use records for anything other 
than care and billing. Health care companies and businesses want to 
be sure their operations are not constrained by overly strict 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Among specific questions:  
</P>
<P>
	Should the federal law replace stricter state laws already on  
the books? 
</P>
<P>
	Should police be forced to get a court order or a warrant before  
seizing medical records? 
</P>
<P>
	How much flexibility should go to health insurance companies for  
the use of medical records in their operations? 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., chairman of the Senate Health,  
Education, Labor and Pensions Committee, wrote a bill with 
compromises on each of these. But he couldn't find agreement on the 
right to sue and teen abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawsuits are a perennial issue on Capitol Hill and dominated  
this summer's debate over new rights for patients in managed-care 
health plans. So while the issue is peripheral to privacy, it 
brings out many of the same arguments pitting consumer groups who 
want to ensure victims are compensated against businesses worried 
about costly judgments. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, the issue is whether to limit damages if someone  
improperly releases records and whether to make plaintiffs prove 
that their records were released on purpose. 
</P>
<P>
	Abortion is even further removed from the essence of the privacy  
debate. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is whether the new privacy rights being created  
include teen-agers who get medical care on their own if there is no 
state law specifically requiring parental involvement. Democrats 
led by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., want to be sure that teens are 
allowed to keep their records private, even from their parents. 
That naturally includes controversial medical visits -- including 
those for abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffords was unable to reach compromise on either of these  
issues before Congress left for its August break. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, the House began work on its own legislation.  
But it is just beginning and is even further from consensus than 
the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress had hoped that a looming deadline would force  
interested parties to compromise, but so far it hasn't. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1996 law requires the Department of Health and Human Services  
to write regulations on medical privacy if Congress fails to act by 
Saturday. The department is busy writing the rules, although the 
department, and the interest groups involved, would prefer that 
Congress write a law instead. 
</P>
<P>
	A law would carry more weight than regulations would, and HHS  
rules would cover only electronic records, not paper files. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, HHS plans to issue proposed regulations this fall, in  
time to take effect by February. 
</P>
<P>
	If Congress fails to act in the fall, it could extend the  
deadline. Meanwhile, the threat of HHS rules may encourage 
compromise, said Joe Karpinski, spokesman for the Senate health 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``That environment,'' he said, ``is the best thing that can help  
us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 16:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Strike Votes Slowly Tallied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The word in Detroit was that the United Auto  
Workers wanted to send a message to Ford Motor Co. by having all 
its Ford members cast a strike-authorization vote on the same day 
rather than over several days. 
</P>
<P>
	Only problem is, it didn't work.  
</P>
<P>
	Strike authorization votes are routine every three years before  
national contract negotiations intensify in September. They 
typically are conducted over several days or weeks; members usually 
vote overwhelmingly to grant their representatives the power to 
call a strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ford vote was scheduled for Tuesday, but some of the 43 Ford  
locals across the country set their own voting schedule. The union 
originally had said it would release the results Wednesday, but by 
late Friday the total still was unavailable. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW spokesman Paul Krell said the vote would be released Monday  
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The move to have all Ford voting on Tuesday led to speculation  
that the UAW was trying to signal its displeasure with the No. 2 
automaker over its possible spinoff of the Visteon Automotive 
Systems Corp. parts unit. The union opposes a spinoff of Visteon, 
which has about 28,500 UAW members. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contracts with Ford, General Motors Corp. and the  
Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler AG expire Sept. 14. 
Strike-authorization voting also was still being conducted in the 
normal fashion this week at GM and Chrysler locals. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 14:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Browns Set for Raucous Home Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Orlando Brown will never forget the ugly scene  
in the old Cleveland Stadium on Dec. 17, 1995, the last time the 
Browns played a home game. 
</P>
<P>
	After seeing bleachers and seats ripped up and tossed on the  
field, and batteries and fireworks thrown at the Cincinnati 
Bengals, Brown wanted to visit with some of Cleveland's fans who 
were about to lose their treasured football team to Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went down to the Dawg Pound at the end of the game,''  
Cleveland's mammoth offensive tackle said. ``I had always heard 
them calling my name, but I never had looked in their eyes. They 
were crying, man. That's when I realized how much people love their 
football here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When they take the field Saturday night in the new 72,000-seat  
Cleveland Browns Stadium, the expansion Browns will be welcomed 
like conquering heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	There's sure to be more tears in the stands, but these won't be  
tinged with sadness. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns will be home again.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland has been waiting nearly three years for Saturday  
night's home opener against the Minnesota Vikings. A giant clock in 
the downtown's Tower City Mall has been counting down the days 
until kickoff since the NFL announced in 1996 it would bring the 
Browns back for the 1999 season as an expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns' home opener will culminate a weeklong celebration,  
which included a stadium dedication, a parade through the city 
streets on Friday and a pep rally in Public Square which drew an 
estimated 40,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Kickoff was still 36 hours away, but Cleveland was carrying on  
like it was New Year's Eve. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans chanted, ``Here We Go Brownies, Here We Go, Woof, Woof!''  
as Mayor Michael R. White, instrumental in bringing pro football 
back, thanked Browns fans for their support. 
</P>
<P>
	White recalled that when the city was trying to convince the  
league to return the Browns, he was often asked: ``What does 
Cleveland want?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'We want our team, our name and our colors,'' he said.  
``And guess what Cleveland. We have our team. We have our name. We 
have our colors. We have our legacy, and a brand new stadium to 
boot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not even a planned rally by the Ku Klux Klan, which has stolen  
recent headlines and increased racial tension in the city, has been 
able to dampen Cleveland's enthusiasm about the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Browns take the field in their traditional orange  
helmets Saturday night, fans may be too excited to care much about 
what is happening on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``This town is fired up,'' said cornerback Antonio Langham, who  
like Brown played for the Browns in '95. ``They've waited three 
years for this. Football is back, a new stadium, the whole nine. 
You might see more hitting in the Dawg Pound than you do on the 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland coach Chris Palmer is hoping for a much better effort  
from his team than he got a week ago in Tampa Bay when the Browns 
(1-1) were awful in a 30-3 loss to the Buccaneers. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer will start rookie quarterback Tim Couch, the team's No. 1  
overall pick in the NFL draft against the Vikings (0-1). Couch, so 
impressive in his pro debut against the Dallas Cowboys in the Hall 
of Fame Game, was under siege most of the time last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
