<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Reporter To Give Back IPO Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- ABC's medical correspondent is returning  
more than $50,000 to drkoop.com after violating insider-trading 
rules by selling shares in the healthcare Web site too soon after 
it went public, the company acknowledged. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Nancy Snyderman, who regularly appears on ABC's ``Good  
Morning America,'' serves as a director of the Internet site named 
after its founder, former U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Snyderman's husband bought 1,650 shares of Austin-based  
drkoop.com during a June 8 initial public offering for $9 and sold 
it one month later when prices soared to $41.27 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	That was a violation of Securities and Exchange Commission rules  
barring corporate officers and directors from profiting from a 
stock sale within six months of purchasing shares, said Sue 
Georgen-Saad, chief financial officer of drkoop.com. 
</P>
<P>
	While Dr. Snyderman's husband doesn't work for the company, he  
is held to the same rules, Ms. Georgen-Saad said. SEC rules 
consider husbands and wives to be one person for filing purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Snyderman didn't immediately return calls to The Associated  
Press for comment, but told The Wall Street Journal that she and 
her husband tried to stop the stock sale after realizing it would 
violate federal rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Snyderman said she ``notified the authorities and disclosed  
it immediately in compliance with SEC regulations. Compliance with 
the SEC is of paramount importance to me and will continue to be 
so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an error on the part of the broker and an unauthorized  
sale,'' said Ms. Georgen-Saad, who added that the transactions also 
violated underwriter rules meant to keep company insiders from 
quickly selling their IPO shares. Top officials at the company 
signed agreements with underwriter Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. not to sell 
stock until 180 days after the public offering. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABC correspondent planned to repay the $53,000 her husband  
earned on the sales Friday or early next week, Ms. Georgen-Saad 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She'll be writing a check for the proceeds of the stock,'' she  
said. ``She's very anxious to put this behind her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to her position on the company's board of directors,  
Dr. Snyderman also contributes content to the consumer healthcare 
site, including a column in which she answers general medical 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Snyderman has worked for ABC for 12 years.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our understanding at the moment is that this is an issue of  
personal finance not having really anything to do with us,'' said 
Eileen Murphy, ABC News spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Murphy said ABC News does have policies related to the  
outside interests of correspondents to head off potential conflicts 
of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't discuss the specifics of those policies,'' Ms. Murphy  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Murphy said she couldn't discuss whether Dr. Snyderman  
violated the policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never discuss the application of the policy in any  
individual situation,'' she said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
