<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks, Dollar Rise in Tokyo / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices closed higher Friday following  
news of a planned alliance of three major Japanese banks. The 
dollar rose against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average jumped 218.37 points, or 1.22  
percent, to close at 18,098.11. On Thursday, the average dropped 
12.52 points, or 0.07 percent, to finish at 17,879.74. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was traded at 111.74 at mid-afternoon, up 0.11 yen  
from its level late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late level 
of 111.40 overnight in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, traders reacted positively after financial  
giants Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and 
Fuji Bank Ltd. said they plan an alliance that would create the 
world's largest banking group with assets of well over dlrs 1 
trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise in Tokyo came after a fall on Wall Street overnight,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average slipped 27.54 points, or 
0.25 percent, to 10,963.84. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 23.59 points, or 1.60 percent, to 1,498.94. The 
TOPIX dropped 3.08 points, or 0.21 percent, to 1,475.35 the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign exchange, investors were cautious about selling  
dollars amid fears the Bank of Japan might step in to prop up the 
greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese finance officials have long maintained that a sudden  
surge in the yen could hurt Japan's giant exporters and have 
intervened in markets to keep the yen low and those companies 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen can hurt exporters by forcing them to raise prices  
abroad or accept less in terms of yen from their overseas 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell sharply against both the yen and the euro  
overnight after a surprise jump in the U.S. trade deficit sparked 
selling of dollars. Against the Japanese currency, the greenback 
dropped as low as 110.68 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 119.08 yen in  
mid-afternoon trading, up from its level of 116.98 yen late 
Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.8500 percent from Thursday's close of 1.9200 
percent, driving its price up to 99.57 yen from 98.98 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
