<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Release Pitcher Ricky Bones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Ricky Bones, who failed to win a game with  
Baltimore and appeared to be losing the zip on his fastball, was 
released by the Orioles on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was made after the Orioles' game against the Chicago  
White Sox was postponed by rain. He was replaced on the 25-man 
roster by Doug Linton, who will start the opener of Saturday's 
day-night doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
	Linton (0-1) will face John Snyder (9-8) in the 1:05 p.m. EDT  
opener. Sidney Ponson (11-8), who was slated to pitch Friday, will 
oppose Mike Sirotka (8-10) in the second game, scheduled for 7:05 
p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Bones, 30, played the past two seasons with Kansas City before  
signing with Baltimore as a free agent in December. He had a 1.62 
ERA through April, but he was placed on the disabled list on July 2 
with right arm fatigue and never again showed the form he displayed 
early in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a quality kid, a great worker,'' Orioles manager Ray  
Miller said. ``But statistically, he wasn't getting it done. The 
first month he looked outstanding, then his velocity went down and 
so did his effectiveness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bones was given two starts this month after Baltimore traded  
Juan Guzman to Cincinnati, but Bones lost at Oakland on Aug. 3 and 
was ineffective against Detroit on Aug. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 0-3 with 5.98 ERA and opponents were hitting .322 against  
him. Miller said his fastball was clocked at under 90 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised. No one likes to be in this position, but  
somebody has to go,'' Bones said. ``They were supposed to make a 
move, and they were looking around, and it was me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said the Orioles placed on waivers but he wasn't claimed.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question I can go somewhere else and pitch. I know  
I'm healthy; even last night I pitched and got two of three guys 
out,'' Bones said. ``I'll stick around here a couple days, and see 
Baltimore from a different sight. Then in a couple days I'll go 
home and see my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friday night's game was called off after a delay of nearly two  
hours. Because Ponson warmed up to pitch, Miller decided to use him 
the second game of the day-night doubleheader. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder was slated to pitch Friday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``Playing two like this doesn't matter to me,'' White Sox  
manager Jerry Manuel said. ``In minor league ball I've been through 
a few of them (day-nighters). But never here (majors) that I can 
remember. This will be the first one of them for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shouldn't matter to us. It doesn't make any difference,''  
Manuel said. ``We've got a bunch of young kids, so we should be 
OK.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
