<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drugs Cast Pall Over Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Marion Jones and Maurice Greene are ready  
to run at the World Championships, where drug cases and positive 
tests continue to tarnish the landscape. 
</P>
<P>
	The championships begin Saturday at 60,000-seat Olympic Stadium,  
with Jones and Greene, the world's No. 1 sprinters, competing in 
the first two rounds of the 100 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Interfering with the excitement of their appearances is the  
grave concern over the sudden rash of doping cases, some involving 
the sport's biggest stars -- Merlene Ottey, Javier Sotomayor, 
Linford Christie and Dennis Mitchell. The latest case, of 200-meter 
runner Troy Douglas of the Netherlands, was disclosed Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the last couple of weeks, our beautiful and lovely sport  
has been marred by all of this,'' said Jones, who will be seeking 
an unprecedented four gold medals at the championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, aiming for three golds, also has been dismayed by the  
crushing drug revelations and thinks blood testing might by the 
solution to slow the onslaught. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait until that time comes,'' he said. ``The number of  
positive tests have been very bad for our sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's spectators, meanwhile, will be anxiously awaiting the  
time when the two mercurial sprinters appear on the track, taking 
the focus from the off-track activities and centering it on the 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that our wonderful performances will overshadow what  
has happened,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones and Greene already have turned in sensational performances  
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, the defending champion in the 100, has the season's two  
fastest times, running 10.80 seconds twice. She owns the five 
fastest times and eight of the best nine in the 200, topped by 
21.81. Jones also has run the 400 once, in a respectable 50.79, and 
has long-jumped 23 feet, fourth-best in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the four events in which she will compete -- the 100, 200,  
long jump and a relay -- the long jump concerns her most. 
</P>
<P>
	``Earlier this season I was having a little difficulty with my  
rhythm on the runway,'' she said. ``Since my last long jump 
competition ... we (Jones and coach Trevor Graham) ... have made 
our necessary corrections and I feel quite confident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' long jump hopes were boosted Friday when 1983 and 1993  
champion Heike Drechsler of Germany withdrew with a calf injury. 
Drechsler was the only athlete to beat Jones in any event last 
year, and also outjumped her last month in Linz, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	While Jones is a prohibitive favorite in both sprints, Greene,  
also running both dashes and a relay, is favored only to defend his 
title in the 100. He shattered the world record in June with a 
stunning time of 9.79, and he has run 9.85, the second-best time in 
the world. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 200, his best time of 19.92 is tied for fourth fastest.  
However, of the three runners ahead of him -- Ato Boldon of Trinidad 
and Tobago, Frankie Fredericks of Namibia and John Capel of the 
United States -- only Fredericks is competing at the championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 200 is a challenge for Maurice,'' coach John Smith said.  
``He needs to step up in this area to become that sprinter he's 
always wanted to be ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	The men's and women's 100 semifinals and final will be Sunday.  
Jones also will have long jump qualifying Saturday, with the final 
on Monday. The relays are on the final day of the championships, 
Aug. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	American John Godina, another athlete attempting to win multiple  
medals, begins competition Saturday in the shot put final. On 
Sunday, he will have discus qualifying, with the final Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Godina is the two-time defending champion in the shot put and  
leads the world in that event this year with a career-best 72 feet, 
3 inches. He has yet to medal in the discus, but ranks second in 
the world this year at 226-6. 
</P>
<P>
	Godina, who has thrown the discus since fifth grade and the shot  
put since 10th grade, has no difficulty adjusting to the two 
implements. 
</P>
<P>
	``Adjusting is nothing,'' he said. ``All of a sudden you take a  
couple of throws with one and you're back into it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun to be able to do both -- to impress people. That's why  
I stick with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's program also includes finals in the women's pole  
vault and men's 20-kilometer race walk. 
</P>
<P>
	The pole vault never has been contested at the outdoor  
championships, but has been held twice at the indoor meet. 
</P>
<P>
	The favorites include 1997 indoor champion Stacy Dragila of the  
United States, world record-holder Emma George of Australia, 1999 
indoor winner Nastia Ryshich of Germany, and Anzhela Balakhonova of 
Ukraine. 
</P>
<P>
	The top contenders in the walk are world record-holder Julio  
Martinez of Guatemala and No. 2 all-time Alejandro Lopez of Mexico. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
