<DOCNO> APW19990820.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Currency Plunges Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The Brazilian real skidded to a  
five-month low on Friday, pushed by uncertainty about 
deficit-cutting reforms and flagging investor confidence in South 
American markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's currency was trading at 1.995 to the dollar at midday --  
down 6 percent from a week ago -- before strengthening late in the 
day to 1.913. 
</P>
<P>
	For Brazilians, the scramble to buy dollars was uncomfortably  
reminiscent of the panic that followed the 1997 crisis in southeast 
Asia and last year's turmoil in Russia. The shock waves quickly 
reached Brazil, which was forced to devalue its currency in January 
and plunged into a recession from which it just now is emerging. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were quick to argue the situation now is very  
different. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Bank President Arminio Fraga said markets had the wrong  
impression that the government was weakening in its resolve to 
enact deficit-cutting reforms, a condition of the International 
Monetary Fund for a $41.5 billion loan approved last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil also is a victim of its neighbors' problems -- elections  
in Argentina, a debt crisis in Ecuador, political unrest in 
Venezuela and Colombia. In New York, Moody's Investors Service 
indicated it may downgrade its ratings for the long-term debt of 
twelve Argentine banks, hurting the value of Brazilian debt bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's an unfavorable wind from abroad,'' said Fraga. ``It's  
not a storm, but it's not a generous climate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The danger is that pessimistic expectations often become  
self-fulfilling. Banks and companies buy dollars as a hedge against 
an uncertain future, which weakens the real and raises the demand 
for dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the Central Bank tried to increase the inflow  
of dollars by eliminating a 0.5 percent tax on some foreign 
investments. In a bid to restore confidence, the government also 
announced it would pass up a $4.35 billion parcel of the IMF loan, 
on grounds it wasn't needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any moment now, (the market) will realize the economy is  
growing more than expected, inflation is low, and we are meeting 
all our fiscal targets,'' said Daniel Gleizer, the Central Bank's 
director of international affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gleizer has a point. The economy has grown for the past two  
quarters and inflation will be close to 8 percent this year, far 
better than expected. Foreign direct investment is strong and 
should easily cover a $23 billion deficit in the balance of 
payments this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Projections for next year are not so rosy, however. Brazil has  
promised a sharp cut in its budget deficit, but Congress is 
dragging its feet on reform bills to reduce government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is nervous just now,'' Amalia Estensorro, Latin  
American economist at BBV Latinvest in London, said this week. 
``International currencies are a bit wobbly in general, but 
particular to Brazil is the indefinition of the fiscal situation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
