<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Illinois Excluded in Organ Sharing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Patients in grave need of new livers have been  
put at risk by a new Midwestern organ-sharing network that excludes 
Illinois, some organ transplant officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is I think somebody's going to die,'' said Dr.  
Michael Abecassis, director of liver transplants at Northwestern 
Memorial Hospital in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a four-state agreement launched this week, donor  
livers are offered to patients with the most urgent need regardless 
of where they reside in Wisconsin, Minnesota, North Dakota and 
South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	Under regions established by the United Network of Organ  
Sharing, the agency that runs the nation's transplant system, 
Illinois also should be included in the region's organ-sharing. 
</P>
<P>
	The four states have not yet submitted their proposal to UNOS,  
but are moving forward anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin officials argued that Illinois was unfairly benefiting  
from their state's strong organ-donor program because under the 
UNOS formula, donor livers are too often shipped to six 
Chicago-area hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wisconsin officials also said the new network was based on  
recommendations from the Institute of Medicine, part of the 
National Academy of Sciences, that suggest smaller organ-sharing 
regions. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is meant to take care of these patients in this  
population base that was recommended by the IOM,'' said Dr. Anthony 
D'Alessandro, the director of multi-organ transplantation at the 
University of Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Illinois could have been included in the new network but  
wouldn't agree to a ``payback'' provision requiring it to provide 
livers to other states in exchange for ones it received, Wisconsin 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really boggles my mind how they can do this,'' Abecassis  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Brems, the director of transplants at Loyola University  
Medical Center, said that if Illinois is receiving more livers for 
seriously ill patients it's because the state contains more than 
half of the region's population. Illinois also has six of the 10 
transplant centers in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Aug. 1, 1,227 patients were awaiting liver transplants in  
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	``There shouldn't be a patient in Chicago dying of liver failure  
when someone who is relatively well in Milwaukee is receiving a 
liver,'' Brems said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bosch, a spokesman for the Regional Organ Bank of  
Illinois, believes Wisconsin has the best interests of patients in 
mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``It all comes back to the fact that we're in the same  
predicament,'' he said. ``If we had enough organs to go around we 
wouldn't have to allocate.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
