<DOCNO> APW19990820.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 07:21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones, Greene Aim for Seven Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Maurice Greene is the world's fastest man.  
Marion Jones is the world's fastest woman. Together, they could run 
away with seven gold medals in the World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The American sprinters will share the spotlight when the sport's  
showcase event opens Saturday, with both determined to establish 
their place in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is bidding to become the first athlete, man or woman, to  
win four gold medals in the championships. She's competing in the 
100 meters, 200, long jump and one of the relays. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will be disappointed if I come back with anything less than  
four,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene is chasing gold in three events: the 100, 200 and 400  
relay. He could become the first man to complete a 100-200 double 
in the worlds, and the first in any major championship since Carl 
Lewis in the 1984 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just eager to get on the track and run,'' Greene said.  
``They say the track is very fast. I just want to see how fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is a big favorite in the 100 and 200, where she is  
unbeaten since 1997 and owns the world-best times this season 
(10.80 seconds and 21.81). 
</P>
<P>
	Her biggest challenge will be in the long jump, where she lost  
last month in Linz, Austria, to Germany's Heike Drechsler, the 
former Olympic and world champion. 
</P>
<P>
	After losing to Drechsler -- 22 feet, 5 inches to 22-3 -- Jones  
returned home to coordinate her blistering speed down the runway 
with her shaky technique. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows earlier in the season I was having a little  
bit of trouble with my rhythm on the long jump,'' she said. ``Since 
my last long jump in Linz, we've gone back to the drawing board and 
made our necessary corrections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some answers will roll in almost instantly. Jones begins her  
long-jump qualifying at 10:30 a.m. Saturday, with the 100 prelims 
starting 15 minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go out there and hopefully on my first jump,  
qualify, and be able to concentrate on the 100 after that,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said she hasn't decided yet whether she will run in the  
400 or 1,600 relay. The decision will rest with her coach, Trevor 
Graham. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trevor has told me that after my three individual events are  
done, hopefully I'm happy with three wins there, he's going to look 
into my eyes and tell if I'm ready to run a 400 meters or not,'' 
she said. ``If he doesn't ... then I'm going to run the 4 by 100.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seville is a dress rehearsal for next year's Sydney Olympics,  
where Jones plans to run in both relays in a bid for a record five 
gold medals. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene, meanwhile, is looking to bolster his reputation as one  
of the most prolific sprinters in history. 
</P>
<P>
	He has broken the 10-second barrier -- the standard for  
excellence in the 100 -- 22 times, including six times this year 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene entered sprinting lore on June 6 in Athens, Greece, when  
he set the 100 world record of 9.79 seconds, shattering Donovan 
Bailey's mark (9.84 seconds in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics) by an 
astounding five-hundredths of a seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	While Greene looks untouchable in the 100, a gold medal in the  
200 is no certainty. Greene is still learning the longer sprint, 
and his best time this year (19.92) is behind the 19.86 run by 
Namibia's Frankie Fredericks and Trinidad's Ato Boldon and the 
19.87 by John Capel. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 200 is a challenge for Maurice,'' said Greene's coach,  
John Smith. ``It's an event he's not run a great deal of, but he's 
real good at it. So he needs to step up in this area to become that 
sprinter he's always wanted to be -- not only stop at the short 
races, but be able to go up to the furlong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With training partner Boldon out of the championships with an  
injury, Fredericks shapes up as Greene's biggest rival in the 200. 
In the 100, Canada's Bruny Surin, Barbados's Obadele Thompson and 
Fredericks are the main challengers. 
</P>
<P>
	There's been speculation that, without Boldon and Bailey to push  
him in Seville, Greene will be less motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not worried about that,'' Smith said. ``That's why I'm  
there. We'll find a reason to run fast. The mere fact that Ato is 
not there means that Maurice will be running with Ato in his spirit 
and his heart.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
