<HEADLINE> Exabyte Eliminating 200 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Computer equipment maker Exabyte Corp. is  
cutting 200 jobs as part of a reorganization aimed at slashing 
costs by as much as $12 million. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 of the layoffs occurred Thursday. Another 40  
positions, including 20 vacancies, will be phased out by the end of 
the month. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining jobs will be eliminated before the end of the  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Exabyte officials announced earlier this month that they would  
make significant cuts to streamline operations. Before the 
reductions, the company employed 1,275 people, including 900 in 
Boulder. 
</P>
<P>
	The reductions will affect most of Exabyte's operations,  
including sales, marketing, manufacturing, administration, quality 
control and engineering. 
</P>
<P>
	Exabyte was founded in the mid-1980s by former Storage  
Technology Corp. executives. It makes tape drives and tape 
libraries for computer data storage. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has struggled the past year, its quarterly revenues  
falling from $63.2 million in the fourth quarter of last year to 
$48.5 million last quarter. Its losses the past three quarters 
totaled $25.7 million. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
