<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Earthquake Strikes Montana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUTTE, Mont. (AP) -- A moderate earthquake struck a sparsely  
populated area of Montana and Idaho today, but there were no 
immediate reports of injuries or significant damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake with a magnitude of 5.3 happened shortly before 8 a.m.  
near Lima in the extreme southwest corner of Montana, near the 
Idaho line, according to the earthquake studies office at the 
Montana Bureau of Mines and Geology in Butte. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shook the floor of the building,'' said Kathy Cherry, who  
works at Yesterday's Cafe in Dell. ``It kind of startled us.'' 
However, she said there was no damage. 
</P>
<P>
	There also was no report of damage at Yellowstone National Park.  
The epicenter is roughly 70 miles west of the park's western edge. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Lay of the state Disaster and Emergency Services office  
said the quake was felt as far away as Billings, roughly 200 miles 
to the east. 
</P>
<P>
	A quake of magnitude 5.0 can cause considerable damage in  
populated areas, though modern building codes can substantially 
reduce the potential for damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty years ago this week, a magnitude 7.5 quake shook the  
Hebgen Lake area east of today's temblor, causing a landslide that 
buried a campground. Twenty-eight people were killed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
