<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 22:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bulger Added To FBI's Fugitive List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The FBI has granted reputed mobster James J.  
``Whitey'' Bulger membership in a very exclusive club -- the 
agency's 10 Most Wanted Fugitives list. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a public relations ploy designed to get people around the  
country looking for the Boston man who has been on the run since 
1995. Even comic strip gumshoe Dick Tracy will be on the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``What this will do is guarantee that he's on the top list of  
every law enforcement official,'' U.S. Attorney Donald K. Stern 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulger is accused of extortion and racketeering. The FBI said he  
siphoned money from illegal gambling, loan sharking and drug 
operations in the Boston area. The agency has posted a $250,000 
reward for information leading to his arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI has said Bulger ran his criminal organization for 30  
years from a Boston neighborhood, but the agency has also conceded 
that it had an improperly cozy relationship with him in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI agent is alleged to have given Bulger and Stephen ``the  
Rifleman'' Flemmi permission to commit crimes in exchange for 
information about other criminals. Lawyers for Flemmi and others 
awaiting trial have asked a federal judge to dismiss the charges 
because they believe the FBI overstepped its legal authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, the agency now places Bulger in the same league as  
Osama bin Laden, the Saudi dissident accused of masterminding the 
bombing of U.S. embassies last year in Africa, and bombing suspect 
Eric Robert Rudolph. 
</P>
<P>
	``James J. Bulger should be considered armed and extremely  
dangerous,'' said Barry Mawn, special agent in charge of the FBI's 
Boston office. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulger, 69, is believed to be traveling with his girlfriend,  
Catherine Greig, 48, who is accused of harboring a fugitive. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulger disappeared just before his indictment on racketeering  
charges in January 1995. Flemmi has testified that Bulger fled 
after being told by an FBI agent that they were about to be 
arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI also announced this week that fugitives on the 10 Most  
Wanted list would be profiled in Sunday editions of the ``Dick 
Tracy'' comic strip. The strip will have an artist's rendering of 
each fugitive and a short outline of why he is wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said Bulger is the 458th person to be placed on the  
list, which was established in 1950. Of those, 429 have been 
captured or located. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulger fills a spot vacated by Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, who  
turned himself in last month and now faces charges he killed seven 
people as he traveled the nation's railways. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saints Extend GM's Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The New Orleans Saints believe they are on  
the eve of greatness, and on Friday, owner Tom Benson took steps to 
reward Bill Kuharich, the man he holds responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	The Saints signed Kuharich, who has the titles of president,  
general manager and chief operating officer, to a new five-year 
contract that will run through Jan. 31, 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am proud to sign Bill to this new contract because it gives  
this team stability across the board at the very top of the 
organization,'' said owner Tom Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuharich, 46, was hired by Jim Finks in 1986 and was promoted to  
his present role in 1997. At that time, the team was coming off a 
3-13 season in which coach Jim Mora had quit halfway through the 
season. Kuharich's first major move was hiring coach Mike Ditka. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Kuharich, the Saints have also locked up Pro Bowl tackle  
William Roaf, defensive end Joe Johnson, linebacker Mark Fields, 
defensive tackle La'Roi Glover and safety Sammy Knight with 
long-term contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Bill has done during his tenure is to try and provide  
stability to the organization by signing head coach Mike Ditka to a 
long-term contract, and by signing our top core players to 
long-term contracts,'' Benson said. ``I feel that is vital in 
today's NFL, as does Bill. By placing him under contract until 
2004, we're ensuring the stability of this franchise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Benson, who extended Ditka's contract last year, locking him in  
through the 2002 season, negotiated the new deal with Kuharich 
before the Saints left training camp in La Crosse, Wis., on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new terms, Kuharich's old contract, which was to  
expire in 2002, was replaced by the new deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look forward to continuing with the positive work we've done  
both on and off the field,'' Kuharich said. ``This will be a great 
opportunity for the Saints organization to see our goal of becoming 
the best franchise in the National Football League come to 
fruition. We aren't satisfied with anything less than the Super 
Bowl and we are continuing to work in that direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kuharich served as the team's director of player personnel from  
1986-93 under Finks. In 1994, when Finks died of lung cancer, 
Kuharich was promoted to vice president of football operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Before joining the Saints, Kuharich served as assistant general  
manager and director of player personnel for the Philadelphia Stars 
of the USFL. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
