<HEADLINE> Gerald Ford Honored in Hometown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Former President Ford was honored in  
his hometown with a revival-flavored tribute marking the 25th 
anniversary of the beginning of his presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Against the backdrop of a gospel choir, the Rev. Billy Graham  
told a cheering crowd of more than 2,000 on Thursday that Ford's 
courage helped a nation recover from the devastation and 
humiliation after President Nixon's resignation on Aug. 9, 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham visited Ford in the White House and offered his support  
when the president issued his pardon of Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	``President Ford came along and healed us under God I believe,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, 85, thanked the crowd and hugged Graham. His eyes, he  
said, are turned on the future, which he believes hold great 
promise -- if America stays spiritually strong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cling, I say, to your faith,'' Ford said. ``We are all God's  
children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tribute was part of a series of lectures in Ford's hometown  
in his honor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
