<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scraps Plane Aid for Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon today scrapped plans to send four  
Air Force transport planes to Turkey to help fight fires triggered 
by the earthquake. But a small U.S. Navy medical team from Naples, 
Italy, arrived on the scene with 27,000 pounds of medical gear and 
surgical supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday the Pentagon announced it was sending three Air  
National Guard C-130 planes equipped to fight fires, plus a C-17 
with fire-suppression materials and personnel. Spokesman Kenneth 
Bacon said Turkish officials had told Defense Secretary William 
Cohen on Wednesday that their most immediate need was firefighting 
aid, but today spokesman Bryan Whitman said the planes were no 
longer needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Navy medical team is composed of 22 people, including  
doctors and nurses from Naples. They brought tents, water and 
prepackaged meals plus surgical supplies, anesthesia machines and 
intravenous fluids. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, three Navy ships led by the USS Kearsarge continued  
en route to Turkey to stand by in case additional medical 
assistance is requested by the Turkish government. The ships, with 
2,100 Marines and 1,000 sailors aboard, are due off the coast of 
Istanbul on Saturday, Whitman said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The ships can provide six operating rooms and five X-ray rooms,  
eight doctors, three dental officers and 88 medical corpsmen. Their 
22 helicopters can provide medical evacuations from the damaged 
areas if Turkey requests it. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the U.S. European Command announced it will send a  
humanitarian assistance survey team of about 20 people Saturday 
from Incirlik Air Base, Turkey, to assess ways the U.S. military 
might provide more help. The team will include troops trained in 
logistics, construction and radio communications. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States also plans to bring in a water-purification  
unit that can handle emergency water needs for about 10,000 people, 
White House National Security Council spokesman David Leavy said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 70 search-and-rescue experts from Fairfax, Va., and  
Miami are stationed in the hard-hit city of Izmit, Leavy said. The 
search teams began round-the-clock shifts early Thursday, Leavy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the State Department, spokesman James P. Rubin said U.S.  
searchers rescued two children and an adult Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavy said there is no estimate yet of the cost of U.S. relief  
efforts in Turkey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
