<HEADLINE> Flyers Sign 1998 Draft Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Flyers signed center Simon  
Gagne, their 1998 first-round draft pick, to a three-year contract 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract had not yet been filed with the players' union  
Friday afternoon, but is believed to be worth about $975,000. 
</P>
<P>
	With Quebec of the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League last  
season, Gagne tied for the team-high with 50 goals and led the 
squad with 70 assists in 61 games. With the silver-medal winning 
Canadian National Team in the 1999 World Junior Championships, 
Gagne scored a tournament-high seven goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Flyers general manager Bob Clarke said the 19-year-old Gagne  
would get ``every opportunity to display his skills during training 
camp,'' but would most likely start the 1999 season back at Quebec. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has the potential to play in the NHL in the very near  
future,'' Clarke said. ``He has a chance of making our club this 
season, but we need to be certain that he would get enough ice time 
to further his development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gagne has scored 89 goals and 131 assists over three seasons in  
the Quebec league. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke also said the team hopes to re-sign two free agents, left  
wing Valeri Zelepukin and center Daymond Langkow, next week, but 
has not spoken to the agent for another unsigned player, left wing 
Craig Berube. 
  	   	
</P>
