<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 17:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rockies GM Bob Gebhard Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Rockies general manager Bob Gebhard  
resigned Friday as the team struggled through the final weeks of 
its second straight losing season. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockies owner Jerry McMorris announced Gebhard's resignation at  
Coors Field while the Rockies played the Cubs in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was Geb's decision,'' McMorris said.  
</P>
<P>
	He fended off questions about recent reports that he planned to  
fire Gebhard at the end of the season, saying, ``That would be pure 
speculation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McMorris said Gebhard didn't tell him whether speculation about  
his job contributed to his decision to resign, but added it could 
have been a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rumors have been more intensive as time has gone by and it's  
clearly taken its toll on Geb,'' McMorris said. ``It was difficult 
for everybody here. There are a lot of red eyes in the organization 
today. He's our friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gebhard did not attend the news conference and wasn't available  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gebhard's responsibilities are being taken over by Pat  
Daugherty, vice president for scouting; Gary Hughes, vice president 
for player personnel; and Tony Siegal, director for baseball 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	McMorris said Hughes is a candidate to become GM.  
</P>
<P>
	``But we're going to do a thorough search,'' the owner said.  
``There are no external names on the list yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gebhard's job has been in jeopardy for a year. Colorado, which  
made the playoffs in 1995 in its third season, finished 77-85 last 
year. The Rockies kept Gebhard but fired manager Don Baylor and 
replaced him with Jim Leyland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all feel responsible and I say WE. We feel like we're part  
of the reason this happened,'' Leyland said. ``He's a friend. He 
brought me here with high hopes. I talked to him before the game 
and he's going to be OK. He bled Rocky purple-and-black like 
nobody. We let him down. I can only speak for myself but if myself, 
my staff and the players had lived up to Geb's expectations, this 
wouldn't have happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Walker learned of Gebhard's resignation during the fifth  
inning of an 11-3 win at Wrigley Field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most of the guys in here pretty much loved him. He  
made some people unhappy but he had a job to do,'' Walker said. 
``GMs aren't supposed to make people happy. They've got a job to do 
and they've got to do what's best for the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite unfortunately, the last couple years we've made Don  
Baylor look bad and we've made Bob Gebhard look really bad. That's 
not their fault. That's our fault. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado is last in the NL West at 55-69.  
</P>
<P>
	Gebhard, 56, was hired in the fall of 1991, about 18 months  
before the Rockies started play. In the November 1992 expansion 
draft, he selected Vinny Castilla, Curtis Leskanic and Kevin Ritz. 
He also traded for Dante Bichette and signed Andres Galarraga. 
</P>
<P>
	Gebhard has made other shrewd deals, notably signing free agent  
Larry Walker before the 1995 season. But he has been criticized for 
other moves, such as the acquisitions of Greg Harris, Darryl Kyle, 
Bill Swift and Bret Saberhagen and the departures of Galarraga, 
Walt Weiss, Andy Ashby, Brad Ausmus, Joe Girardi and Armando 
Reynoso. 
</P>
<P>
	Since making the playoffs, the Rockies have disappointed fans.  
They finished 83-79 in each of the 1996 and 1997 season before 
dropping below .500 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	While Colorado has the top batting average in the National  
League at .286, it has the worst ERA in the majors at 5.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Gebhard began his professional baseball career as a pitcher,  
playing 11 years that including stints with the Minnesota Twins and 
the Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a player/coach for Montreal from 1974-75, was promoted to  
minor league field director in 1976 and later to pitching coach. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the Minnesota Twins in 1987 as director of player  
personnel, and became a team vice president the following year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
