<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Friday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
 *Dun &AMP; Bradstreet Corp., down 5 3/16 at 25 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	The Murray Hill, N.J.-based company does not expect its  
third-quarter and year-end earnings to meet Wall Street analysts' 
estimates. The earnings shortfall is due to weakness at its Dun &AMP; 
Bradstreet Operating Company division, which provides commercial 
credit and marketing and purchasing information. Dun &AMP; Bradstreet 
also operates the debt-rating firm Moody's Investors Service. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sprint Corp., down 4 1/16 at 45    	
</P>
<P>
	Lehman Brothers downgraded the telecommunications company's  
stock. The investment firm said the Sprint trails its long-distance 
rivals MCI Worldcom and AT&AMP;T in scale, network reach and growth of 
assets. 

</P>
<P>
 *Dillard's Inc., down 5 3/4 at 23 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The Little Rock, Ark.-based department store chain said poor  
performance at stores acquired last year resulted in an unexpected 
25 percent drop in its second-quarter earnings. The company said 
the weakness could extend into the third quarter. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
 *Books-A-Million Inc., up 3/16 at 10 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The Birmingham, Ala.-based book retailers reported  
second-quarter earnings that topped Wall Street analysts' 
expectations. 

</P>
<P>
 *Ditech Communications Corp., up 22 7/8 at 56 3/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The Mountain View, Calif.-based company's first-quarter results  
beat Wall Street analysts' estimates. The manufacturer of 
communications equipment expects revenue to increase in the next 
two or three quarters to anywhere between $12 and $15 million. 

</P>
<P>
 *American Access Technologies Inc., up 1 at 8 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	The Lake Mary, Fla.-based telecommunications company purchased  
Genco Inc., a manufacturer of generator enclosures, for $550,000 in 
American Access stock valued at $20 per share. American said it 
estimates sales from the new Genco unit will reach about $4 million 
during the next 18 months. 

</P>
<P>
 *Amazon.com, up 7 5/16 at 113 7/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle-based Internet retailer launched a new service  
called Purchase Circles that helps gift buyers find its most 
popular products in 3,000 different cities, universities and 
workplaces. 





  	   	
