<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. Teens Protest Hacky Sack Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA FE (AP) -- Four people who were playing Hacky Sack in this  
city's historic Plaza were arrested for violating a city ordinance 
that forbids the tossing or kicking of objects. 
</P>
<P>
	Two teens and two adults were arrested Thursday for kicking  
around a Hacky Sack, a golf ball-size bean bag that is kicked a few 
feet in the air by players in a circle. The charges stem from the 
same ordinance that forbids bike riding and skateboards. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a complete abuse of power under a tyrannical  
government,'' said Simon Constable, 16, one of those charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they arrested the four after they kept playing  
despite repeated warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were given the opportunity to stop,'' Capt. David Segura  
said. ``They felt it wasn't just and continued as a form of 
protest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Constable said he suspects police arrested them because it was  
the day before the start of Indian Market, which draws an average 
of 100,000 people to Santa Fe and the Plaza, which has existed for 
centuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``They wanted to clear out (teen-agers) because they don't want  
youth scaring off their paychecks,'' Constable said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
