<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> School Reviews Star of David Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) -- A school system will review a decision  
prohibiting a Jewish student from wearing a Star of David necklace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Harrison County School Board had earlier told high school  
junior Ryan Green that he could not display the Star of David 
because a school policy banned wearing anything visible that could 
be viewed as a gang symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement officials say some gang symbols incorporate  
six-pointed stars but normally have other elements, such as a 
letter or a pitchfork. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision led to a threatened lawsuit by the American Civil  
Liberties Union and complaints from religious groups and others. 
</P>
<P>
	David Ingebretsen, with the ACLU in Mississippi, said today the  
board's promise to review the decision would not end his plans for 
a lawsuit. He said he intended to ask U.S. District Court to 
instruct the school board to immediately suspend the policy pending 
a decision on a lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The school does not ban Christian crosses on jewelry, saying no  
gangs around there use anything similar to it as a symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	School board members met privately Thursday with representatives  
from the Jewish community, law enforcement and tourism bureaus. The 
groups later issued a joint statement saying they agreed the 
decision was motivated by safety concerns and not religious 
prejudice. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very calm meeting, a very professional meeting,''  
said Luis R. Dorfman, president of the Southeast Region B'nai 
B'rith and past president of Congregation Beth Israel. He said 
everyone at the meeting agreed that the board is sincerely 
interested in safety and ``is not motivated by anti-Semitism or 
religious discrimination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	School Superintendent Henry Arledge said the board will likely  
discuss the necklace policy again on Aug. 30 and make a decision on 
Sept. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would think the board will just review it on the grounds of  
it being a religious symbol and try to come to some kind of 
resolution to make it acceptable,'' Arledge said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingebretsen said the lawsuit would go beyond the Green family.  
</P>
<P>
	``Their son has said he wanted to do this, not only for himself  
but others who might be affected by the policy in the future,'' 
Ingebretsen had said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 11:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Banks Announce Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The deal struck by three Japanese lenders to form  
the world's biggest bank generated optimism Friday that similar 
alliances would follow, thinning the ranks of an overcrowded 
industry that has long lost its knack for turning a profit. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts approached the alliance cautiously, saying the  
marriage of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., the Industrial Bank of Japan 
Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. could founder if they fail to unload excess 
baggage and depend on sheer size alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Even one of the main players in the pact, the chairman of  
Dai-Ichi Kangyo, expressed similar fears. 
</P>
<P>
	``If big banks just get together, it's possible they'll become  
too massive, like an elephant, and might topple when the right leg 
gets in the way of the left leg,'' Katsuyuki Sugita said at a press 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger will create a mammoth financial institution with  
complementary strengths -- investment banking for IBJ and retail 
banking for DKB and Fuji. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets at the three banks exceed $1.2 trillion, which would make  
the new entity the largest banking group in the world, surpassing 
the $735.3 billion in assets of Germany's Deutsche Bank and the 
$652 billion of Japan's largest bank, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, 
as well as the largest U.S. bank -- Citigroup, at $668.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the alliance's sheen of boldness, some analysts saw it  
as a defensive move, designed more to survive the new 
government-engineered era of competition in Japan's financial 
markets than to stake a claim in the global arena. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past two years, the number of major Japanese banks has  
dwindled to 17 from 20 with the collapse of a city bank and two 
long-term credit banks. Some experts predict that number soon to 
fall to five or six. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's banks have been troubled by huge loans gone sour after  
the speculative lending rush of the late 1980s and early 1990s, and 
the three lenders in Friday's alliance have been hard hit. 
</P>
<P>
	IBJ rose to prominence as a financier for Japan's dramatic  
postwar ascension to global renown, but it has struggled to remain 
relevant as the age of the Japanese industrial bank wanes. The 
bank's main rivals -- Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan and Nippon 
Credit Bank -- have both collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the banks denied they were getting together merely to  
stay afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be front-runners in bringing about a revival of  
Japan's financial sector,'' said IBJ head Masao Nishimura. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials went out of their way to welcome the pact,  
even though it still faces questions from Japanese antitrust 
regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a simple merger, but rather a new, resolute move  
built on lessons learned from the past, and as such I evaluate it 
highly,'' said Hakuo Yanagisawa, head of Japan's Financial 
Reconstruction Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Yanagisawa's comments suggest the government will encourage  
further alliances. And the three-way deal will certainly put 
pressure on other Japanese banks to forge their own mega-mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say several of Japan's major banks -- including Sanwa  
Bank, Sumitomo Trust Bank and Mitsubishi Trust and Banking -- are 
likely to be involved in major banking alliances. 
</P>
<P>
	``(The IBJ-DKB-Fuji alliance) would appear to constitute the  
first shot in a series of like moves,'' said James Fiorillo, a 
banking analyst at ING Barings. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank, which already have an alliance, said  
Friday they are actively pursuing a merger, and the Yomiuri 
newspaper reported that they will set up a holding company in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to cut costs, the bank chiefs promised to reduce  
the combined number of branches by 150 within five years after 
forming a joint holding company by October next year. By the spring 
of 2002, the group will be reorganized according to its financial 
operations, such as consumer banking, corporate banking and 
securities. 
</P>
<P>
	They also plan to cut up to 6,000 jobs, or 17 percent, from  
their combined payroll. The new group is aiming for annual profit 
of nearly $9 billion and to reduce costs by $896 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial experts warned the banks to keep their word.  
</P>
<P>
	``Rapid restructuring is essential to the success of the  
proposed alliance,'' said credit-rating agency Standard and Poor's. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
