<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 19:06:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC Reports on Drug-Resistant Staph </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Federal health officials say the deaths of  
four previously healthy children from a drug-resistant bacteria is 
not cause for panic, but they stress that doctors need to be aware 
the bacteria has spread. 
</P>
<P>
	``They need to be able to take this into account when they're  
making decisions about how to test for infections and how to treat 
them,'' said Dr. Timothy Naimi, an epidemiologist with the Centers 
for Disease Control and Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	One-quarter of all humans carry staph bacteria, but  
drug-resistant staphylococcus aureus infections were largely 
thought to be confined to hospitals and nursing homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The deaths of the children, from diverse ethnic backgrounds and  
environments, indicated healthy people could be susceptible to the 
drug-resistant strain. 
</P>
<P>
	The children, two from Minnesota and two from North Dakota,  
ranged in age from 1 to 13. Two were white, one was black and one 
was American Indian. Their deaths, between 1997 and 1999, were 
documented in a report released by the CDC. 
</P>
<P>
	Two hundred people have become ill in the past two years after  
contracting staph infections resistant to penicillin and 
cephalosporin, drugs from the most common class of antibiotics, the 
CDC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Kirk Smith of the Minnesota Department of Health said cases  
had been reported in Australia, New Zealand and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not in any way a widespread epidemic,'' Naimi said  
Friday. ``The risk to any individual of getting an infection from 
staph aureus is very low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Staph germs are passed through skin-to-skin contact but  
generally don't become a problem unless they enter the body through 
a cut or abrasion. Good hygiene such as frequent hand-washing can 
minimize the chance of infection. 
</P>
<P>
	The four children who died were given the right antibiotics to  
treat their symptoms, but the doctors who treated them were not 
aware the drug-resistant strain had spread into the general 
population, said Dr. Michael Osterholm, a former Minnesota state 
epidemiologist involved in the CDC study. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason the bacteria may have become resistant to some drugs  
is the overuse of antibiotics, said North Dakota state 
epidemiologist Larry Shireley. 
</P>
<P>
	``As physicians in the medical community, we need to look at how  
we are prescribing drugs, to make sure that we are prescribing 
drugs appropriately and look at the drug resistance pattern when we 
treat,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
