<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Citadel's Faulkner Finishes College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANDERSON, S.C. (AP) --Shannon Faulkner, who fought a legal battle  
to open the all-male military academy The Citadel to women, has 
graduated from a college 200 miles across the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Faulkner earned a bachelor's degree in secondary education  
of English this month at Anderson College, one of two schools she 
attended after dropping out of The Citadel. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Faulkner made national headlines when she sued The Citadel  
in 1993 seeking admission. She became the first woman day student 
at the state-run military school in Charleston in January 1994, 
attending classes under a federal court order. 
</P>
<P>
	She started classes and training in August 1995, but left after  
six days, citing the pressure of her long struggle and the 
isolation of being the only female cadet. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Faulkner attended Furman University in Greenville in 1996  
and 1997 before going to Anderson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Citadel dropped its all-male admissions policy in 1996,  
following a U.S. Supreme Court decision striking down the all-male 
policy at the Virginia Military Institute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
