<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 12:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Anounces Blood Tests for Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Some form of blood testing will be  
introduced at next year's Sydney Olympics in a bid to improve 
detection of performance-enhancing drugs, the IOC announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In another move to step up the fight against drugs, the  
International Olympic Committee affirmed that a world anti-doping 
agency will definitely be set up by the end of this year and will 
be operational for the Sydney Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls for blood testing at the Olympics have mounted in the wake  
of a spate of high-profile drug scandals in track and field and 
other sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Several performance-enhancing drugs of choice, such as human  
growth hormone and EPO (erythropoietin), cannot be detected in 
standard urine tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug issue was a centerpiece of an IOC executive board  
meeting on the eve of the World Athletics Championships opening 
Saturday in Seville. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be blood testing in Sydney, if not for doping  
control, at least for scientific research,'' IOC spokesman Franklin 
Servan-Schreiber said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The test works and we have a procedure,'' he said, noting that  
blood tests were carried out at the world short-course swimming 
championships in Hong Kong earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal is to have a foolproof test that could be used as part  
of the official doping control procedures during the Sydney Games. 
Normally, all medalists, as well as other athletes chosen at 
random, are tested during the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Servan-Schreiber said blood tests could also be implemented in  
out-of-competition controls on the eve of the Sydney Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can find a test that is 100 percent reliable and will  
not jeopardize the reputation of athletes or cause legal problems 
for the federations, we would have no problem'' using it for 
official controls, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the test is not perfected yet, athletes will be asked to  
undergo ``voluntary'' blood testing for research purposes. The test 
results would be unofficial, and positive tests would not be 
sanctioned. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC also declared its commitment to the establishment of an  
international anti-doping agency. The project was approved in 
February at a world drug summit in Lausanne, Switzerland, but the 
location of the agency and other details still have not been 
finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said the agency, which would coordinate drug testing  
around the world, would be in place by the end of the year and be 
up and running by the Sydney Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC has been at odds with European governments over the  
status and location of the agency. Critics say the agency should be 
completely independent of the IOC and should not be based in 
Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	A special IOC panel is scheduled to meet Sept. 10 to finalize  
arrangements for the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is putting up $25 million to set up the agency, but  
expects governments and other organizations to contribute as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, the IOC approved the allocation of $2 million for  
further anti-doping research, particularly for developing reliable 
tests for EPO and human growth hormone. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC also backed the anti-doping efforts of the International  
Amateur Athletic federation, the world governing body of track and 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	The sport has been rocked by recent positive drug cases  
involving such high-profile athletes as Javier Sotomayor, Linford 
Christie and Merlene Ottey. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand why these cases have led to criticism of  
the sport,'' IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said. 
``Personally, I believe athletics deserves to be congratulated 
because it is fighting doping with facts, not just words. The IAAF 
should be an example to other federations.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
