<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Hurt in Hot Air Balloon Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- A downdraft slammed a hot air balloon into the  
ground, scattering sightseeing passengers as it bounced into a 
highway median and then into the desert. Three people were injured, 
one seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was blood and screaming,'' passenger Janet Barton said.  
``It was quite frightening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Long, president of Hot Air Expeditions, which owns the  
balloon, said the pilot and 12 passengers -- including tourists from 
England -- were on an hour-long flight north of Phoenix on Thursday. 
The balloon was suddenly forced down by windy ``microburst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fire Department Capt. Doug Mummert said the balloon hit a  
highway median and then bounded over one of the lanes and across 
100 feet of desert. 
</P>
<P>
	``People either bounced out or were thrown out of the gondola,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Long said it was the first flight injury in the company's  
11-year history. He said pilot William Swanson made a good landing, 
given the weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite rain, wind, lightning and dark clouds in the area, Long  
said Swanson and two of the company's other pilots took balloons up 
after checking with weather officials. Two balloons landed when 
winds got stronger, but Swanson couldn't find an open area to land. 
</P>
<P>
	The most seriously injured was Helen Bermener, 51, who was in  
serious condition at a hospital with head, ankle and wrist trauma. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
