<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Earnhardt Jr. No Rookie to Mich. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- Dale Earnhardt Jr. hopes all the notes  
he's been taking on driving at Michigan Speedway pay off in 
Sunday's Pepsi 400. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt Jr., son of the seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup  
champion, will start from the 17th position after turning in a 
qualifying lap Friday of 186.042 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	And he beat his dad in the process. Dale Sr. could do no better  
than 35th in qualifying with a lap of 183.763 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	While it will be his first Winston Cup start on the 2-mile  
superspeedway, Earnhardt Jr. competed in a NASCAR Busch Series race 
in August 1998 and an International Race of Champions event this 
June. In the latter race, he finished second to his dad. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tested the Winston Cup car last week at Michigan,''  
Earnhardt Jr. said. ``I think some of what we learned will help us 
with the Busch car and I, of course, got a few lessons from my dad 
when we ran the IROC race here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the younger Earnhardt's third Winston Cup start this  
season. He also ran at the Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte, N.C., and 
the Jiffy Lube 300 at Loudon, N.H. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made the first round (qualifying), and I was worried at the  
start of the year about just making the races,'' Earnhardt said. 
``We made the first rounds of my first three races and that gives 
us something to work on next year. ``This is all about taking notes 
and getting experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GO AHEAD, PLEASE*: Bill Elliott thinks the only time that being  
first is worth it is at the end of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott's feelings were reinforced after luck of the draw put  
him first on the track for qualifying. He turned in a lap of 
186.384 mph. However, the track conditions improved throughout the 
session and so did other drivers' speeds. As a result, Elliott 
ended up with the 14th-best speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to be the first guy out,'' Elliott said. ``You don't  
really know where you stand because it seems like so much has 
changed when we practiced last. The Busch cars went out there and 
then we ran again and you don't really know where you're at when 
you sit down to really go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott has won seven times at Michigan, the last time in 1989.  
In the Kmart 400 in June, he qualified fifth but finished 41st on 
race day after an oil fitting broke on his McDonald's Ford early in 
the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a good run here in the spring,'' Elliott said. ``We've  
got to just keep digging. The biggest thing is we're trying to turn 
this deal around. If we keep nibbling at it week in and week out, 
we'll be all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PARTING OF WAYS*: Team SABCO and Joe Nemechek will be parting  
ways at the end of the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was an extremely difficult decision for the both of us,  
but we have been discussing it for a while,'' team owner Felix 
Sabates said. ``I've developed a very close relationship with Joe, 
(his wife) Andrea and his mom and dad throughout our three years 
together. But Joe and I both felt that a fresh start would be best 
for us all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek started with Team SABCO in 1997. Since then, he's had  
three pole positions and finished in the top 10 eight times. His 
best and only top-10 finish this season was sixth at the Pontiac 
Excitement 400 in Richmond. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got the equipment and we've got the communication,''  
Nemechek said. ``We've just been unable to make it work in our 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sabates said a replacement driver will be named in the near  
future. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MARLIN FINED*: Sterling Marlin was fined $5,000 by NASCAR for  
intentionally hitting Chad Little with his car following last 
week's Frontier at the Glen in Watkins Glen, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Marlin, who finished 33rd, hit Little, who was 14th, while the  
cars were entering pit lane. Marlin bumped Little's rear bumper 
several times with his Chevrolet. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR said Marlin was cited for ``actions detrimental to auto  
racing.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
