<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Makes Grains, Soybeans Retreat / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices retreated  
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade after some private forecasters 
predicted a greater possibility of rain in some dry growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
        Some meteorologists were calling for increased rainfall in  
the next few days across the Midwest, while a tropical storm in the 
Gulf of Mexico opened the possibility for rain in the U.S. Delta. 
</P>
<P>
        Investors ignored reports out of a crop tour of Midwestern  
farms, which indicated yields are likely to be far lower than current 
U.S. Agriculture Department estimates. Market participants said those 
reports already had been factored into prices. 
</P>
<P>
        Analysts said the latest forecasts gave the market a chance  
to take a rest from strong gains made earlier this week. Still, the 
National Weather Service's 10-day forecast, released after trading 
had ended, called for only normal to below-normal precipitation in 
major growing states. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery fell 2 3/4 cents to $2.86 1/2 a  
bushel; December corn fell 3 3/4 cents to $2.22 1/2 a bushel; December 
oats rose 1/4 cent to $1.14 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 5 
cents to $4.72 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef futures were mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
        October live cattle fell .20 cent to 65.45 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle was unchanged at 78.17 cents a pound; October lean hogs 
rose 1.45 cents to 44.65 cents a pound; February pork bellies rose 
1.17 cents to 55.32 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
