<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Multiple Killer Caught in Pa. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MENDENHALL, Pa. (AP) -- Luck ran out this morning for escaped  
murderer Norman Johnston, who was captured not far from his 
hometown after a manhunt that lasted nearly three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see the smile on my face, that says it all,'' state police  
Capt. Henry Oleyniczak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police focused on the area Thursday night after spotting a car  
stolen in Newark, Del., where Johnston had been sighted and nearly 
captured. The driver fled after crashing the car, but he was 
tracked down by authorities using helicopters and dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston, 48, was captured in a shed without a struggle,  
Oleyniczak said. He was not armed. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston escaped Aug. 2 after cutting his way through a cell  
window at a maximum-security prison in Huntingdon, nearly 200 miles 
from here in western Pennsylvania. After his escape, authorities 
here alerted dozens of residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Mendenhall is only a few miles from Johnston's hometown of  
Kennett Square, just outside Philadelphia. Some of his relatives 
still live in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sightings were made by police, who even struggled with  
Johnston a couple of times. He fought them off and ran away. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston was convicted in 1980 of killing four teen-agers to  
cover up a multimillion-dollar burglary ring he ran with his two 
brothers. The film ``At Close Range,'' starring Sean Penn, was 
based on the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston and his two older brothers, Bruce Sr. and David, were  
sentenced to life terms for the slayings in the late 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Johnston Sr. also was convicted of killing his son's  
girlfriend and trying to kill his son, Bruce Jr., who later gave 
incriminating testimony against his father and uncles. 
</P>
<P>
	The burglary ring included more than 40 people and operated for  
nearly 20 years. The gang was responsible for stealing hundreds of 
trucks, cars and farm equipment in Delaware, Maryland and 
Pennsylvania. At least 25 other people were convicted of burglary 
and fencing charges until the gang's 1987 demise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Johnston brothers have continued to appeal their murder  
convictions, and Norman Johnston was to have a hearing later this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, authorities also captured a murderer and an  
arsonist who escaped from another state prison this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael McCloskey and Anthony Yang broke out of the  
medium-security state prison Monday in Dallas, 100 miles northwest 
of Philadelphia. They were arrested together Thursday night near 
Wyoming, less than 10 miles from the prison. 
</P>
<P>
	McCloskey was convicted of shooting a 70-year-old man to death  
during a lunchtime robbery of a Philadelphia bar in 1985. Yang 
admitted setting 10 fires in 1987 that caused $3 million in damage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
