<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets ended the week higher  
Friday, with prices rising in Tokyo on news that three Japanese 
banks plan an alliance to become the world's biggest banking group. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 218.37 points,  
or 1.22 percent, to close at 18,098.11. On Thursday, the average 
dropped 12.52 points, or 0.07 percent, to finish at 17,879.74. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial giants Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., Dai-Ichi Kangyo  
Bank Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. said they plan an alliance that would 
create a banking giant with assets of more than $1 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement boosted the banks' shares to their daily rise  
limit. Issues of other banks rumored to be considering similar 
moves also rose. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 111.48 yen at  
late afternoon, down 0.15 yen from its level late Thursday in 
Tokyo, but above its late level of 111.40 overnight in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai shares also surged, with the key index soaring more than 5  
percent, as as banking stocks rebounded strongly from recent 
losses, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand index rose 22.51 points, or 5.3  
percent, to 440.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks rose for the third straight session as  
investors shrugged off a possible rise in U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 163.15 points, or 1.2 percent, to close at 
13,566.74. On Thursday, the index had surged 410.49 points, or 3.2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, share prices on Wall Street fell on expectation of  
a rise in interest rates next week. The Dow Jones industrial 
average slipped 27.54 points to 10,963.84, after dropping as much 
as 118 points in earlier trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks advanced for a third day as a protest  
against constitutional changes proposed by President Joseph Estrada 
went off peacefully. The Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 
selected companies rose 50.27 points, or 2.3 percent, to 2,209.47. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher as investors were encouraged  
by a government plan to support shares of fundamentally sound 
companies that have fallen below book value. The market's key 
Weighted Stock Price Index rose 152.75 points, or 1.9 percent, to 
8,117.42. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly lower. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 4.18 points, or 0.1 percent, 
to 2,177.38. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed mixed in thin trading as  
participants awaited a decision next week by the U.S. Federal 
Reserve on interest rates. The All Ordinaries Index slipped 1.70 
points, or 0.05 percent, to 3,025.4. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher for a second day, boosted by  
continued foreign buying. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index 
rose 7.21 points, or 0.8 percent, to 878.39. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher on foreign  
buying. The main Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip 
stocks, rose 4.94 points, or 0.6 percent, to 763.38. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed higher as investor confidence  
returned after shaking off lingering fears of a possible U.S. 
interest rate rise. The benchmark Straits Times Index rose 17.40 
points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,087.42. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed lower. The benchmark Composite  
Index fell 5.579 points, or 0.9 percent, to 576.167. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
