<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevorkian Aide Accused of Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO RANCHO, N.M. (AP) -- An associate of Jack Kevorkian has been  
charged with first-degree murder, accused of giving a drug overdose 
to a multiple sclerosis patient whose death once was blamed on 
natural causes. 
</P>
<P>
	Georges Reding was charged Thursday with the death of Donna  
Brennan, 54, of Rio Rancho. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding, a 74-year-old retired psychiatrist, also was indicted on  
charges of practicing medicine without a license, trafficking in a 
controlled substance and evidence tampering. 
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy showed Ms. Brennan died in 1998 from a lethal dose of  
a sedative. Authorities said telephone and credit card records, 
along with a witness, place Reding at Brennan's house around the 
time of her death. 
</P>
<P>
	``This whole case began because the family asked the Rio Rancho  
Department of Public Safety to look into the circumstances 
surrounding Donna Brennan's death,'' District Attorney Mike Runnels 
said. ``It was their unease that initiated the whole thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reding did not return a message left Thursday at his home in  
Galesburg, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Schwartz, Reding's attorney, has said Ms. Brennan  
contacted the psychiatrist for counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	``The indictment is absolutely ridiculous. There's no way  
they're ever going to show that Dr. Reding murdered anybody,'' 
Schwartz said. ``We're dealing with a woman who was very severely 
ill, who had expressed an interest in ending her suffering in the 
only way it could be ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way they can show she didn't end her own life.''  
</P>
<P>
	Assisted suicide is a felony in New Mexico, punishable by up to  
18 months in prison. But the grand jury chose to indict Reding on a 
charge of first-degree murder, which carries a potential life 
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	If the case goes to trial, the indictment says jurors ``may be  
instructed to consider murder in the second degree.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian is serving a 10- to 25-year sentence for second-degree  
murder and drug delivery in the lethal injection of a patient with 
Lou Gehrig's disease. Kevorkian, 71, says he has attended more than 
130 suicides. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Reding and Kevorkian were charged in connection with  
three assisted suicides in Oakland County, Mich. A prosecutor later 
dropped all the charges, saying there was insufficient evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than two years later, Reding and Kevorkian were arrested on  
charges they resisted arrested and interfered with police while 
dropping a body off at a Royal Oak, Mich., hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Reding was acquitted; Kevorkian was convicted.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
