<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Bank Scandal Intensifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A top-level parliamentary committee  
demanded Friday that Indonesia's finance minister and bank 
restructuring agency chief be dismissed over a widening bank 
corruption scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have to be fired,'' said Ekki Syachruddin, a deputy of  
the ruling Golkar Party, referring to Finance Minister Bambang 
Subianto and Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency Chairman Glenn 
Yusuf. 
</P>
<P>
	Syachruddin said the committee looking into the ballooning Bank  
Bali scandal had not yet decided whether Indonesia's central bank 
governor, Sjahril Sabirin, should also resign. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, police said they had named a key figure in Golkar  
as a suspect in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The affair broke after an audit into Bank Bali found its  
directors had funneled $80 million in government bailout money to 
PT Era Giat Prima, a little-known finance and debt-collection 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	PT Era is controlled by a senior Golkar official. Opponents of  
Golkar allege the money was to bankroll a bid by President B.J. 
Habibie to retain the presidency when an electoral college selects 
a head of state in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition politicians have implicated several members of  
Indonesia's ruling elite in the scandal, including some Cabinet 
ministers and one of Habibie's brothers. Golkar leaders have denied 
any involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	Syachruddin's committee threatened to take the unprecedented  
step of summoning Habibie to testify on the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Police spokesman Brig. Gen. Togar Sianipar said investigators  
have requested presidential approval to interrogate Setya Novanto, 
Golkar's deputy treasurer. Novanto and Bank Bali's president 
director, Rudy Ramly, were among five people named Friday as 
suspects in the case, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police chief Gen. Roesmanhadi told the Suara Pembaruan daily  
that police might begin questioning Cabinet ministers as well as 
the chairman of the presidential advisory council about their 
alleged involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Monetary Fund, which is overseeing a massive  
economic plan for the world's fourth-most populous nation, has 
demanded that wrongdoers in the case be brought to justice. The IMF 
fears the scandal could damage attempts to reform Indonesia's 
crippled economy, long riddled by corruption. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
