<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed, Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar was mixed Friday, losing ground to  
the euro but recovering a bit from a seven-month low against the 
Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0668, up  
from $1.0630 late Thursday. The dollar also was quoted at 111.52 
Japanese yen, up from 111.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign exchange analysts said Friday's currency markets had  
little direction and were essentially drifting on momentum from 
earlier in the week. Traders were skittish about taking a strong 
position in advance of Tuesday's meeting of Federal Reserve 
policy-makers.	   The session was basically a ``continuation of optimism'' for a 
rebound in the fledgling single European economy, said David Solin, 
a partner at Foreign Exchange Analytics in Essex, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe's economy, which no long ago appeared on ``the edge of  
total disaster,'' now appears to be stabilizing, Solin said. 
</P>
<P>
	And traders remain enthusiastic on the potential of the yen,  
despite Friday's mild reversal against the dollar. ``Most people 
are bullish on the yen,'' said Thomas Arnold, chief currency trader 
at Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold cited several reasons for traders' optimism; the rebound  
in Japan's Nikkei Index, Tokyo's benchmark stock market indicator 
that has risen nearly 30 percent since Jan. 1; fund managers' 
increased interest in Japanese stocks; and the merger announced 
Friday of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Fuji and Industrial Bank of Japan 
into the world's largest bank, which is being viewed as a positive 
for Japan's resurgent economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4957 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5037 Thursday, and 1.4964 Canadian dollars, upfrom 1.4930. The 
British pound fell to $1.6142 from $1.6186. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8334 German 
marks, down from 1.8403; 6.1491 French francs, down from 6.1708; 
and 1,815 Italian lire, down from 1,821. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
