<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Wants To Fine Sears, Wal-Mart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration is proposing  
fines against the nation's two largest retailers for allegedly 
violating hazardous materials regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears, Roebuck and Co. and Wal-Mart Stores are accused of  
shipping hazardous materials without using the proper packaging and 
inadequately labeling them. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA increased its number of hazardous material inspectors  
after 110 people were killed in the May 1996 crash in the 
Everglades of a ValuJet airliner, spokeswoman Elizabeth Isham Cory 
said. The crash was attributed to mislabeled oxygen canisters, 
which caused a fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA alleges Bensonville, Ark.-based Wal-Mart on May 11,  
1998, improperly offered a shipment containing dry chemical fire 
extinguishers for transport by Airborne Express from a facility in 
Hermiston, Ore. to Seymour, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	The extinguishers were not packaged properly, nor labeled or  
described as required by the Department of Transportation, Cory 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight ounces of the nonflammable material in one extinguisher  
leaked and was noticed by Airborne ground crew, Cory said. The FAA 
is seeking a $50,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart spokesman John Bisio said that the company is  
investigating their shipping procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	``We safely ship thousands of cases of merchandise every day. We  
take this matter very seriously and are cooperating with the FAA 
fully on this,'' Bisio said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA is accusing Hoffman Estates, Ill.-based Sears of giving  
a garden tractor battery that contained corrosive materials and 
explosive gases to Airborne Express on Oct. 1. The package was 
shipped to Airborne's sorting facility in Wilmington, Ohio, where 
the ground crew noticed acid stains on the container's exterior. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA is proposing a $55,000 fine against Sears.  
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as we learned about this last year, we took prompt  
action to make sure we can avoid this kind of shipment in the 
future,'' Sears spokeswoman Jan Drummond said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies have 30 days to respond to the FAA's allegations.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
