<DOCNO> APW19990820.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 13:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former AD Sues Tennessee State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Vivian Fuller, fired as Tennessee State  
athletic director last January, is suing the school, claiming she 
was let go because she tried to improve women's sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuller, who was the only black woman athletic director at a  
Division I school with a football program, also said she was 
treated less favorably than her male colleagues, fired without 
notice and defamed by school officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed Thursday in U.S. District Court, also names  
the Tennessee Board of Regents, which oversees TSU. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuller is seeking an unspecified financial award, damages for  
lost income and reinstatement as athletic director or a comparable 
job at the school. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials contacted by The Tennessean said they had not  
seen the lawsuit and declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuller, 42, was hired in October 1997 after serving as athletic  
director at Northeastern Illinois for five years. She was fired 14 
months later when school officials said they wanted to take the 
athletic program in another direction. 
</P>
<P>
	Fuller said shortly before her firing she questioned the  
disparity in funding between the men's and women's athletic 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the athletic department is ``dominated by male  
employees and by a male chauvinist atmosphere'' and that school 
officials treated her with less respect than her male counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	After she was fired, Fuller said the locks to the athletic  
director's office door were changed and security guards accompanied 
her while she collected her belongings, causing ``humiliation, 
embarrassment and stress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee State hired a new athletic director on Monday. James  
Smith, an assistant athletic director at Memphis, takes over on 
Sept. 1. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
