<HEADLINE> Drechsler Exits World Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Heike Drechsler, the German long jumper  
who competed in all six previous World Championships, pulled out of 
this weekend's meet because of a leg injury. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the latest in a late rush of withdrawals to hit the  
championships, which open Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	British 110-meter hurdler Tony Jarrett, the Commonwealth Games  
champion, pulled out because of a back injury sustained last month. 
</P>
<P>
	James Beckford, the Jamaican long jumper who is No. 4 in the  
world this year, was dropped from the team because he refused to 
take part in his national championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Drechsler, 34, arrived in Seville Thursday but announced her  
withdrawal 24 hours before the opening of what would have been her 
seventh World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did some sprints and I started having problems again,'' she  
said. ``I'm sad because I was in good form, but I'm relieved the 
decision has been made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drechsler had shaped up as the main rival to American star  
Marion Jones in the long jump. Jones, who is seeking an 
unprecedented four gold medals in Seville, lost to Drechsler last 
month in Linz, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
	Drechsler was the youngest champion at the inaugural worlds in  
1983, when she was 18. She won the gold again in 1993, and has six 
medals from six championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Drechsler is one of the biggest names who will miss the  
championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ato Bolton, the 200-meter record holder, is out with a hamstring  
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Also out with injuries are Sergei Bubka, who has won the pole  
vault title at all six previous championships, and Olympic 200 and 
400 champion Marie-Jose Perec of France. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban high jump world record-holder Javier Sotomayor was  
suspended after testing positive for cocaine and Jamaican spinter 
Merlene Ottey pulled out after learning she flunked a test for 
steroids 
  	   	
</P>
