<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Giants in Rush To Realign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The announcement Friday of three Japanese banks'  
plan to create the world's largest banking group is the latest in a 
slew of recent alliances and mergers involving Japanese 
corporations. Here are some of the more significant: 
</P>
<P>
	--AUTO MERGER: Nissan Motor Co. and Renault SA sealed the world's  
fourth-largest auto partnership in March when the French automaker 
agreed to pump $5.8 billion into Nissan's debt-laden operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal made Renault the largest shareholder in Nissan and  
marked increasing involvement by foreign companies in Japan's once 
virtually closed auto sector, which had been struggling with 
slumping sales caused by the Asian economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	--OIL MERGER: Nippon Oil Co. and Mitsubishi Oil Co., two of  
Japan's largest petroleum distributors and refiners, announced last 
October a union that would create the nation's biggest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	The result, named Nisseki Mitsubishi Co., aims to save $630  
million within five years by combining its two parent corporations' 
administrative, distribution and refining operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was a reaction to lower demand due to a recessionary  
economy and a plunge in retail gasoline prices following the 
lifting of a ban on imported fuel in early 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	--BANK MERGER: In a marriage of Japanese financial giants,  
Mitsubishi Bank and the Bank of Tokyo agreed in 1995 to merge to 
form what was then the world's largest bank, with more than $690 
billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal marked an aggressive attempt to compete internationally  
with more profitable rivals in the United States and Europe. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
