<HEADLINE> Tszyu, Gonzalez To Fight for Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Kostya Tszyu and Miguel Angel Gonzalez have waited  
10 months to fight each other, and their chance finally comes 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-round bout for the WBC super-lightweight crown has been  
canceled three times because of injuries and a legal dispute. Tszyu 
and Gonzalez are competing for a title that has been vacant since 
April 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've gotten tired of watching him in videos as I prepared for  
the fight,'' said Gonzalez, of Mexico. ``I'm not going to believe 
when the referee tells us to touch gloves and come out fighting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bout was scheduled for last October, only to be postponed  
when Tszyu suffered a hand injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescheduled for November, the fight was again canceled because  
of a rib injury to Gonzalez. Then, when it seemed the bout was 
ready for the spring, legal problems between the fight's promoters, 
Don King and America Presents, left Tszyu and Gonzalez waiting 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	The 140-pound title has been vacant since Oscar De La Hoya  
relinquished it to move up to the welterweight division. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya's only defense in the division was a tough 12-round  
decision over Gonzalez in January 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``The delays haven't bothered me,'' said Tszyu, a Russian living  
in Australia and a former IBF junior-welterweight champion. ``It 
gave me time to prepare for different plans for Miguel, and one of 
them will work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tszyu (22-1-1, 18 KOs) usually starts a fight with a vengeance,  
looking for the quick finish. But he could change his strategy 
against Gonzalez, who had a 10-fight run as WBC lightweight 
titleholder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who knows what's going to happen with me?'' Tszyu said. ``I  
know I rush a little too much because I don't fight often. It's not 
good for me when I knock down opponents early, because I become 
anxious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez (43-1-1, 33 KOs) will be ready for any quick assault  
from Tszyu, 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's constantly throwing punches,'' Gonzalez said. ``You have  
to control him from a distance and not give him much of an 
opportunity to become active.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, 27, said if he defeats Tszyu, he will fight countryman  
Julio Cesar Chavez in a rematch of their disputed draw last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tszyu has his sights set on unifying the 140-pound belt against  
the other recognized world champions, Sharmba Mitchell (WBA) and 
Terronn Millet (IBF). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
