<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGwire's Pace Same, Target Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mark McGwire is launching baseballs out of  
stadiums at the same record pace he set last year. The target has 
changed, and with it, the interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year we were talking about chasing history, chasing 61,''  
McGwire said Friday before his St. Louis Cardinals were rained out 
against the New York Mets. ``Now people want to talk about Home Run 
Derby Two. This is much lighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire has 48 home runs, one more than last season after the  
122 games and one fewer than Sammy Sosa, whose 66 home runs last 
season fell four short of McGwire's record. Sosa hit two homers 
Friday against Colorado to move back into the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	With Roger Maris' and Babe Ruth's names out of the conversation,  
McGwire and Sosa are only chasing each other. And even though they 
haven't slowed down a bit from 1998, McGwire doesn't expect either 
to make history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seventy is like ridiculous. It really is,'' McGwire said. ``I  
think 60 will be gotten again. Seventy is an extra 10. It is 
unfathomable when you think that I had to hit five in the last 
three days to get there. I don't know how you can ever dream about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's more than a dream. It could be reality. If McGwire hits as  
many homers in the final 40 games of this season as he did last 
year, he'd not only reach 70, he'd top it by one. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only do what I am capable of doing,'' he said. ``People  
say to me every day, `Are you going to hit a home run today.' It's 
like they're asking, `Will I walk down street today?' I wish it was 
easy, but it's not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's just that he's made it look that way the last few years.  
McGwire has 227 homers since the beginning of 1996 and with 13 more 
this season he will be averaging 60 a season over four years. 
That's a plateau that had been reached twice before last season -- 
by Ruth and Maris. 
</P>
<P>
	Four more years at that pace, and McGwire will be threatening  
Hank Aaron's career mark of 755. He is currently 251 homers short. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think anything is possible,'' he said. ``But the man with  
the best shot is Ken Griffey. He has the age, that great stroke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire took advantage of his 40-minute forum with reporters to  
talk about teaching -- young players on how to play the game, the 
public about sexual abuse and children about role models. 
</P>
<P>
	He even revealed that he would tell his own son not to take  
androstenedione, the over-the-counter dietary supplement that 
caused controversy during his chase. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would tell him not to,'' McGwire said. ``That's the way I  
feel. I wouldn't want him to be associated with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last August, McGwire acknowledged to The Associated Press that  
he had used andro for more than a year. McGwire's admission helped 
spark a tenfold increase in sales of the supplement last fall and 
led many steroid experts to warn of serious health consequences for 
teen-agers who took it to emulate McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, McGwire said he had stopped taking andro  
before the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got tired of seeing my name associated with it,'' he said.  
``I didn't want to be seen as an endorser of a product which I 
wasn't endorsing. I got tired of hearing about underage kids taking 
it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
