<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 05:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Farm Van Violations Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A statewide sweep of surprise  
inspections of farm-labor vehicles turned up more than 200 safety 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's early-morning sweep came 10 days after a van crashed  
into a tractor-trailer near Fresno, killing 13 farm workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Highway Patrol checked 118 farm-labor vehicles  
and found a total of 221 safety violations, including defective 
lights, tires, wheels and brakes. Officers took 36 vehicles out of 
service because of serious safety problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to keep the pressure on to make sure all vehicles  
carrying farm workers are safe,'' said CHP Commissioner D.O. 
Helmick. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle check took place the same day that a state Senate  
committee approved legislation requiring seat belts and inspections 
for all vehicles used to transport farm workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal approved 9-1 by the Senate Transportation Committee  
was prompted by the Aug. 9 van crash. The van had an unlicensed 
driver and no seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This month's accident is not new but now Californians are  
focused on these tragedies like never before,'' said Assemblyman 
Dean Florez, one of the bill's sponsors. ``Somehow, these deaths 
used to be seen as part of the harvest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In last week's accident, a van carrying 15 workers from an  
overnight shift at Terra Linda farms crashed into a tractor-trailer 
that was turning around on the two-lane road. Only two passengers 
survived. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1983 Dodge Ram was last certified in 1997 and did not have  
seat belts. None are required under a code that lets farm-worker 
vehicles carrying more than 10 passengers be classified as buses, 
which are exempt from seat belt laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would require seat belts in all vehicles used to  
transport farm laborers, and would require the vehicles to be 
inspected at least once a year. An 800 number would be set up for 
people to report violations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regulation is so long overdue and it's been avoided because it  
costs money,'' said Rosalinda Guillen from the United Farm Workers 
of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Traffic accidents have killed at least 63 farm workers in  
California's Central Valley in the last decade, a bill backer said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
