<HEADLINE> Man 'Sorry' in Yosemite Slay Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- The man suspected of killing four women  
near Yosemite National Park says he is ``truly sorry'' for the pain 
he's caused and says selling his story could compensate families of 
the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Cary Stayner, 38, is charged with last month's slaying of  
naturalist Joie Ruth Armstrong, 26, and is suspected in the 
killings of Carole Sund, 42, her 15-year-old daughter Juli and 
16-year-old Argentine exchange student Silvina Pelosso in February. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter sent to The Fresno Bee from the Fresno County jail,  
Stayner wrote: ``I would like to say how deeply sorry I am for all 
the pain and sorrow I've brought upon so many people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stayner has pleaded innocent to a first-degree murder charge,  
which carries a potential death sentence. No one has been charged 
in the sightseers' case. 
</P>
<P>
	Stayner's late brother, Steven, was the subject of a book and  
television movie after being kidnapped as a child and sexually 
abused for seven years before escaping. After his July 24 arrest, 
Cary Stayner reportedly said he'd like to see his life story turned 
into a TV movie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realize that the money would be little consolation for the  
loss of their loved ones but until the jury, judge and executioner 
fulfill their role in this matter, it's all I have to offer,'' 
Stayner wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said it wants to see the letter. ``It could be a very  
important piece of evidence,'' said FBI agent Nick Rossi. 
</P>
<P>
	Stayner likely won't face trial for months. A judge on Thursday  
said a trial date probably will be scheduled on Dec. 2. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
