<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Powerful Quake Hits Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A powerful earthquake rattled three  
Central American nations Friday, damaging buildings in Panama but 
leaving other parts of the region unscathed, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6.7-magnitude quake, with its epicenter 55 miles south of  
Costa Rica's capital, San Jose, struck at 4 a.m. and was felt 
throughout that country as well as parts of Panama and Nicaragua, 
said Don Blakeman, a geophysicist at the National Earthquake 
Information Center in Golden, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The quake was felt most strongly in villages along Costa Rica's  
Pacific coastline and the major cities in the central valley, where 
most of the 3.5 million people of the country live. 
</P>
<P>
	In western Panama, where people rushed out into the streets and  
authorities reported broken windows, cracked walls and other minor 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Two residential buildings made of concrete were seriously  
damaged in Panama's La Mesa de San Cristobal, said civil defense 
spokesman Jorge Correa. 
</P>
<P>
	Only slight tremors were felt in the southern half of Nicaragua,  
and no damage or casualties were reported there. 
</P>
<P>
	The last major quake to hit Costa Rica occurred on April 1991.  
It registered 7.4 in magnitude and caused the death of 95 people. 
About 800 were injured and severe damages were reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
