<DOCNO> APW19990820.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 01:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Banks Announce Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Hoping to find their way out of the industry's  
worst crisis since World War II, three Japanese banks announced 
today an alliance that would create the world's largest banking 
group -- a giant with more than $1 trillion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance, to be implemented over the next two years, was  
announced by the presidents of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., the 
Industrial Bank of Japan Ltd., and Fuji Bank Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	The move sent share prices soaring on the Tokyo Stock Exchange  
and was generally welcomed by analysts as a long-overdue effort to 
deal with the realities of an overcrowded market, massive bad loans 
and woefully low profit margins. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts were skeptical about whether size alone would  
help make the banks more competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be front-runners in bringing about a revival of  
Japan's financial sector,'' Industrial Bank of Japan head Masao 
Nishimura told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets at the three banks exceed $1.2 trillion, which would make  
the new entity the largest banking group in the world. Their assets 
would surpass the $735.3 billion of Germany's Deutsche Bank and the 
$652 billion of Japan's largest bank, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi. 
</P>
<P>
	Other banks may be following suit. Tokai Bank and Asahi Bank are  
also considering a plan to set up a joint holding company, a Tokai 
spokeswoman said. The Yomiuri newspaper reported today that the 
holding company will be set up in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan announced today, Fuji Bank, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank  
and the Industrial Bank of Japan said they will reduce the combined 
number of branches by 150 within five years after forming a joint 
holding company by October next year. 
</P>
<P>
	By the spring of 2002, the group will be reorganized according  
to its financial operations, such as consumer banking, corporate 
banking and securities. 
</P>
<P>
	They also plan to reduce by 6,000, or 17 percent, their combined  
payroll. The new group is aiming for annual profit of more than 
$8.9 billion and to reduce costs by $896 million, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt the need to create a bank in Japan that is competitive  
on an international level,'' said Fuji Bank president Yoshiro 
Yamamoto. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's banks have been troubled by huge loans gone sour after  
the speculative lending rush of the late 1980s and early 1990s. 
Turning around the banking woes has been viewed as integral to help 
bring along economic recovery in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts agree the main problem of Japan's banking sector  
is that it was overly protected up to now by the government and has 
never been under much pressure to be competitive. It has a dismal 
record as far as turning profits and has been slow in cost-cutting. 
</P>
<P>
	James Fiorillo, analyst at ING Baring Securities Japan, said the  
alliance was part of an inevitable overall trend in the financial 
sector, but remained cautious about the prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would, therefore, view the alliance as much a defensive  
move as an offensive move,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	All three of the banks have had their troubles, although they  
denied they were getting together merely to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank has reported problem loans at its  
parent company amounting to $20 billion. It posted a consolidated 
net loss of $4 billion for the fiscal year ending in March. Fuji 
Bank and the Industrial Bank of Japan also reported large group 
losses for fiscal 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, news of the plan sent the banks' stock prices higher  
today on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Industrial Bank of Japan shares 
were up by 10 percent to $9.70 from the previous close; Dai-Ichi 
Kangyo Bank by 11 percent to $9; Fuji Bank by 9 percent to $9.30. 
</P>
<P>
	And U.S. ratings agency Moody's Investors Services today placed  
on review for possible upgrade the ratings for long-term credit and 
financial strength of the three banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The banks, however, acknowledged more than just size was needed  
to solve their problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``If big banks just get together, it's possible they'll become  
too massive, like an elephant, and might topple when the right leg 
gets in the way of the left leg,'' said Katsuyuki Sugita, head of 
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
