<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 00:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foster Fined for Duke List Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Gov. Mike Foster won't pay a $20,000  
fine for violating campaign finance law by not reporting his 
purchase of a voter list from white supremacist David Duke. The 
governor's supporters will. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster, a Republican who is seeking re-election, said he would  
use campaign funds to pay the fine -- something his attorneys said 
he can legally do. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Board of Ethics fined Foster on Thursday for failing  
to report more than $150,000 in payments to ex-Ku Klux Klan leader 
Duke for a computerized voter list. The governor said the violation 
was unintentional. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have never intentionally broken the law in my life,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a consent opinion negotiated between Foster's lawyers and the  
board, the governor was found to have twice violated the state's 
campaign finance disclosure law. 
</P>
<P>
	The first time was during the 1995 governor's race when he  
failed to report a $103,000 payment for a computerized ``list of 
conservative voters,'' the board said. The second was in 1997 when 
he paid $52,000 for the right to continue to use the list. 
</P>
<P>
	The list of 60,000 to 80,000 names was bought by Foster through  
Impact Mail Ltd., a Metairie firm that brokered the transaction and 
made a $15,000 commission on the deal, Duke said after a grand jury 
appearance in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Orleans federal grand jury has sought information on  
whether Duke paid taxes on income he received from Foster and 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the purchase has become an issue in Foster's  
re-election campaign with his leading opponents -- Rep. William 
Jefferson and Baton Rouge businessman Phil Preis, both Democrats -- 
lambasting him over the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster has said he tried to keep the purchase secret because  
``it ain't real cool to put out there that you're buying something 
from David Duke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has also said he didn't think he needed to report the  
purchase because he used his own money and didn't use the list in 
his campaign. But the Ethics Board said the purchase should have 
been reported regardless of whether the list was used because it 
was bought for the potential purpose of influencing the election. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke ran unsuccessfully for Congress this year, using the  
campaign to tout his latest book contending that blacks are 
genetically inferior to whites and that an Aryan revolution is 
needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
