<HEADLINE> Boy Must Tear Down Treehouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MACHESNEY PARK, Ill. (AP) -- To 9-year-old Gregory Webb, it's a  
treehouse -- even if it is made from lawn chairs, leftover carpet 
and a pet carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	To town officials, it's debris that must be removed.  
</P>
<P>
	Chad Atkinson, the director of planning and zoning in Machesney  
Park, said the treehouse must be gone by the end of next week, 
citing the village's public nuisance ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty sad when the government doesn't have anything  
better to do than tear down a little boy's treehouse,'' said Leslie 
Webb, the boy's mother who has lived in the neighborhood for 18 
years. ``It may not be the prettiest treehouse, but it's his.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Radio host Bruce Butler of WROK in nearby Rockford mentioned the  
issue on his show and there have been enough donations and 
volunteers to build Gregory a new treehouse -- before the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'll be two stories with four decks,'' Gregory declared.  
  	   	
</P>
