<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought May Mean Smaller Apples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- An apple a day may keep the doctor away, but this  
fall you might need to snack on two. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of rain throughout the region will likely produce a  
crop of smaller than usual apples. However, the smaller the fruit, 
the sweeter the taste, say apple growers. 
</P>
<P>
	The apple crop will still be plentiful and will bloom about a  
week earlier than usual, said Russell Powell, executive director of 
the New England McIntosh Growers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	For consumers, the smaller size will mean more apples to a  
bushel -- about 120 instead of 96. A normal-sized apple is about an 
inch bigger than this year's apples are expected to be, Powell 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller apples are just one of many results from the drought,  
which has affected about 15 percent to 20 percent of the country. 
This year's drought has parched crops from Virginia into parts of 
the Midwest and forced suburbs from Washington to New York to 
restrict water use. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Agriculture, using its Aug. 12 crop  
production report, estimates drought-related losses to farmers is 
``$1 billion and counting,'' USDA Chief Economist Keith Collins 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Needless to say, New England apple growers are concerned. Jay  
Marshall, owner of Marshall Farm, Inc. in Fitchburg, Mass., said 
that while the volume of his crop is about average, the apples are 
smaller than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no money in small apples,'' Marshall said. ``They'll  
pay more money for that larger apple and they can sell it for more 
money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The prolonged exposure to the sun does have the added bonus of  
making the apples sweeter than their larger counterparts, which 
contain more water. 
</P>
<P>
	``The smaller they are, they tend to concentrate the sugars,''  
said Cindy Cook-Charpentier, who works at Cook's Valley Farm in 
Wrentham, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, apple growers were faced with the opposite problem:  
too much rain dampened bees' efforts to pollinate the trees. As a 
result, the trees produced fewer apples, but they tended to be 
larger, with a higher water content. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, in areas where rainfall has been plentiful, apples  
should be the normal size. Apple growers say they're waiting to see 
if Mother Nature gives them a final burst of water sometime over 
the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we receive no moisture in the next month, that could have a  
negative effect. If you have plenty of apples and they're smaller, 
that could bring your volume down,'' Powell said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 10:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
