<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Salons Offering Free Condoms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hair stylist Jean Arnold has been listening to  
clients talk about their love lives for the past 25 years. Now, 
she's doing more than just listening. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold is one of 25 beauty salon owners in the nation's capital  
giving her customers free condoms with each cut, color or setting. 
</P>
<P>
	It's part of a month-old pilot program sponsored by the District  
of Columbia's Department of Health aimed at preventing the spread 
of AIDS among black women by giving them condoms to be used by 
their boyfriends. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 1,024 district women who reported having AIDS between  
1995 and 1998, 970 were black, health department statistics show. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold says it's easy to talk to her clients about safe sex.  
</P>
<P>
	``You're like a big sister to them after they come to you for a  
while,'' said Arnold, who owns Mode Beauty Salon in a low-income 
area near Howard University in Northwest Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``This way I help teen-agers get protection,'' she said. ``They  
might not buy condoms on their own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The condoms she distributes, unlike those in stores, are hidden  
inside shiny black make-up compacts. Also inside is an insert 
explaining how using condoms can prevent HIV infection. 
</P>
<P>
	Women say they love the compact's design, said Lisa Hill, who  
owns Braid-a-Beauty on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of women feel embarrassed carrying condoms, and carrying  
the compact makes it a little bit easier,'' Hill said. 
</P>
<P>
	City health officials designed the compact with that in mind,  
said Ronald E. Lewis, director of the D.C. Administration for 
HIV/AIDS, saying the concealment removed a ``psychological 
barrier'' to carrying a condom. Each compact with a condom costs 
the city $1.85, said spokeswoman Judith Johnson. In stores, condoms 
cost $3 to $4 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	The city's policy is to distribute condoms to those 16 or older,  
he said, but some salon owners give the compacts to younger 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Catholic Archdiocese of Washington contends city health  
officials should be encouraging abstinence, particularly among 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the only way to protect the sexual health of women and to  
end pregnancies out of wedlock,'' said archdiocese spokeswoman 
Susan Gibbs. 
</P>
<P>
	She also questioned whether hair stylists should play a role in  
the fight against AIDS. ``It's questionable to use beauty salons to 
distribute medical supplies,'' Gibbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill disagreed: ``They feel very comfortable talking about this  
with me. They're here for a long time, and we develop an intimate 
relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The D.C. Department of Health seems undeterred by criticism. It  
has given each participating salon 300 compacts and 1,000 condom 
refills. Salon owners say they give out five to 25 compacts a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis said the program may be expanded throughout the city and  
beyond its borders. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will closely evaluate and refine the program in coming  
months, and hope that it provides a model for other cities,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
