<HEADLINE> Bengals Safety Injured in Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- Cincinnati Bengals safety Kelvin Moore was  
strapped to backboard and taken from the field on a cart Friday 
night after his head hit the knee of Detroit Lions wide receiver 
Brian Stablein. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Lions officials, Moore sustained a cervical spine  
injury and was conscious and had motor functions when he was taken 
to POH Medical Center where he was listed in stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore landed awkwardly and lay motionless on the turf at the  
Silverdome after falling injured at 9:47 of the third quarter with 
the Lions leading 13-0. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was delayed about 12 minutes while medical personnel  
placed him on the backboard and put a neck brace on him. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Tressa Gardner of POH Medical Center said Moore was in  
stable condition but declined to immediately discuss the extent of 
the injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	After his team's 16-0 loss, Bengals coach Bruce Coslet said  
Moore had injuries to two vertebra in his neck, and ``that's all I 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They said he gained some feeling in the extremities on the  
field, so that's a real good sign, but who knows,'' Coslet said. 
``We'll just wait and see. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything I'd say at this point is pure speculation, and I am  
completely out of my area of expertise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, a 24-year-old rookie free agent out of Morgan State,  
spent most of last season on the practice squad but was on the 
active team for the last four games, playing mostly on special 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	As medical personnel tended to Moore, the Silverdome's sparse  
crowd fell silent, reminiscent of two years ago when Lions 
linebacker Reggie Brown sustained a career-ending neck injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit offensive lineman Mike Utley was paralyzed from the  
waist down after falling on his head after a collision in a game in 
1991. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
