<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Exchange OKs Late Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Accelerating a move toward longer trading days,  
the Chicago Stock Exchange said Friday it will extend its trading 
hours into the late afternoon to snare an increasing number of 
investors who want to buy and sell outside traditional market 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``The driving factor here is listening to investor needs,''  
exchange chief executive Bob Forney said Friday. Investors ``don't 
believe that the only time to buy is between 9 o'clock and 4 
o'clock,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The move by the nation's third-largest stock exchange -- which  
accounts for about 3 percent of U.S. stocks traded daily -- beats 
industry stalwarts the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock 
Market to the punch in shaking up the way financial markets have 
done business for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Both have announced plans to extend their hours, but have put  
off implementation until at least next year to further study the 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago exchange is one of several regional stock exchanges  
that trade the same stocks as those traded in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in October, it will allow limited trading of a variety  
of top corporations between 4 p.m. Eastern time and 6:30 p.m. 
Eastern time. Included will be stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poors 100 
index and Nasdaq 100 index, as well as the 50 to 100 most-active 
issues that aren't in those indexes. 
</P>
<P>
	To protect investors from wide price swings that might take  
place when only a small number of people are trading, investors 
will only be allowed to buy and sell through ``limit orders.'' This 
means buyers will have to state beforehand the maximum price they 
are willing to pay and sellers will have state the minimum price at 
which they are willing to sell. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision gives an increasing number of individual investors  
a more traditional outlet for doing business than online firms. 
</P>
<P>
	With U.S. markets' current hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. Eastern  
time, investors on the West Coast get shut out after lunch, 
although the Pacific Exchange allows trading until 4:30 p.m. 
Between 20 percent to 25 percent of online trades by individual 
investors are placed after hours. 
</P>
<P>
	That has led to the creation of a number of electronic  
competitors vying for after-hours business. Just this week, ETrade 
Group Inc. -- the second-biggest online broker -- said it would work 
with Reuters Group Plc's Instinet, which operates the largest 
electronic trading network, to begin offering after-hours trading 
to individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an important step -- the first move by a traditional staid  
exchange into a world that has been solely an e-commerce place,'' 
said James Punishill, a securities analyst for Forrester Research 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago exchange also could profit from being the first to  
experiment with new ways as the ``stodgy'' NYSE and Nasdaq, 
``locked themselves out of this market for the next 12 months,'' 
Punishill said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago exchange said it expects fast approval from the  
Securities and Exchange Commission because it already has a 
sophisticated electronic trading system in place and would have 
minimal effects on staffing. 
</P>
<P>
	Extending hours is expected to put additional stress on the  
financial service industry, which is currently scrambling to fix 
any potential Year 2000 computer problems and switch next year to 
stock prices quoted in decimals instead of fractions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realize the hours may change at a time that's not real  
convenient to everybody,'' Forney said. ``We're willing to take the 
risk and see if we're right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several large brokerage firms in Chicago declined comment Friday  
on how the change would affect their staffing. But the exchange is 
confident of participation by the largest of the 150 brokerages 
connected to its electronic system, Forney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the move could be trouble for smaller firms.  
</P>
<P>
	``If this would become effective, it would almost put a little  
company like this out of business,'' said Jay Klopfenstein, owner 
of Chicago-based Norwood Securities. ``We could not afford to hire 
somebody to go those extra hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC and others have expressed concern about the risks for  
individual investors in after-hours trading because of thin trading 
volume, which could results in large price swings. 
</P>
<P>
	Forney said such concerns will be addressed by the  
limit-orders-only rule and the decision to extend trading only to 
6:30 p.m. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
