<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European shares closed higher Friday, spurred by  
news of merger talks among utilities and good performances by 
banks, pharmaceuticals and technology shares. 
</P>
<P>
	European shares also were buoyed by the strong opening by U.S.  
stocks, as the dollar perked up against the yen from Thursday's 
seven-month low. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies closed up  
2.61 points, or 0.9 percent, at 305.55. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 
Index, which tracks 297 companies in countries that joined the 
single currency, was up 3.34 points at 319.44 points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was up 35.91 points at  
3,715.39 points, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index was up 29.17 points at 
3,666.40 points. 
</P>
<P>
	News that German utilities Veba and Viag are discussing a merger  
that could be worth around $5 billion drove the Dow Jones Stoxx 
Conglomerate index 1.8 percent higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The 8.4 billion euros double bid by Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux for  
Belgium's Tractebel and Sita also buoyed the utility sector, 
pushing Tractebel's shares sharply higher. The Dow Jones Stoxx 
Utility index closed up 0.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The entry of several banks and of pharmaceutical giant Roche  
into the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 index gave the banking and drug 
sectors a boost. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, HSBC bank, which became a component of the Dow Jones  
Stoxx 50 index, closed up 16 pence at 765 pence. 
</P>
<P>
	London's FTSE-100 index of blue-chip shares was up 1 percent at  
6,180.8 points. 
</P>
<P>
	In other domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index was up  
1.3 percent to 5254.14, the Paris CAC-40 index was 1.4 percent 
higher to 4,472.00, and Milan's MIBtel index rose 0.9 percent to 
33,280.00. Amsterdam's AEX Index rose 0.7 percent to 564.54 and 
Belgium's Bel-20 index rose 0.6 percent to 3,108.59. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
