<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Approves Gun-Control Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- After prolonged lobbying by Gov. Gray  
Davis, the state Assembly has approved a bill aimed at curtailing 
the manufacture and sale of handguns known as Saturday Night 
Specials. 
</P>
<P>
	``This law will give California one of the strongest handgun  
safety standards in the country,'' said Luis Tolley of Los 
Angeles-based Handgun Control, which proposed the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, approved 43-26 on Thursday, would make it a  
misdemeanor to make or sell an unsafe handgun in California after 
Jan. 1, 2001. Handguns would have to have a safety device and pass 
firing and drop-safety tests in independent laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis already has signed bills to restrict assault weapons and  
limit gun purchases to one per month. The Senate, which backed an 
earlier version of the bill, now must consider the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents, including the National Rifle Association, said the  
bill would not get handguns off the streets, since current guns 
would not be banned or confiscated. Existing guns could still be 
sold by private parties, though not by licensed dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't ban the old stuff. Everybody can have everything  
that exists,'' said NRA lobbyist Stephen Helsley. ``The 
black-market sale of handguns will increase.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a Democrat, also directed state agencies to halt their  
sales and transfers of confiscated firearms after a state inquiry 
found that more than 6,000 guns had been sold, traded or 
transferred by state government to gun dealers in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Buford Furrow Jr., the man accused in the Aug. 10 shootings at a  
Jewish community center in Los Angeles, is believed to have used a 
gun once owned by a Washington state police department that sold 
the weapon to a gun dealer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
