<HEADLINE> U.S. Drug Chief To Visit S. America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Barry McCaffrey, the White House drug policy  
chief, said Friday he plans to visit his counterparts in four South 
American countries during a tour next week. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey, director of the Office of National Drug Control  
Policy, begins his trip in Brazil before moving on to Bolivia, Peru 
and Argentina. His visits will include meetings with each country's 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey made a similar tour last month and met with leaders  
from Colombia, Venezuela and Ecuador. He also made stops in Aruba 
and Curacao. 
</P>
<P>
	``On this trip we'll continue to listen to the viewpoints of  
countries who have been very active in trying to build hemispheric 
cooperation,'' McCaffrey said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey recently requested a $1 billion increase in U.S.  
anti-narcotics aid to fight drug problems in Colombia, saying 
current efforts were falling short and the situation had become an 
emergency. On Friday, he said the production of coca, which is used 
to make cocaine, doubled in Columbia in three years, and heroin 
production went from nonexistent to six tons a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The `billion dollar proposal' is out there to allow the  
administration to seize the initiative,'' McCaffrey said. ``Have we 
moved fast enough? Of course not. But what I would also underscore 
is that this is not a U.S. problem, and it's not a Colombian 
problem. It's a multinational problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey also announced that his office will sponsor a Western  
Hemisphere drug policy leadership conference here in November. More 
than 30 governments will be invited to the gathering. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
