<HEADLINE> Canadian Rejects Air Canada Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Air Canada has asked the federal government to  
approve a plan that would see it take over Canadian's international 
business while the smaller airline focuses on domestic routes. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian Airlines rejected the proposal, however, saying Friday  
that it's not acceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Canadian's international routes are the most profitable part  
of our operation,'' Canadian Airlines spokesman Jeff Angel said 
from the airline's headquarters in Calgary. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Canada proposal will form the basis of historic talks  
next week between the two carriers. The talks were made possible 
when Ottawa lifted domestic competition laws for 90 days so the two 
airlines and any other interested investors could share sensitive 
financial data to keep Canadian flying. 
</P>
<P>
	Transport Minister David Collenette gave Canadian and Air Canada  
the freedom to negotiate ticket prices, routes and shared capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian Airlines, with 14,000 employees, is desperately seeking  
new investors to keep the debt-ridden carrier flying. Canadian says 
it needs up to $500 million to allow it to restructure and move 
away from what has been a chronic cash crisis over the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	In its proposal, filed with the federal government, Air Canada  
said a successful deal with Canadian Airlines would include the 
purchase of Canadian's international routes, along with associated 
assets and liabilities; provide code-sharing opportunities for 
Canadian Airlines on Air Canada international routes; and allow 
Canadian keep its domestic operations to compete with Air Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada said it would provide the cash infusion Canadian  
Airlines needs to stay afloat. It also said that most of Canadian 
Airlines' staff would keep their jobs, while Air Canada would hire 
certain employees associated with Canadian's international 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal-based Air Canada, with 23,000 employees, would not  
disclose financial terms. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
