<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Gets Life for Girl's Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARTOW, Fla. (AP) -- A 15-year-old boy was sentenced Friday to  
life for murdering an 8-year-old neighborhood girl in a crime a 
judge said would bring an even harsher sentence on Judgment Day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not perceive you to be a child,'' state Circuit Judge  
Charles Arnold told Joshua Phillips. ``Your monstrous act made you 
an adult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joshua was tried as an adult last month and convicted of  
first-degree murder in the Nov. 3, 1998 death of Maddie Clifton. 
</P>
<P>
	He had pretended to help in the neighborhood search for Maddie  
when there was hope she was still alive, even though her body was 
stuffed into the frame of his waterbed. The pixie-faced girl lived 
across the street from him in a Jacksonville neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Joshua lifted his eyes briefly as he entered the courtroom and  
smiled at his mother. She smiled back. He stood with his head 
bowed, showing no emotion when told that he would not be sentenced 
as a juvenile but as an adult, and would spend life in prison with 
no hope for parole. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge quoted the Bible, then said: ``I'm certain that on  
your Judgment Day you, Joshua Patrick Philips, will be given a 
harsher sentence than I could impose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sentencing came after emotional pleas from both families.  
</P>
<P>
	Joshua's father, Steve Phillips, said it was ``ludicrous and  
obscene'' to have prosecuted the murder charge. Joshua's mother, 
Melissa Phillips, expressed her sorrow to the Cliftons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each time I look out of our kitchen window to the house across  
the street, my heart clutches at the thought of what the Cliftons 
are going through,'' she said through tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry about their grief, but I cannot repair their  
heartbreak any more than I can repair our own,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddie's family told the judge of the memory of an effervescent,  
giggly girl and the impact of a murder that ``was cruel and 
senseless and took Maddie from us all,'' said Steve Clifton, the 
father. He said the family expected Joshua to spend his life in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one or nothing can look up at me with those big, brown  
eyes,'' Maddie's mother, Sheila, told the judge. ``Pictures and 
memories, that's all I've got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida law bars the death penalty for killers under 16. Joshua  
was 14 at the time of the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	Joshua never denied killing Maddie, but said he accidentally hit  
her in the eye with a baseball as they played in his back yard, 
then panicked at her screams and hit and stabbed her to quiet her. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddie's body was hidden for a week until Joshua's mother made  
the grisly discovery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 07:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mall Is Latest in Providence Renewal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- This once-ugly city has become something  
of a Seattle of the East, made trendy by its harbor-like Waterplace 
Park, a new arts district, and a skyline familiar to millions of 
Americans who watch the TV show ``Providence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the city embarked on a new chapter of its much-touted  
rebirth by opening one of the most elaborate shopping malls in the 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	Planners say Providence Place mall, a towering red-brick  
structure whose two halves straddle a river, will draw up to 20 
million shoppers a year -- many from neighboring Massachusetts and 
Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	The mall will ultimately have 165 stores, but only 43 opened  
today -- including Nordstrom's, one of the anchor stores. Among 
others to come are Filene's, Lord &AMP; Taylor, Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, 
Gap, Ann Taylor, and Borders Books and Cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	Also coming to the $460 million mall, which stretches over 13  
acres, are a 16-screen movie theater and a 3-D IMAX theater -- 
expected to be ready later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	With some justification, perhaps, Mayor Vincent A. Cianci Jr.  
gloats about his city's renaissance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can remember when you could roll a bowling ball down the  
streets and you wouldn't hit anybody,'' says Cianci. ``Most 
American cities would drool over Providence now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new mall is the latest piece -- and by far the largest one --  
of an attractive mosaic Cianci has been fashioning out of this city 
of 160,000. 
</P>
<P>
	What's unusual about the new mall is not what's in it, but the  
spectacular view you get of what's outside it. 
</P>
<P>
	Linking the two halves of the multi-level mall is a vaulted  
glass structure called the Wintergarden. As you look out the 
Wintergarden's big glass window you see Waterplace Park, fashioned 
several years ago out of the river that now runs beneath the mall. 
Iron pedestrian bridges arch over Waterplace Park, making it look a 
little like Venice. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing outside the mall, admiring it and Waterplace Park, was  
70-year-old Providence native Larry Orsini. 
</P>
<P>
	``You should have seen Providence in the 1970s. It was really  
down in the dumps,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Providence was once home to booming textile and jewelry  
industries, but many of the factories closed and the city's 
industrial base collapsed. The advent of suburban shopping malls 
nearly killed downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	But a renaissance began taking root here about a dozen years  
ago. It might not have happened without Cianci. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the city he governs, Cianci has staged an amazing comeback.  
</P>
<P>
	Cianci pleaded no contest in 1984 to charges of using a  
fireplace log to assault the lover of his estranged wife. He was 
forced out of office for five years but was re-elected in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Cianci has poured his energies into rebuilding this  
city -- as well as his reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	One of his achievements is Waterplace Park. Others are a  
downtown skating rink and an arts district where artists live and 
work in renovated buildings. 
</P>
<P>
	This stunning turnaround has caught the attention of travel  
writers from across the country, and their articles have resulted 
in a surge of visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	But Providence is still healing. You can see that when you walk  
a few blocks from the new mall to the heart of downtown -- called 
``Downcity'' by the locals. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the big department stores that were once in Downcity have  
gone. There are a few clothing stores and a smattering of other 
commercial establishments. There is little life left in Downcity. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Downcity retailers worry about that imposing new presence  
up on the hill -- Providence Place mall. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could go two ways,'' says Roger L. Gross, co-owner of a  
Downcity men's clothing store. 
</P>
<P>
	The hordes of outsiders expected to visit the mall may also  
discover shops that are in the Downcity area, says Gross. 
</P>
<P>
	Or the mall could drain even more business away from Downcity,  
creating, in Gross' words, ``this giant sucking sound as people go 
over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Gross says gamely, ``I'm not afraid of competition.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
