<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Call for Milosevic's Ouster Repeated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Their spirits high after a  
successful rally in the capital, key opposition leaders said Friday 
the Serb people have shown they will settle for nothing less than 
the ouster of President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are two sides in Serbia today -- the regime and the  
people,'' said Zoran Djindjic, a key opponent of Milosevic. 
``Everybody will soon have to take one of the sides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Djindjic, a key leader of the umbrella opposition group, The  
Alliance for Change, spoke at a press conference a day after an 
estimated 150,000 people gathered at an opposition rally to demand 
Milosevic's ouster. 
</P>
<P>
	``The citizens of Serbia want the removal of Slobodan Milosevic  
and they do not want compromise or any deal with the government,'' 
said Vladan Batic, another Alliance leader. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alliance for Change leaders reiterated Friday that Milosevic  
has until mid-September to step down or he would face nationwide 
protests and a general strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbia's opposition remains fractured over how changes in the  
country should be carried out. The Alliance for Change and some 
other groups are demanding unconditional resignation by Milosevic 
and formation of a transitional government. 
</P>
<P>
	Vuk Draskovic, another key leader, however has agreed to an  
early election organized by Milosevic. But Draskovic was jeered 
when he proposed that idea at Thursday's rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Chanting slogans against Milosevic, the crowd at the rally  
roared in approval every time the opposition speakers called for 
his removal. It was the biggest outburst of popular anger against 
Milosevic in years, but the state-run media he controls portrayed 
the gathering as a ``failure,'' and as a ``disappointment'' to the 
organizers, who the media calls pro-NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, Belgrade students staged a mock celebration of  
Milosevic's 58th birthday. About 50 people watched as the student 
group lit candles on a huge cardboard cake and made a wish -- for 
Milosevic to step down as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	The birthday cake was sliced into pieces representing  
territories of the former Yugoslavia Milosevic lost in the four 
wars he has fought during his decade in power. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
