<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CBS, NCAA Discuss Hoops Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS and the NCAA are negotiating an extension of  
the agreement that gives the network broadcasting rights to the 
Division I basketball tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks are occurring amid increasing interest from several  
potential bidders who want to acquire the rights once CBS' 
eight-year, $1.73 billion contract expires in 2002. At least one 
CBS rival is willing to offer at least $4 billion over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wally Renfro, the NCAA's director of public relations, said the  
NCAA is currently negotiating exclusively with CBS for an 
extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been having discussions with CBS for some time and  
those discussions will continue,'' he said. ``We have the ability 
to talk to anybody, and we have not. Certainly what we do have is 
that we will not enter into any agreement until we have concluded 
negotiations with CBS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is trying to secure an extension in order to keep the rights  
off the open market. ABC/ESPN, Fox and ISL, which holds the TV and 
marketing rights to the men's and women's soccer World Cup, have 
expressed interest in the basketball rights. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS declined comment on the negotiations.  
</P>
<P>
	ISL vice president Jim Wheeler said his company would be  
prepared to offer $4 billion for 10 years to secure the rights for 
TV, the Internet, licensing, marketing and sponsorship. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where we're prepared to start,'' Wheeler said.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler contacted NCAA president Cedric Dempsey and expressed  
his desire to acquire the rights, although they have not discussed 
numbers, Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN/ABC boasts five networks that could be used to televise  
every tournament game throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``All along we have said we have interest in it,'' ESPN  
spokesman Mike Soltys said. ``Our belief is that basketball fans 
would benefit from seeing every game nationally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox, which has expressed interest in the past, declined comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Neal Pilson, the former president of CBS Sports who now heads  
the consulting firm Pilson Communications and is a consultant to 
ISL, said CBS' strategy is to wrap up an extension before others 
can bid on the rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I'm CBS, I want to get the deal done before it hits the  
open market,'' said Pilson, who made the original deal to bring the 
NCAA tournament to CBS in 1981. ``When I was with CBS, we did that 
several times, renegotiating the deal before it hit the open 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pilson also said that any contract would include more than just  
TV rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is happening now is that the marketing rights are being  
marketed along with the TV rights,'' he said. ``Television is 
combining with the marketing side to negotiate a single deal 
instead of two separate deals. That's what CBS is trying to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The marketing rights to the tournament are held by Host  
Communications, and Pilson said it's likely that CBS and Host would 
provide the NCAA with a combined offer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
