<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unfamiliar Names Top Speed Chart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- It's not business as usual two days into  
practice at the brand new Chicago Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The top of the speed chart after Friday's practice sessions for  
the inaugural Target Grand Prix does not include CART points leader 
Dario Franchitti or sensational rookie Juan Montoya or oval master 
Michael Andretti. 
</P>
<P>
	The new one-mile track in this urban suburb west of Chicago has  
shaken up the competitive open-wheel series, putting Helio 
Castro-Neves, Max Papis and ``Super Sub'' Roberto Moreno at the 
head of the line. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, speeds picked up considerably from Thursday's  
opening practice sessions, with Castro-Neves turning a lap of 
161.285 mph, followed by Papis at 161.229 and Moreno at 160.977. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like this track very much,'' said Castro-Neves, whose first  
and only career pole came earlier this season on the one-mile oval 
in Milwaukee. ``This is a different track than Milwaukee. The turns 
are not narrow, but they are tight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Papis, who hasn't been known for his oval racing prowess until  
recently, said, ``We've been working for a couple of days on the 
race pace and not worrying too much about speed. But my team is 
still confident from the U.S. 500.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian driver was referring to the race last month at  
Michigan Speedway, where he dominated on the two-mile oval only to 
run out of fuel on the last lap and watch Tony Kanaan win. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's funny that I've come from road racing and now I'm known  
for my oval performances, but this is a very nice oval,'' Papis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	One key characteristic of the new 1.029-mile CMC track is the  
tight turns that Castro-Neves talked about. Combined with CART's 
use of a big rear speedway wing on the cars, the configuration 
forces the drivers to brake hard heading into both turn one and 
turn three. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't carry as much speed into the turns and I think  
that's good,'' Papis said. ``I expect we will see a little more 
overtaking in the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moreno, who filled in for Mark Blundell earlier this season and  
is now subbing for injured Christian Fittipaldi, is 12th in the 
season points despite having no full-time ride and missing four of 
14 races. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to go from 180 to 130 miles an hour in the corners,''  
Moreno said. ``But that's OK. The track is very smooth and very 
wide, so it is just the way you have to drive it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite running hundreds of laps during the first two days, the  
only incidents have been harmless spins on Thursday by Richie Hearn 
and Michel Jourdain. 
</P>
<P>
	``The track is a challenge, but it seems like everybody really  
likes it,'' Papis said. ``For a new track, it really has very good 
grip. It's really surprising.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti, who leads Montoya by just one point in the season  
standings and is 28 ahead of third-place Andretti was 12th at 
158.552. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting better every session,'' Franchitti said. ``But we  
need to continue to work for a better balance. We need to keep up 
with the improving track conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andretti, Moreno's teammate, was frustrated through much of  
Friday's practice before finally moving up to 14th at 157.889. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually we adapt the car to the driver,'' Andretti said. ``For  
this race, we're going to have to adapt the driver to the car. This 
track suits a smooth driver rather than an aggressive one. I'm in 
the second category. But we're making progress with each lap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya, coming off his series-high fifth win of the season last  
Sunday in Lexington, Ohio, was the slowest of the points leaders. 
He was 15th at 157.815. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're disappointed the way the car's been handling,'' he said.  
``It's frustrating, but with a new track maybe we have to expect 
some problems before we can improve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More practice, as well as qualifying for Sunday's race is  
scheduled Saturday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
