<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racist Container Find Spurs Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORWALK, Conn. (AP) -- Two containers of medical waste were found  
at synagogues, marked with swastikas and references to last week's 
Jewish center shootings in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	One container was found Thursday morning in front of the  
Congregation Beth El in Norwalk, two days after a similar discovery 
at a temple in Stamford, about 15 miles away. Police in both cities 
said they believe the incidents are linked and have formed task 
forces with members of the FBI and U.S. Attorney's Office. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no words to describe the evil this represents,''  
Norwalk police Chief Harry Rilling said. 
</P>
<P>
	An employee of the 350-member Congregation Beth El the  
discovered the medical waste, including syringes, in the rear 
parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	A swastika was drawn on the container and police found a note  
that referred to Buford O. Furrow Jr., the white supremacist 
charged in the shooting of five people at the Jewish center in 
suburban Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow also allegedly shot and killed a Filipino-American postal  
worker after fleeing. When he surrendered to the FBI, Furrow 
reportedly said the community center shootings were meant to be ``a 
wake-up call to America to kill Jews.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hate,'' said Marvin Rosenbaum, president of Congregation  
Beth El. ``Los Angeles is 2,000-plus miles away ... but now it's no 
further away than walking out your front door.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, medical waste was found in a swastika-emblazoned  
container at Temple Beth El in Stamford. A picture of Furrow was 
taped to the container. 
</P>
<P>
	Stamford police said four additional containers of medical waste  
without anti-Semitic symbols have been found in recent months at 
two library branches, a school and a shopping center. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
