<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Official Linked to Prostitutes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The official who coordinated sexual violence  
awareness training for University of Minnesota athletes twice was 
cited for soliciting prostitution, police records show. 
</P>
<P>
	Rufus Simmons' most recent arrest came in June. His first  
offense was in 1991. Athletic director Mark Dienhart said Thursday 
he wasn't aware of either case until asked about them by the Star 
Tribune of Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would personally find it highly inappropriate to have a  
person with this type of a conviction in his background functioning 
in a program designed to provide our students with the information 
to make good choices in life,'' Dienhart said in a written 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The revelation comes less than two months after the school  
concluded an investigation into at least 40 cases of sexual 
misconduct or domestic assault by male athletes. The probe focused 
on whether administrators improperly were involved in decisions to 
prosecute in those cases. Investigators determined that there was a 
culture of insensitivity toward alleged victims and poor judgment 
by officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons, a university employee for 27 years, retired July 31  
from his job as associate men's athletic director. It is not clear 
whether the latest prostitution arrest played a role in the 
58-year-old's decision to retire. Simmons did not immediately 
return a phone call today from The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Minneapolis police records show that Simmons was arrested June  
15 after he exposed himself to a female undercover officer and 
offered her $20 for oral sex. Police taped the conversation. He is 
scheduled to appear in Hennepin County District Court on Aug. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 15, 1991, he was cited for the same offense. Court  
documents show that he pleaded guilty and paid $800 in fines and 
court costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, Simmons was in charge of various programs aimed at  
teaching male athletes to conduct themselves responsibly when 
interacting with women. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
