<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Royal Family Withdraws Dog Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A puppy abandoned at Heathrow Airport by an  
American couple won many hearts and, it appeared, a home with Abu 
Dhabi's ruling family. But the offer of a home was withdrawn when 
media interest got out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``All they wanted was the dog, not the press intrusion,''  
Heathrow spokesman Mark Pursey said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The American owners of Gucci, a young Maltese terrier, had been  
stopped by customs officials after arriving from Paris by train, 
Pursey said. All dogs entering Britain must undergo a six-month 
quarantine, although the Labor government has announced plans to 
relax the tough anti-rabies regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Gucci was placed in temporary quarantine while the unidentified  
couple took a two-week vacation in Britain and the three were 
supposed to return to New York together. But the couple never went 
back to the quarantine center to get the dog. 
</P>
<P>
	When contacted in New York by animal customs officers, the  
couple said they wanted the dog destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a member of the ruling family in the United Arab  
Emirates agreed to adopt Gucci, Pursey said. But the offer was 
followed by phone calls to Heathrow by reporters pretending to be 
members of the royal household and by calls to the family, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the family's offer was withdrawn, all is not lost.  
</P>
<P>
	Pursey said there have been hundreds of offers to adopt Gucci.  
</P>
<P>
	If the new owner is British, Gucci will have to spend six months  
in quarantine. But if the owner lives abroad in a country without a 
quarantine, she'll be able to go straight to her new home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
