<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China.com Gets Inadvertent Benefit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- An inadvertent stock sale helped Internet  
provider China.com generate a $1.9 million second-quarter profit 
despite a loss from its operations. 
</P>
<P>
	In reporting the results Friday, China.com boasted that sales  
are booming. Its U.S. shares shot up nearly 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of our operating numbers exceeded internal and external  
projections,'' said Peter Yip, China.com's chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue for the three months ended June 30 soared 174 percent to  
$2.4 million from $881,000 in the same period a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	China.com had an operating loss of $3.5 million in the quarter,  
compared with an operating loss of $2.0 million a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	But the gain on dealings in its own stock gave China.com a net  
profit of $1.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	China.com had intended to sell part of its 3 percent stake in  
the Internet advertising firm 24/7 Media Inc. in June, but brokers 
inadvertently sold the whole stake, said China.com's chief 
financial officer, David Kim. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock then plunged 20 percent over the next three days, and  
China.com bought back the shares it had wanted to keep, pocketing a 
surprise profit of $5.1 million, Kim said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It could have been just a hiccup in the market,'' Kim told The  
Associated Press. ``The sale was inadvertent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China.com recently listed on the Nasdaq Stock Market amid much  
criticism from analysts who said the name was far catchier than the 
track record of the Chinese-language Internet content provider 
partially controlled by China's Xinhua News Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a spotty track record, China.com attracted a flurry of  
investors when it went public in mid-July, becoming the first 
Chinese-language Internet company to list in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	On its debut, shares were offered at $20.00 and rallied nearly  
236 percent to $67.10. The early enthusiasm has waned, however. But 
it got a lift Friday with the release of the financial data. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's U.S. stock rose $3.50 to close at $35.50 a share  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In its report, the company said it wants to expand in Asia by  
acquiring four smaller Internet companies for less than $10 million 
each. It would not identify the targets. 
</P>
<P>
	China.com targets users in mainland China, Hong Kong, and  
Taiwan. But many surveys say China.com is only a minor player in 
the China market -- not even making the top 20 in some surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	Yip said it is doing better than that.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are much more than a China play. We still have a long way  
to go,'' said Yip. ``But we believe we are in the top 10.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China.com posted a $8.5 million loss in all of 1998 on revenue  
of $3.5 million, and analysts were apprehensive about control of 
its content, because of the company's connections with the 
government-run Xinhua. 
</P>
<P>
	Allegations that Xinhua was filtering out politically and  
morally sensitive material from China.com surfaced before the 
shares were sold on the Nasdaq, but Yip argued that Xinhua has been 
instrumental in expanding the company's operations in the mainland. 
</P>
<P>
	``We strongly believe that we must work with the government,  
particularly in China,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Apart from Xinhua, with a 10.9 percent stake in the company,  
other key shareholders are Hong Kong-based New World 
Infrastructure, with 18.2 percent; and U.S. Internet access 
provider America Online Inc., with 8 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
