<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Browns Set for Raucous Home Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Orlando Brown will never forget the ugly scene  
in the old Cleveland Stadium on Dec. 17, 1995, the last time the 
Browns played a home game. 
</P>
<P>
	After seeing bleachers and seats ripped up and tossed on the  
field, and batteries and fireworks thrown at the Cincinnati 
Bengals, Brown wanted to visit with some of Cleveland's fans who 
were about to lose their treasured football team to Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went down to the Dawg Pound at the end of the game,''  
Cleveland's mammoth offensive tackle said. ``I had always heard 
them calling my name, but I never had looked in their eyes. They 
were crying, man. That's when I realized how much people love their 
football here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When they take the field Saturday night in the new 72,000-seat  
Cleveland Browns Stadium, the expansion Browns will be welcomed 
like conquering heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	There's sure to be more tears in the stands, but these won't be  
tinged with sadness. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns will be home again.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland has been waiting nearly three years for Saturday  
night's home opener against the Minnesota Vikings. A giant clock in 
the downtown's Tower City Mall has been counting down the days 
until kickoff since the NFL announced in 1996 it would bring the 
Browns back for the 1999 season as an expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns' home opener will culminate a weeklong celebration,  
which included a stadium dedication, a parade through the city 
streets on Friday and a pep rally in Public Square which drew an 
estimated 40,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Kickoff was still 36 hours away, but Cleveland was carrying on  
like it was New Year's Eve. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans chanted, ``Here We Go Brownies, Here We Go, Woof, Woof!''  
as Mayor Michael R. White, instrumental in bringing pro football 
back, thanked Browns fans for their support. 
</P>
<P>
	White recalled that when the city was trying to convince the  
league to return the Browns, he was often asked: ``What does 
Cleveland want?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'We want our team, our name and our colors,'' he said.  
``And guess what Cleveland. We have our team. We have our name. We 
have our colors. We have our legacy, and a brand new stadium to 
boot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not even a planned rally by the Ku Klux Klan, which has stolen  
recent headlines and increased racial tension in the city, has been 
able to dampen Cleveland's enthusiasm about the Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Browns take the field in their traditional orange  
helmets Saturday night, fans may be too excited to care much about 
what is happening on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``This town is fired up,'' said cornerback Antonio Langham, who  
like Brown played for the Browns in '95. ``They've waited three 
years for this. Football is back, a new stadium, the whole nine. 
You might see more hitting in the Dawg Pound than you do on the 
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland coach Chris Palmer is hoping for a much better effort  
from his team than he got a week ago in Tampa Bay when the Browns 
(1-1) were awful in a 30-3 loss to the Buccaneers. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer will start rookie quarterback Tim Couch, the team's No. 1  
overall pick in the NFL draft against the Vikings (0-1). Couch, so 
impressive in his pro debut against the Dallas Cowboys in the Hall 
of Fame Game, was under siege most of the time last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Browns Set for Raucous Home Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Orlando Brown will never forget the ugly scene  
in the old Cleveland Stadium on Dec. 17, 1995, the last time the 
Browns played a home game. 
</P>
<P>
	After seeing bleachers and seats ripped up and tossed on the  
field, and batteries and fireworks thrown at the Cincinnati 
Bengals, Brown wanted to visit with some of Cleveland's fans who 
were about to lose their treasured football team to Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went down to the Dawg Pound at the end of the game,''  
Cleveland's mammoth offensive tackle said. ``I had always heard 
them calling my name, but I never had looked in their eyes. They 
were crying, man. That's when I realized how much people love their 
football here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When they take the field Saturday night in the new 72,000-seat  
Cleveland Browns Stadium, the expansion Browns will be welcomed 
like conquering heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	There's sure to be more tears in the stands, but these won't be  
tinged with sadness. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns will be home again.  
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland has been waiting nearly three years for Saturday  
