<DOCNO> APW19990820.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 22:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burnitz Returns to Milwaukee Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- All-Star outfielder Jeromy Burnitz returned to  
the Milwaukee Brewers' lineup Friday night after a month on the 
disabled list with a broken bone in his right hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz, hitting in the cleanup spot, went 0-for-2 with two  
walks as the Brewers lost 10-3 in the first game of a three-game 
series against the San Francisco Giants. He went on the disabled 
list July 18 after being hit by a pitch during a game against 
Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	``My bat felt quick when I swung, and I saw the ball great,''  
Burnitz said. ``(It was) way better than I expected, actually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz was hitting .273 with 26 home runs and 73 RBIs, both  
still team bests. He was the National League's player of the month 
for June, when he hit .317 with 12 homers and 31 RBIs, and he 
started in his first All-Star game in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Burnie's our lineup,'' interim manager Jim Lefebvre said.  
``He's like Barry Bonds is to the Giants and Mark McGwire is to the 
Cardinals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers, who were hovering near .500 when Burnitz went on  
the DL, went 11-19 during his absence and fell out of contention in 
the NL Central. Manager Phil Garner also was fired and GM Sal Bando 
was reassigned during that month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just his presence, I think, is going to help us,'' Lefebvre  
said. ``The toughest thing for him will be patience. Just don't try 
to hit a six-run homer. Just relax and play baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers tried several players in Burnitz's cleanup spot,  
with little success. On Friday night Milwaukee failed to hit a home 
run in its 11th straight game, the longest drought in franchise 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Outfielder Alex Ochoa, who is hitting .308 with four homers and  
13 RBIs since the All-Star break, fared the best. Ochoa moved to 
the fifth spot in the lineup with Burnitz's return. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any doubt that when one of your main  
guys goes down it adds pressure to the guys around you,'' Burnitz 
said. ``I think getting back in the lineup is going to take some 
pressure off some guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers briefly fell 10 games below .500 during their recent  
road trip, going 3-4. Friday's loss knocked them back to 10 games 
below .500. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 14:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Two Moroccans Stripped of Medals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Two Moroccan female athletes have been  
stripped of gold and bronze medals for using a muscle-building 
steroid in the first reported cases of doping at the Arab Games, an 
official said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Siham Hanifi will lose her gold in the women's 200 meters and  
Morocco will also have to give up another gold it won in the 
400-meter relay because Hanifi was part of the team, said Reda 
Kazem, the head of the Arab Games Doping Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	A second Moroccan, Karima Shaheen, will also lose the bronze  
medal for the women's discus throw, Kazem said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both athletes tested positive for Nandrolone, a muscle-building  
steroid that has been the cause of a rash of recent positive tests 
-- including several at the Pan American Games and even others 
announced this week in advance of the World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazem said only Shaheen's and Hanifi's samples tested positive  
among the 84 sent to an International Olympic Committee-accredited 
laboratory in the German city of Kreischa, near Leipzig. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to international figures, this is reasonable,'' Kazem  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We only tested athletes competing in the track and field  
events. No other tests have been conducted yet,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said most gold medal winners were tested. Suspicions about  
Hanifi were raised after she boosted her performance dramatically 
in the 200 meters, a day after losing badly in the 100 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	The track and field events were held Aug. 11-14 while the games  
formally opened on Aug. 15 for other events. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, 39-year-old Jamaican sprinter Merlene Ottey  
withdrew from the World Championships after testing positive for 
Nandrolone. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last month, Cuba's Javier Sotomayor, Britain's Linford  
Christie and American Dennis Mitchell have also seen their careers 
tarnished by positive tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazem said Hanifi and Shaheen have the right to appeal. The Arab  
Games' Steriods Committee does not have the jurisdiction to ban 
athletes. Bans imposed by international organizations range between 
two months and life. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the games' executive committee, Sari Hamdan,  
rejected accusations that the organizers were victimizing Moroccan 
athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't accuse athletes falsely and we don't accuse the  
country of working with steroids. We have 100 percent confidence in 
the tests and everything has been conducted according to the 
international rules and regulations,'' Hamdan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug testing was introduced in the Arab Games for the first time  
in 1997 when the championships were held in Beirut, Lebanon. Twelve 
athletes tested positive for banned substances during those games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990820.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 10:35:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Thought on TV Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A rock video that Marshall Herskovitz saw 15  
years ago still haunts him. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't even recall which band made it. ``I just remember the  
image: A group of people in a post-apocalyptic society tearing down 
walls. There was smoke and filth all around. Annihilation. 
Anarchy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	We might wonder why it left such an impression. TV has never  
shrunk from violent displays, and doesn't now, whether on MTV or a 
Fox newsmagazine, on ``NYPD Blue'' or pro wrestling's ``Monday 
Nitro Live!'' Violence is part of TV's stock in trade, including 
chopper-cam coverage of school shootings and workplace massacres. 
</P>
<P>
	So what's the big deal about some rock-video Armageddon?  
</P>
<P>
	Besides, who's Herskovitz to be beefing? He works in TV. He is  
one of Them. His latest series, produced with partner Edward Zwick, 
is ``Once and Again,'' which premieres on ABC in September. 
</P>
<P>
	No one, it's true, will mistake this new drama for a  
shoot-'em-up. Here, as with their ``thirtysomething'' a decade ago, 
Herskovitz and Zwick probe feelings and relationships. While a 
heart may be broken, a skull seldom is. 
</P>
<P>
	But that doesn't absolve them. They are part of TV, and TV,  
along with movies, music and video games, is (so to speak) under 
the gun. And Herskovitz knows it. 
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't have been surprised when a recent Senate Judiciary  
Committee report concluded that mass media dominate a child's life, 
and their ``exceedingly violent'' images lead to real-world 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	These findings jibe handily with the received wisdom from the  
past half-century: That TV, along with the rest of the media, is 
often harmful and should somehow be disciplined. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of us have long agreed. Then we witness recent horrors: the  
shootings at Colorado's Columbine High School, Mark Barton's bloody 
rampage in Atlanta and the siege at a Jewish community center in 
Los Angeles, to name just three. We feel a heightened urgency to 
put things right. 
</P>
<P>
	But as John Romano, co-executive producer of NBC's fall drama  
``Third Watch'' and thus another one of Them, wrote in a recent 
issue of Newsweek magazine, ``The more seriously we take the 
possible dangers of TV watching, and the possible need for 'tough' 
government intervention, the more important it is that we raise the 
IQ of the discussion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, such discussion has been contentious and  
inconclusive since Marshal Dillon blasted his first bad guy on 
``Gunsmoke.'' It has shown no recent uptick in intellectual rigor. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor much sign of common purpose. Hollywood cries censorship. The  
gun lobby screams about the right to bear arms. Moral crusaders 
want entertainment sanitized. Politicians want to court the 
greatest number of voters. In the midst of this deadlock, 
Herskovitz is speaking at a seminar at Manhattan's Museum of Radio 
and TV. The subject is TV violence, and despite being one of Them, 
he seems genuinely troubled by some of TV's messages. 
</P>
<P>
	Like that long-ago rock video. ``It was very well done, very  
powerful,'' he somberly recalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, he knew when he saw it there was more to the picture.  
</P>
<P>
	``I remember thinking, 'That was filmed on a sound stage, and  
all of these people arrived on time, and they were wearing 
costumes, and they got paid.''' 
</P>
<P>
	When lunch was announced, they must have lined up at the craft  
services table and heaped their paper plates. Then at the end of 
the day, someone called it a wrap and everyone went home. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is, they were locked in a cooperative venture to  
create an image of utter destruction and anarchy,'' Herskovitz 
says. However unintended, nonviolence lurked as the underlying 
moral of the video. 
</P>
<P>
	But who besides Herskovitz noticed?  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, `All the kids who watch it are just going to take  
this image of anarchy and, somehow, somewhere in their minds, it's 
going to click that THAT'S reality.''' 
</P>
<P>
	What haunts Herskovitz, and with good reason, is the irony that  
chaos can be systematically faked -- then taken as the real thing by 
its audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Herskovitz comes armed with no cure-all. But he does voice this  
modest proposal: ``A really strong structure of education and 
interpersonal connection,'' he says, might help kids see the truth 
outside the box called TV. 
</P>
<P>
	In our homes and in schools, we could promote a healthy balance  
in our kids' outlook. And we can resolve that, before we try to 
curtail TV's power, we will reassert ours as viewers. Then we might 
find that, whatever we're looking at on TV -- from rock videos to 
car commercials -- seeing isn't blindly believing. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, home remedies like these may not seem like much. But it  
sure beats what we're doing now: Just talking through the 
bloodshed, while we wait for a real conversation to begin. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`20/20': The recent shootings in a Los Angeles Jewish community  
center were a frightening reminder of the prejudice and intolerance 
that exists. Buford Furrow Jr., the reputed white supremacist who 
allegedly killed a postman and wounded five -- mostly children -- is 
said to have claimed his attack was ``a wake-up call to America to 
kill Jews.'' But did this hatred have roots in an earlier wave of 
extremist violence? ``20/20 Friday'' re-examines the evolution of 
one right-wing hate group called The Order, which mounted a reign 
of terror in the early 1980s. Meredith Vieira examines the 
conspiracy of hate, focusing on this group some called ``America's 
terrorists.'' It airs tonight at 10 p.m. EDT on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
