<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phelps Dodge Makes Bids for Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Phelps Dodge Corp. upped its bid Friday to $2.7  
billion to acquire Asarco Inc. and Cyprus Amax Minerals Co., two of 
the world's leading producers of copper and metals, a day after the 
two companies had publicly rejected its overtures. 
</P>
<P>
	Asarco and Cyprus had announced a $2.2 billion merger last month  
that would form the nation's largest copper company. Thursday, the 
boards of the two companies rejected a lower bid by Phelps Dodge 
worth about $2.56 billion while affirming their plans to go ahead 
with their own combination. 
</P>
<P>
	J. Clarence Morrison, senior vice president at Prudential  
Securities, Inc. said although Phelps Dodge's bid is reasonable, 
there's no certainty it will be able to aquire its two competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Asarco and Cyprus) feel and have always felt that their two  
companies have been undervalued for many years. Their interest is 
now in seeing that they get the best offer possible for the 
assets,'' Morrison said. 
</P>
<P>
	The unsolicited offers by Phelps Dodge, ranked No. 4 in the  
United States, come on the heels of a huge consolidation in the 
aluminum industry. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Reynolds Metals. Inc. agreed to a $4.4 billion  
acquisition by Alcoa Inc., while last week, Canadian aluminum giant 
Alcan Aluminium agreed to combine with European rivals French 
company Pechiney and Alusuisse-Lonza (Algroup) of Switzerland to 
form an aluminum giant called Alcan-Pechiney-Algroup. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge's bid for Asarco was worth about $960 million and  
its bid for Cyprus Amax was worth about $1.7 billion. The 
Phoenix-based company said neither offer was contigent on the 
success of the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Amax declined to comment, while Asaroc could not  
immediately be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge said the tax-free mergers with the New York-based  
Asarco and Englewood, Colo.-based Cyprus Amax, would create ``a 
large, resource-rich portfolio of lower-cost global copper assets'' 
and estimated worldwide copper production of the combined companies 
would reach 3.8 billion pounds annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge recently slashed its production by closing mines,  
smelters and refineries throughout the Southwest, laying off 
approximately 1,650 workers in Arizona, New Mexico and Texas. The 
company has suffered in the wake of dropping copper prices and 
lower copper sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of all three companies traded higher Friday on the New  
York Stock Exchange. Phelps Dodge closed up 56 1/4 cents to $59.12 1/2, 
Asarco closed up $4, or 22 percent, to $22.43 3/4, and Cyprus Amax 
closed up $2.87 1/2, or 20 percent, to $16.43 3/4. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
