<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Lieberthal Gets Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mike Lieberthal, who overcame a pelvic  
injury to become one of the best catchers in the National League, 
agreed Friday to a $19 million, three-year contract extension with 
the Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberthal missed the last two months of the 1998 season and  
wasn't sure if he'd be healthy enough to play when he showed up at 
spring training. His numbers -- .310 average, 25 homers, 78 RBIs -- 
and his first All-Star appearance provided the answer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This hopefully is the first of many long-term contracts,''  
Lieberthal said. ``I really wouldn't want to play anywhere else. 
This is a great chance for us to win for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest effort by the Phillies to show that they are  
committed to building a winner after entering the season with the 
fourth-lowest payroll in the National League. The Phillies signed 
first baseman Rico Brogna to a $4 million, one-year contract 
extension Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our No. 1 goal is to win here and be successful on the field  
for a long period of time,'' general manager Ed Wade said. ``Our 
second major goal is to retain the nucleus of this ballclub. To 
sign Rico Brogna to a one-year contract and to add Mike to the list 
of multiyear contracts, that certainly is a clear indication that 
we're committed to doing exactly what we said we were going to 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberthal, 27, is second to New York's Mike Piazza among NL  
catchers in homers and RBIs. He leads the league with a .999 
fielding percentage, having made one error in 106 games and 715 
chances. His 84-game errorless streak is the longest current streak 
in the majors among catchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberthal, who got a $1 million signing bonus, will make $4.5  
million next season, $6 million in 2001 and $7 million in 2002. The 
deal includes a $7.25 million club option for 2003 with a $500,000 
buyout. 
</P>
<P>
	With Lieberthal signed, the Phillies now focus their attention  
on right fielder Bobby Abreu, who was third in the league with a 
.340 average entering Friday night's game against the Dodgers. 
Abreu, who is eligible for salary arbitration after the season, did 
not agree to a multiyear deal in spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade said he spoke with Abreu's agents, Peter and Ed Greenberg,  
two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we'll get us to the finish line this time,'' Wade  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberthal was batting .256 with eight homers and 45 RBIs when  
he was placed on the disabled list last July 24. His mysterious 
injury was diagnosed as a ``stress reaction'' in the pelvic region. 
Whatever that was, it kept Lieberthal out for the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had an injury that really took six months to heal,''  
Lieberthal said. ``It was a long injury. When I came to spring 
training, I don't think I was 100 percent, but I was close. There 
were questions in my head about whether I'd ever be able to play 
the same, if this thing would ever heal. It took a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This summer, Lieberthal became the Phillies' ninth catcher to  
make the All-Star team and the first since Darren Daulton in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone from the media to Lieberthal's batterymate, Curt  
Schilling, has questioned the Phillies' commitment to winning. They 
have two winning seasons in the last 13 years and haven't made any 
significant free-agent signings in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	But even with young talent and a low payroll, a second winning  
season this decade is within reach. The Phillies were a season-high 
13 games above .500 two weeks ago and had a shot at making the 
playoffs until Schilling went on the disabled list with a sore 
shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year or the year before, I would probably look honestly  
at our team and say we're eight or nine players away from really 
competing with the Braves or the first-place clubs,'' Lieberthal 
said. ``Now I can honestly say that we're really close. We're a 
couple of pitchers away.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
