<P>
	Japanese Banks Announce Merger Plan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The deal struck by three Japanese lenders to form  
the world's biggest bank generated optimism Friday that similar 
alliances would follow, thinning the ranks of an overcrowded 
industry that has long lost its knack for turning a profit. But 
analysts approached the $1.2 trillion alliance cautiously, saying 
the marriage of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., the Industrial Bank of 
Japan Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. could founder if they fail to unload 
excess baggage. The merger will create a mammoth financial 
institution with complementary strengths -- investment banking for 
IBJ and retail banking for DKB and Fuji. 

</P>
<P>
	Chicago Exchange OKs Late Trading  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Stock Exchange on Friday approved  
after-hours trading for institutional and individual investors, the 
first exchange to do so. The nation's third largest stock market 
said it will add two extra hours of trading to thwart encroachment 
from electronic trading. Pending regulatory approval, it hopes to 
add the extra hours Oct. 1. The Chicago Stock Exchange's move comes 
as other exchanges across the country move to extend stock trading 
into the late evening and early hours. Both the Nasdaq Stock Market 
and the New York Stock Exchange are seeking to extend their hours. 

</P>
<P>
	First Union Hooks Up With Dell  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- First Union Corp. is encouraging its  
70,000 employees to buy personal computers so they can work at home 
and become more familiar with the company's online banking 
services. Offering $500 discounts on PCs made by Dell and loans at 
prime rate, or 8 percent, officials at the nation's sixth-largest 
bank believe the program will create a contented, more productive 
and computer-savvy work force. The bank has been making a strong 
push in online bill-paying, securities trading and other 
Internet-based products and services. First Union shares closed up 
1/8 at 42 11/16. Stock in Dell fell 5/8 to 43 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	US Airways Workers Get Union  
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- Ticket agents, gate workers and other  
service workers at US Airways have won the right to join the 
Communications Workers of America after a lengthy legal battle with 
the airline, union officials announced Friday. Of the 7,806 workers 
eligible to vote, 5,215 cast ballots in favor of the union, 
according to the National Mediation Board, which counted ballots. 
About 10,000 workers will be covered by the union, but only those 
working for US Airways in 1996 were eligible to vote. US Airways 
stock dropped 1 1/4 to 31 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA Wants To Fine Sears, Wal-Mart  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration is proposing  
fines against the nation's two largest retailers for allegedly 
violating hazardous materials regulations. Sears, Roebuck and Co. 
and Wal-Mart Stores are accused of shipping hazardous materials 
without using the proper packaging and inadequately labeling them. 
The FAA increased its number of hazardous material inspectors after 
110 people were killed in the May 1996 crash in the Everglades of a 
ValuJet airliner, a spokeswoman said. The crash was attributed to 
mislabeled oxygen canisters, which caused a fire. Shares in Sears 
shed 13/16 to 40 1/8. Stock in Wal-Mart gained 5/8 at 46 11/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Brazil's Currency Plunges Again  
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The Brazilian real skidded to a  
five-month low on Friday, pushed by uncertainty about 
deficit-cutting reforms and flagging investor confidence in South 
American markets. Brazil's currency was trading at 1.995 to the 
dollar at midday -- down 6 percent from a week ago -- before 
strengthening late in the day to 1.913. For Brazilians, the 
scramble to buy dollars was uncomfortably reminiscent of the panic 
that followed the 1997 crisis in southeast Asia and last year's 
turmoil in Russia. In January, Brazil was forced to devalue its 
currency and plunged into a recession from which it just now is 
emerging. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Sue MBNA for Sex Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity  
Commission has filed a civil rights lawsuit against MBNA Corp., 
alleging that the credit card company allowed a two-year pattern of 
sexual harassment against a woman by a male co-worker. The lawsuit 
charges the company violated the 1964 Civil Rights Act by not 
stopping the harassment. It seeks back pay, costs and damages which 
could reach more than $300,000. The government is asking the court 
to order MBNA to provide programs that ``eradicate the effects of 
its past and present unlawful employment practices.'' 

</P>
<P>
	NBC Might Buy Stake in Paxson  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is reportedly negotiating a deal to buy part  
of Paxson Communications Corp., which owns or operates 73 
television stations across the country. The talks focus on NBC 
buying 32 percent of Paxson, the Wall Street Journal reported 
Friday, citing unidentified sources. The move would be worth more 
than $300 million at current stock values. Last week, Paxson said 
it had hired Salomon Smith Barney to explore its options following 
a landmark Federal Communications Commission decision that allows a 
single company to own more than one TV station in a local market. 
Shares in General Electric Co., NBC's parent company, gained 1 5/16 
to 112 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Surplus on Track Despite Shortfall  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government recorded a budget  
deficit of $25.16 billion in July as money flowing into the 
Treasury slowed following an influx from quarterly income tax 
payments the month before. However, the government is still on 
track for posting a big surplus this year. The Treasury Department 
said Friday that last month's budget deficit of $25.16 billion was 
slightly higher than the $24.08 billion deficit reported in July 
1998. In July, government outlays totaled $147.07 billion, while 
receipts totaled $121.91 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	ABC Reporter To Give Back IPO Gains  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- ABC's medical correspondent is returning  
more than $50,000 to drkoop.com after violating insider-trading 
rules by selling shares in the healthcare Web site too soon after 
it went public, the company acknowledged. The husband of Dr. Nancy 
Snyderman, who serves as a director of the Internet site, bought 
1,650 shares of drkoop.com during a June 8 initial public offering 
for $9 and sold it one month later when prices soared to $41.27 a 
share. That was a violation of SEC rules barring corporate officers 
and directors or their spouses from profiting from a stock sale 
within six months of purchasing shares, drkoop.com said. 

</P>
