<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Criticizes Arms Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A senior Russian military official criticized the  
results of the latest Russian-U.S. arms reduction talks today, 
saying there were just too many differences remaining between 
Moscow and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no results,'' said Leonid Ivashov, the chief of the  
Defense Ministry's international cooperation department. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides concluded three days of consultations in Moscow on  
Thursday. Much of the talks focused on U.S. wishes to modify the 
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty so it can build a limited 
missile defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscow strongly opposes any changes, saying a missile defense  
system in the United States would upset the current strategic 
balance and could set off a new arms race. 
</P>
<P>
	``The very approach to the development of a national  
anti-missile system in the United States follows the American 
policy path,'' Ivashov said in remarks cited by the Interfax news 
agency. ``First, they take a decision, finance these projects, and 
then Russia is made to face facts on the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. proposal would involve a limited missile defense system  
meant to shoot down a single missile or a small number of them. 
Washington argues the system would not spoil the balance of power 
because it would not be effective against the kind of massive 
attack Russia is capable of launching. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivashov also accused the Americans of trying to link ABM treaty  
modifications to the future of the planned START III treaty. START 
III would cut nuclear warheads to between 2,000 and 2,500 per side. 
</P>
<P>
	At the second round of talks, expected in Washington in  
September, ``we expect a constructive approach from the United 
States, without pressure and linkages,'' Ivashov said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivashov also announced that Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev plans  
to meet with U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen soon to discuss 
the Kosovo situation. He said the meeting is likely to take place 
in September. 
</P>
<P>
	That announcement came as Ivashov and other officials were  
threatening to withdraw Russia's peacekeepers from Kosovo or change 
their role there if conditions become ``unacceptable.'' They did 
not elaborate but stressed that there were no such conditions 
present now, Russian news agencies reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has said the current international peacekeeping effort in  
the breakaway province is failing to stop ``ethnic cleansing'' of 
ethnic Serbs, Russia's historic allies and fellow Orthodox Slavs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States and NATO are trying to establish their own  
order in the Balkans, excluding the region's nations in the 
process,'' Ivashov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
