<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Ref Sentenced on Tax Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- An NBA referee has received two years' probation  
and a $5,000 fine for failing to pay taxes on the money he saved by 
``downgrading'' from first class on his league travel, U.S. 
Attorney Kate Pflaumer said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Roy Alexander of Tacoma pleaded guilty May 7 to a charge  
he had filed a false tax return for 1993. Alexander admitted to 
having a travel agency make up two itineraries for his travel in 
1993. The one he submitted with his official NBA expense forms 
showed him traveling by first class, when in fact he had downgraded 
his tickets and kept the money without reporting it as income, 
Pflaumer said in a release. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a collective-bargaining agreement with the National  
Association of Basketball Referees, the league was required to 
allow referees to travel in first class on trips longer than two 
hours. The agreement also allowed referees to downgrade their 
tickets to a lower class and keep the difference, ``a major 
employment inducement by which potential NBA referees were informed 
that they could supplement their salaries,'' the release said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a plea agreement, Alexander admitted he had known he was  
required to report the downgrade money as income. The NBA had taken 
several steps to ensure that referees were aware of the 
requirement, the U.S. Attorney's Office said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander is one of 15 NBA referees across the country who have  
been prosecuted on similar charges, the U.S. Attorney's Office 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
