<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Will Try LA Suspect First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The first trial for white supremacist Buford  
Furrow Jr. will be a federal case focusing on the killing of a 
Filipino-American mailman rather than a state prosecution for 
shootings at a Jewish community center. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury on Thursday charged Furrow, 37, with murder  
of a federal employee, which carries a potential death sentence. He 
also was charged with gun violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The mailman, Joseph Ileto, was gunned down Aug. 10, shortly  
after five people were wounded at the North Valley Jewish Community 
Center. Police said Furrow shot Ileto nine times because he was a 
nonwhite federal worker. 
</P>
<P>
	At the community center, Furrow fired 70 shots, wounding a  
68-year-old receptionist, a 16-year-old counselor and three boys, 
police charge. He reportedly scouted three Jewish institutions for 
places to kill Jews before settling on the community center. 
</P>
<P>
	He fled the shootings but surrendered in Las Vegas.  
</P>
<P>
	Months of hearings are likely on such issues as pretrial  
publicity, change of venue, use of Furrow's confession to the FBI 
and whether the death penalty will be sought. 
</P>
<P>
	If a mental defense is sought, complex pretrial litigation could  
delay the trial until next year. Furrow has a history of mental 
problems and has had ties to hate groups in the Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecution spokesman Thom Mrozek said prosecutors could  
return to the grand jury and seek a superseding indictment adding 
civil rights violations or hate crimes to the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``We acknowledge this is still an ongoing investigation and  
there is the possibility of additional charges including civil 
rights charges which include hate crimes charges,'' Mrozek said. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow's post-indictment arraignment is scheduled for Aug. 30.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
