<HEADLINE> Vikings' Thomas Pleads No Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CROWLEY, La. (AP) -- Minnesota Vikings defensive back Orlando  
Thomas has been put on probation for a year after pleading no 
contest to a simple battery charge stemming from an assault on his 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, who had a six-month jail term suspended under a plea  
agreement, also was ordered Thursday to pay fines and court costs 
of $601 by State District Judge Jules Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	He also must serve five days of home detention by Aug. 19, 2000,  
the judge ruled. Edwards, who also ordered Thomas to complete a 
domestic abuse and anger program, gave him credit for completing an 
NFL domestic abuse program. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas was arrested in April after his wife, Demetra, called the  
sheriff's office in Acadia Parish and said she had been assaulted. 
She was treated at a hospital and released. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas was born in Crowley, played high school football there  
and owns a home in the town, which is 140 miles west of New 
Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	After the hearing, Thomas returned to preseason training with  
the Vikings. 
  	   	
</P>
