<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milwaukee Signs Veteran Forward Reid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- General manager Ernie Grunfeld continued to  
retool the Milwaukee Bucks' roster Friday, signing free agent 
forward J.R. Reid to a three-year, $6.6 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid is the third veteran acquired by the Bucks in two days. On  
Thursday, Milwaukee traded forwards Chris Gatling and Armon Gilliam 
to Orlando for Danny Manning and Dale Ellis. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid's contract fits under the Bucks' salary cap because of the  
$2.2 million middle-class exception. Milwaukee has 14 players under 
contract for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Adding his size, aggressiveness and experience to that of our  
current players bolsters our front line,'' Grunfeld said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid, 31, finished last season with the Los Angeles Lakers,  
where he averaged 9.0 points and 5.2 rebounds. Reid was acquired by 
the Lakers from Charlotte last season in the five-player trade that 
sent Glen Rice to Los Angeles and Eddie Jones to the Hornets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucks are the fifth team for Reid, a former Olympian and the  
fifth overall pick in the 1989 draft. He also has played for San 
Antonio and New York, and he played the 1996-97 season in France. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've added another key player in J.R., who's not afraid to do  
the little things that make a basketball team successful,'' Bucks 
head coach George Karl said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucks have searched in vain for quality big men during the  
1990s, but the team now has six players who are 6-foot-10 or taller 
on its roster. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid's up-and-down career experienced a revival last season. His  
points and rebound averages were his highest since the 1992-93 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	He provided a physical presence and quality minutes, sometimes  
as a starter, for the Lakers late in the season and into the 
playoffs. The Bucks could use some of the same spark that Gatling 
was supposed to provide, but never did. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid became a physical leader for the Lakers during the playoffs  
when he outmuscled and outplayed Charles Barkley during their 
series win over the Houston Rockets. Reid also picked up a $10,000 
fine for knocking Scottie Pippen to the floor during the 
series-clinching win. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
