<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Sue MBNA for Sex Harassment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity  
Commission has filed a civil rights lawsuit against MBNA Corp., 
alleging that the credit card company allowed a two-year pattern of 
sexual harassment against a woman by a male co-worker. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed Thursday in U.S. District Court, charges the  
company violated the 1964 Civil Rights Act by not stopping the 
harassment. It seeks back pay, costs and damages which could reach 
more than $300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit claims that Maureen Harns, 33, of Newark, was forced to  
take a medical leave of absence when she suffered an emotional 
collapse in February 1997 from ``intolerable'' working conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Harns no longer works for MBNA. However, James Hogan, the  
co-worker named in the suit, continues to work for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is asking the court to order MBNA to provide  
programs that ``eradicate the effects of its past and present 
unlawful employment practices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said the company has a policy in place to combat  
sexual harassment, but did not follow it. 
</P>
<P>
	MBNA spokesman Brian Dalphon said the company would not comment  
on the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The EEOC said it filed the lawsuit after an investigation and  
failing to settle with the company on behalf of Harns. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second formal charge against MBNA in the past year  
by the federal government. In December, the Labor Department filed 
a complaint against MBNA alleging hiring discrimination against 
minorities who sought jobs as account representatives and 
telemarketers. 
</P>
<P>
	MBNA officials denied those charges at the time, claiming 24  
percent of new hires during the two-year review period of 1994 and 
1995 were minorities. That case is pending. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
