<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Eyes Improved N. Korea Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- North Korea's new willingness to negotiate  
about missile tests could provide a timely opening for improving 
relations, an Ohio congressman headed for a tour of the communist 
nation said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity is there. I see a lot of good signs,'' said  
Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall will make his fifth trip in five years to North Korea next  
week. As with the other visits, the trip will be primarily 
humanitarian. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said in an interview, however, that he also will use the  
opportunity to speak with officials in Pyongyang and tell them how 
important it is for them to abandon efforts to test a ballistic 
missile. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a firing ``would create tremendous problems'' for North  
Korea if it hopes to expand trade with the rest of the world, Hall 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, an official of the North Korean Foreign Ministry  
said his country is ready for negotiations over its reported plan 
to test-launch a long-range missile. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea created alarm last August when it launched a  
ballistic missile over Japan. Analysts have said the North Koreans 
were on the verge of testing a missile with an even greater range, 
one that theoretically could reach as far as Hawaii and Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan, South Korea and the United States have said North Korea  
would face economic and diplomatic penalties if it test-launches 
the missile. Hard hit by food shortages, Pyongyang gets aid from 
all three countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``We now have a golden opportunity to make some progress, and we  
should take advantage of it,'' Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall, an expert on hunger and poverty who has traveled widely in  
Africa and Asia, said food shortages are not as great a problem in 
North Korea as they were during his visit last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect to find things a little better,'' he said, but  
contaminated drinking water continues a huge problem as does the 
lack of adequate medicine or heat in the winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said his visit would include a trip to several remote,  
mountainous regions along North Korea's northern border with China. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be in the country Aug. 26-29.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
