<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 18:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Given a second chance, Bill Parcells took Rick Mirer.  
</P>
<P>
	The New York Jets, still seeking a backup quarterback, obtained  
Mirer from the Green Bay Packers on Friday for an undisclosed draft 
choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells, while with the New England Patriots, bypassed Mirer  
with the first pick in the 1993 draft and selected Drew Bledsoe. 
</P>
<P>
	Now as Jets' coach, Parcells has added Mirer into the battle for  
the job of backing up Vinny Testaverde. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer, who was drafted second in 1993 by Seattle, has never  
lived up to expectations, bouncing from the Seahawks to Chicago and 
then to Green Bay. His competition in New York will be Scott Zolak 
and Ray Lucas. 
</P>
<P>
	In six years, Mirer has completed 867 passes for 9,541 yards,  
with 41 touchdowns and 62 interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	After going to Green Bay last September, Mirer was the Packers'  
third quarterback for 12 games and then moved up to No. 2 when Doug 
Pederson was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Pederson left for Philadelphia as a free agent in the offseason,  
but the Packers felt Mirer was expendable because of the progress 
made by Matt Hasselbeck and rookie Aaron Brooks. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Broncos    	
</P>
<P>
	Strong safety Tyrone Braxton has decided to rest a strained calf  
muscle in his right leg and miss Denver's exhibition game against 
the Green Bay Packers on Monday in his hometown of Madison, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't just another game for me, but you don't want to  
risk further injury,'' Braxton said. ``They said that if I'm not 
100 percent, they won't let me go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Growing up, Braxton spent a lot of time on the Wisconsin campus  
and dreamed of playing in Camp Randall Stadium and then later 
having a career with the Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We used to sneak into the stadium and watch the Badgers  
play,'' Braxton said. ``I wanted to get a scholarship there, but 
was a little too small.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            *Cardinals    	
</P>
<P>
	Surgery is scheduled for Ernest Dye on Sunday to repair nerves  
damaged in a car accident that nearly severed his arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors feel confident that Dye's arm will remain viable. The  
offensive lineman has already undergone one operation to repair the 
bone and restore blood flow to his arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other players in the car at the time, Lester Holmes and Carl  
Simpson, received only minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Packers    	
</P>
<P>
	Right tackle Earl Dotson was back on the field after missing  
every practice this week because of a bulging disk in his back. 
</P>
<P>
	Dotson is not sure what his immediate future is, but hopes to  
play in Monday's exhibition game against the Denver Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a little sore,'' Dotson, a seventh-year player, said.  
``I'm going to try to work through it and aim for Monday night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive line coach Larry Beightol isn't sure if Dotson will  
see action in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't decided what we're going to do,'' Beightol said.  
``If the doctors give him the OK, then we'll play him some.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dotson took an injection Sunday after Saturday's exhibition  
opener and said he felt fine, but then woke up Monday with pain. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he tweaked his back in the offseason lifting weights and  
then aggravated it two days before an intrasquad scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've known it was there for two years. The fact that really  
scared me is when we did an MRI, it actually showed it was worse 
when I first did it. That got me antsy a little bit. After talking 
to our medical staff, they assured me they will try everything to 
get it better without having surgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Surgery, which is a last resort, would mean Dotson would miss  
four to six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Bengals    	
</P>
<P>
	Tremain Mack, who has had a series of alcohol-abuse arrests, has  
been suspended by the NFL and will not be allowed to play in the 
first four games of the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Paul Tagliabue also decided that the last four  
games the kick returner-defensive back missed last season, while in 
jail for drunken driving, will count as a suspension, which will 
cost him about $62,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension, which will complete an eight-game suspension for  
violating the league's substance abuse policy, begins Sept. 5, and 
runs through Oct. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the suspension without pay, the commissioner said  
Mack is responsible for paying a four-week fine based on his 1998 
salary for a previous violation of the policy. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	Ty Law, who had one year remaining on his contract, agreed to a  
six-year contract extension that makes him the second-highest paid 
cornerback in football behind Deion Sanders. Both the total package 
and the $14.2 million signing bonus are the biggest in franchise 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first name that you hear when people say cornerback is  
Deion Sanders. ... I would even say Deion Sanders,'' Law said after 
agreeing to a extension that could pay him $50 million over the 
next seven years. ``I want to be at that same level. When I retire, 
five years later I want to be inducted into the Hall of Fame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is structured so that it frees up about $450,000 in  
salary cap space this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Law, 25, the Patriots' first-round draft choice in 1995, led the  
team with nine interceptions last season and was named co-MVP in 
the Pro Bowl. He has 18 interceptions in four seasons, good for 
10th on the team's career list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
