<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Aug. 20, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Death Toll in Turkey Passes 9,000  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Rescuers pulled two children out of the  
rubble of Turkey's devastating earthquake today, while the 
government admitted that the lack of water and sweltering heat made 
chances of survival slim for the up to 35,000 people still believed 
trapped. People trapped in such situations usually die of 
dehydration after 72 hours -- a window that passed early today for 
Turkey's quake victims. The death toll surged to 9,082 dead, with 
about 34,000 injured. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Planes Strike Into Chechnya  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian warplanes today attacked  
Islamic rebels in the breakaway republic of Chechnya and raided 
villages held by the militants in neighboring Dagestan, the Defense 
Ministry said. The airstrikes on two villages inside Chechnya 
raises the prospect of widening the two-week-old conflict, which 
has so far been concentrated in several villages in Dagestan. It is 
Russia's most serious internal conflict since the 1994-96 war in 
Chechnya. 

</P>
<P>
	Storm Strengthens in Gulf of Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A tropical storm moving slowly northward  
through the Gulf of Mexico could strengthen into a hurricane by 
tonight, the U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami reports. 
Tropical Storm Bret was located about 230 miles southeast of 
Tampico this morning and moving northward about 7 mph with maximum 
sustained winds near 65 mph. A tropical storm warning was extended 
northward to the coastal town of La Pesca, 350 miles north of the 
Gulf port city of Veracruz. The center is advising Texans to keep 
an eye on the storm's weekend track. 

</P>
<P>
	Headers May Cause Mental Harm  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Adult soccer players appear to suffer a loss of  
some mental abilities over time, possibly from whacking the ball 
with their head, two researchers suggested today. Their study, 
outlined at the annual meeting of the American Psychological 
Association, bolsters a growing body of research pointing to 
possible mental harm from headers. But researchers caution that no 
study has conclusively demonstrated that headers -- as opposed to 
concussions from colliding with other players -- are to blame. It is 
also unknown if the impairment, as measured by psychological tests 
in such studies, translates into any real handicaps in everyday 
life. 

</P>
<P>
	Congress Talks Back Through E-Mail  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate members are increasingly  
using e-mail to take their message directly to voters, although no 
one seems inclined to ditch the taxpayer financed system of mail 
for lawmakers. Nevertheless, some offices now are sending hundreds 
of e-mail messages at a time. Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., e-mails 
his legislative schedule and an update on issues each Monday to 
about 5,000 constituents. Congress has been getting steadily more 
high-tech. No members had Web pages before the start of the 104th 
Congress in 1995, and now all but six do, a House spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Supreme Court CD-ROM Released  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supremes have a new greatest-hits  
collection, but this time the featured vocalists are Chief Justice 
William H. Rehnquist, the late Justice William J. Brennan and other 
current and past members of the nation's highest court. ``The 
Supreme Court's Greatest Hits'' is a CD-ROM compiled by a 
Northwestern University political science professor, with 
recordings of oral arguments in 50 major cases dating back to 1957, 
plus texts of the court's opinions and graphics showing how the 
justices voted. The court decided in 1993 to let anyone get copies 
of the argument recordings from the National Archives. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 123.79 in Late Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today, but investors were moving  
cautiously ahead of next week's Federal Reserve meeting and an 
expected increase in interest rates. Just before the close, the Dow 
Jones industrial average was up 123.79 at 11,087.63, building on 
earlier gains and wiping out yesterday's 27-point loss. On the 
NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,579-1,303. The Nasdaq was up 16.60 
at 2,638.03. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Wings, Lidstrom in 3-Year Deal  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Red Wings today announced a three-year deal  
with defenseman Nick Lidstrom, the All-Star who had been waffling 
about whether to play for the Wings or sign with a team in his 
native Sweden. Last season, Lidstrom had 14 goals and 43 assists in 
81 regular season games. He was the runner-up for the Norris 
Trophy, awarded to the best defenseman. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
