<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Perrot Will Always Be a Comet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It will get harder before it gets easier. Everybody who loved  
Kim Perrot understands that now. 
</P>
<P>
	But soon enough, family, friends and her Houston Comets  
teammates will remember what she stood for: that giving anything 
less than all of themselves would be cheating all the others. And 
then soldiering on will not seem quite as hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has lost a member of its family,'' backup center  
Tammy Jackson said Thursday night from the team's hotel in Los 
Angeles. ``Kim's faith and determination in life will constantly 
inspire us both as individuals and as a team. Her fire will always 
motivate us to not only win games but to enjoy life. 
</P>
<P>
	``No. 10,'' she added, ``will always be a member of the Houston  
Comets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perrot died Thursday afternoon of lung cancer, surrounded by  
family and friends, after six months of fighting the disease. The 
only reason anybody was surprised she lost was because Perrot beat 
everyone and everything else she took on. 
</P>
<P>
	There were tears at the WNBA's only game, Cleveland at New York,  
later in the evening. In Houston, Comets fans wore white ribbons 
and pink hearts with ``Kim'' inscribed on them to honor her at a 
game earlier this week. But in few places was the hurt more 
palpable than in the hotel rooms where Perrot's teammates prepared 
to go on without her. 
</P>
<P>
	The Comets were in Los Angeles preparing for tonight's game  
against the Sparks before moving on to play Sacramento on Saturday. 
Postponing the games was never an option. 
</P>
<P>
	``She would be kicking their tails if they didn't play,''  
Carroll Dawson, the club's executive vice president, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing will be tougher for some than others. And the moment you  
saw Cynthia Cooper struggling to hold herself together when the 
national anthem was played at the Comets game Monday night, you 
thought she was going to have the toughest time of all. Instead, 
she went out and dropped 42 points on Utah -- two shy of her 
career-high -- in an 80-71 win. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of those sad-turned-wonderful nights when the games  
seem like the heavy business of life, instead of the other way 
around. Cooper knew she was about to lose a close friend and 
running mate and somebody was going to pay. The redeeming part is 
that the somebody was just a basketball team. And when she was 
done, Cooper ran into the embrace of her own team, exhausted and 
sobbing. 
</P>
<P>
	It was like that the first few nights for Bo Kimble after he  
lost his friend and sidekick, Hank Gathers. On a Sunday night in 
March, 1990, in the middle of a game, Gathers collapsed on the 
court within shouting distance of his mother and aunt in the 
stands. Moments later, his heart gave out on him. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the Comets, Gathers' Loyola Marymount teammates decided to  
keep playing, if only to dedicate their effort to Gathers. They 
accepted an NCAA bid awarded the team when the conference 
tournament was canceled and immediately took off on one of the 
greatest runs the college postseason has ever seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Like a comet, Marymount was kept aloft by a high-octane mix of  
anger, grief and nervous energy in the wake of Gathers' sudden 
death. In successive games, Kimble and a supporting cast of 
overachievers zoomed past New Mexico State, Michigan and Alabama 
before crashing back to earth in a loss to eventual national 
champion UNLV. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning a championship for Perrot won't be as daunting a mission  
for Cooper &AMP; Co. -- at least the playing part. Cooper has been the 
leading scorer and league MVP in the two seasons completed so far, 
the reason why the Comets are the WNBA's two-time defending 
champions. 
</P>
<P>
	In a way, Perrot was her Gathers and Houston's catalyst, a  
tenacious defender who could score as well as set up others. 
Replacing her points and assists won't be the hard part; replacing 
her spirit will. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very tough on them,'' coach Van Chancellor said,  
``because they just lost Kim. She was such a vital part of this 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the friends Kim Perrot left behind will remember  
that she willed them the desire to keep playing, not a set of 
instructions on how it was to be done. Then each of them will have 
to take the lessons she taught them and figure that out for 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	And with the passage of time, they will discover what Bo Kimble  
did: that the hole the death of a friend or a family member leaves 
in your heart doesn't stay empty forever. 
</P>
<P>
	``A day doesn't go by that something doesn't happen that reminds  
me of Hank,'' Kimble said a few years after Gathers' death. ``The 
difference is that not a lot of it is painful anymore. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
