<HEADLINE> Sen. Thurmond OK After Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Sen. Strom Thurmond was hospitalized  
briefly Friday after he became dizzy and collapsed at a university 
reception. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurmond, 96, told reporters gathered outside Palmetto Baptist  
Medical Center in Columbia that he felt good. 
</P>
<P>
	But he appeared unsteady on his feet as he walked to his car  
about 6:25 p.m., two hours after he was brought to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurmond was admitted after collapsing at a reception for a  
federal magistrate at the University of South Carolina, Thurmond 
spokesman John DeCrosta said. The South Carolina Republican never 
lost consciousness, DeCrosta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurmond was expected to attend a wedding Saturday in  
Charleston, said state Sen. John Courson, a friend of Thurmond's. 
</P>
<P>
	First elected to the Senate in 1954, Thurmond became the oldest  
person to serve in the Senate at age 93. At age 94 he became the 
longest-serving senator ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurmond has been hospitalized briefly several times in recent  
years, including for a day in Washington after he became dizzy 
during a Promise Keepers rally in October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	That December, Thurmond spent several days in a military  
hospital for a respiratory infection and earlier that year he spent 
several days at a hospital in Washington recovering from the flu. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
