<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burnitz Returns to Milwaukee Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- All-Star outfielder Jeromy Burnitz returned to  
the Milwaukee Brewers' lineup Friday night after a month on the 
disabled list with a broken bone in his right hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz was hitting in the cleanup spot as the Brewers opened a  
three-game series against the San Francisco Giants. He went on the 
disabled list July 18 after being hit by a pitch during a game 
against Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnitz is hitting .273 with 26 home runs and 73 RBIs both still  
team bests. He was the National League's player of the month for 
June, when he hit .317 with 12 homers and 31 RBI, and he started in 
his first All-Star game in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Burnie's our lineup,'' interim manager Jim Lefebvre said.  
``He's like Barry Bonds is to the Giants and Mark McGwire is to the 
Cardinals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers, who were hovering near .500 when Burnitz went on  
the DL, went 11-19 during his absence and fell out of contention in 
the NL Central. Manager Phil Garner also was fired and GM Sal Bando 
was reassigned during that month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just his presence, I think, is going to help us,'' Lefebvre  
said. ``The toughest thing for him will be patience. Just don't try 
to hit a six-run homer. Just relax and play baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers tried several players in Burnitz's cleanup spot,  
with little success. 
</P>
<P>
	Outfielder Alex Ochoa, who is hitting .308 with four homers and  
13 RBI since the All-Star break, fared the best. Ochoa moved to the 
fifth spot in the lineup with Burnitz's return. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was hurt, I realized what I take the most pride in is  
playing everyday,'' Burnitz said Friday after batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brewers briefly fell 10 games below .500 during their recent  
road trip, going 3-4. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
