<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-20 02:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Florida Shelters Unsafe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Many of Florida's public hurricane shelters would  
be unsafe in a major storm the size of Hurricane Andrew, according 
to inspectors who say many structures aren't sturdy enough or are 
located in flood plains. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Division of Emergency Management surveyed 800 of  
Florida's 3,000 shelters and found 95 percent of the buildings 
could suffer significant damage in a particularly strong hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	For weaker storms -- Category 1 or 2 hurricanes -- most Florida  
shelters are adequate, said Danny Kilcollins, an engineer with the 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	But after studying damage from more powerful storms -- including  
Hurricane Andrew in 1992 and Hurricane Hugo in 1989, engineers 
learned a lot about what kinds of buildings can withstand winds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even in a compliant structure, we can't absolutely guarantee  
safety,'' Kilcollins said this week. ``But we've tried to identify 
buildings that clearly have features that perform well during 
hurricanes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many Florida shelters are older school buildings, made with  
unreinforced masonry. Steel-reinforced block is rare in buildings 
constructed before the 1990s. In southwestern Florida, many 
shelters also are in flood zones. 
</P>
<P>
	The study has been going on for about five years, and Kilcollins  
said it is likely to continue for at least another three years. The 
draft report released to county officials this week covers 21 of 
the state's 67 counties. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Miami area, where many buildings have been rebuilt since  
Hurricane Andrew, 44 of 62 shelters fell below the recommended 
guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like two days before Halloween, saying someone has a book  
on the Internet on how to poison candy,'' complained Bill Johnson, 
assistant director of the Miami-Dade Office of Emergency 
Management. ``I don't know where anyone is getting the information 
that my schools have failed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Loftus, a spokesman for the state Division of Emergency  
Management, said criteria for a safe shelter were set high by 
inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a perfect world, all our shelters would have generators and  
catered dinners,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some shelters didn't meet the criteria because engineering plans  
for the buildings were unavailable to inspectors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
