<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conn. Probes Hate Messages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Two plastic containers of medical waste  
marked with swastikas and references to the Jewish center shootings 
in Los Angeles were found outside two synagogues. 
</P>
<P>
	One container was found Thursday in front of the Congregation  
Beth El in Norwalk, two days after a similar discovery at a temple 
in Stamford, about 15 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in both cities said they believe the incidents are linked  
and have formed task forces with the FBI and U.S. Attorney's 
Office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was an attempt to frighten the congregation and to  
frighten Jews generally, not just here,'' said Rabbi Joshua 
Hammerman of Temple Beth El in Stamford. 
</P>
<P>
	Taped to one of the containers was a newspaper picture of Buford  
O. Furrow Jr., a white supremacist charged in last week's shooting 
of five people at a Jewish community center outside Los Angeles. 
The other had Furrow's name written on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow also allegedly shot and killed a Filipino-American postal  
worker. When he surrendered, Furrow reportedly said the shootings 
were meant to be ``a wake-up call to America to kill Jews.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no words to describe the evil this represents,''  
Norwalk police Chief Harry Rilling told The Advocate. 
</P>
<P>
	Stamford police said four additional containers of medical waste  
without anti-Semitic symbols have been found since December 1998 at 
two library branches, a school and a shopping center. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
