<HEADLINE> Ex-Cop Killed After Taking Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photo LR102    	
</P>
<P>
	BRYANT, Ark. (AP) -- A former Texas policeman wanted for a  
federal parole violation and suspected in a car-theft ring was shot 
to death after taking two hostages. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect's two sons fled during the shooting and were later  
caught. 
</P>
<P>
	James B. Frye, a former Orange, Texas, policeman, was killed  
Friday after he refused to go along with marshals who tried to 
arrest him on a warrant for charges in Texas and Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	The marshals had been waiting for Frye, 36, to arrive at a  
storage facility. He did, but when confronted ran into Middleton 
Heat and Air and took two women hostage at knifepoint. Neither was 
injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just kept telling him to get his hands up and he kept  
bringing his hands down,'' said Mike Ackerman, an auto repairman 
who works at a shop nearby. ``I was telling everybody here that he 
looked like he was fixing to run, and he dropped his hands and 
ran.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shop's general manager was hit by a ricocheting bullet but  
not seriously hurt. Frye's sons Derrick, 16, and Damon, 15, were 
caught in a wooded area shortly afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	Frye had been a parole officer and also worked as a detective  
during seven years with the Orange police department, Chief Sam 
Kittrell said. Orange is a city of 20,000 about 100 miles east of 
Houston. He left the department in October 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Frye served two years in a Texas prison for stealing and  
transporting tractors across state lines, Chief Deputy U.S. Marshal 
Brian Murray said. He was wanted in Texas for a parole violation 
and also was wanted in Louisiana for possessing stolen vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant is on Interstate 30 about five miles southwest of Little  
Rock. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
