<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Surplus on Track Despite Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government recorded a budget  
deficit of $25.16 billion in July as money flowing into the 
Treasury slowed following an influx from quarterly income tax 
payments the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the government is still on track for posting a big  
surplus this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department said Friday that last month's budget  
deficit of $25.16 billion was slightly higher than the $24.08 
billion deficit reported in July 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, government outlays totaled $147.07 billion, while  
receipts totaled $121.91 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Government receipts from individual income tax payments in July  
came to $59.98 billion, following $92.99 billion the month before. 
And corporate income tax payments totaled just $3.4 billion, 
compared with $39.26 billion in June. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first 10 months of fiscal 1999, which began Oct. 1,  
1998, the government posted a surplus totaling $69.11 billion, up 
from the $42.98 billion surplus for the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am pleased to announce that we are on track to reach the  
largest annual budget surplus ever,'' President Clinton said in a 
statement. ``Thanks to solid fiscal discipline, the surplus at this 
point in the fiscal year is $69.1 billion -- the largest in history 
over a comparable period and more than $20 billion over last year's 
level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, in its midyear economic forecast,  
projected that the surplus, which totaled $69.2 billion in 1998, 
will climb to $98.8 billion in the current fiscal year, which ends 
Sept. 30, and $142.5 billion in 2000. Congressional accountants are 
predicting a surplus of about $120 billion for all of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the government enjoyed its first budget surplus since  
1969. Assuming administration projections for this year come 
through, this will be the first back-to-back surpluses since Dwight 
Eisenhower was president in 1956 and 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	The June surplus of $53.57 billion was not revised by the  
government, the Treasury Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also used the opportunity to renew his opposition to  
Republican plans for a big tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tax bill passed by Congress would reverse the achievement  
of fiscal discipline that has been so critical in making the 
American economy the strongest it has been in generations,'' 
Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
