<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Charged for Scaling Sears Tower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A French daredevil known as ``Spiderman'' was  
arrested Friday on top of the Sears Tower after climbing the 
110-story building without the aid of suction cups or a safety net. 
</P>
<P>
	Alain Robert, 37, of Pezenas, France, was met on the roof by  
officers who handcuffed him and charged him with criminal trespass 
and failure to use a safety device while operating an aerial show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now I'm very happy because I got on top of the Sears  
Tower,'' Robert said. ``So it was a very big adventure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1 1/2-hour climb created a spectacle on Wacker Drive, a busy  
downtown thoroughfare. Traffic backed up and TV station helicopters 
hovered to show the stunt live on morning news programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Chalk dust helped Robert keep his grip as he worked his way up a  
seam in the building, but condensation in the low-level clouds 
shrouding the top was an unwelcome surprise. His grip faltered, but 
he was able to recover, said Isabel Hardy, Robert's manager. 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney, George Andrews, said he hopes the charges will be  
dismissed once the judge considers Robert's courage and the 
``impressiveness of the feat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardy said Robert would return to France to be with his wife and  
three children until his Oct. 13 court date. He could face up to a 
year in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert works full-time as professional climber, scaling  
buildings as publicity for his sponsor, the French shampoo company 
Norgil. He has climbed more than 30 skyscrapers, including the 
Empire State Building in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sears Tower held the ``world's tallest'' title until 1996  
when the 1,483-foot Petronas Twin Towers skyscraper in Kuala 
Lumpur, Malaysia, was ruled taller. Robert tried to climb the 
towers in 1997, but building managers said the exterior fittings 
couldn't support the weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert's effort marks the second time the Sears Tower has been  
conquered by a daredevil. 
</P>
<P>
	On Memorial Day 1981, Dan Goodwin, a Las Vegas stuntman who went  
by the name ``Spider Dan,'' climbed the building using three huge 
glass carrier suction cups. He was convicted of disorderly conduct 
and fined $35. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
